{"title_page": "2nd Chapter of Acts", "text_new": "{{Third-party|date=April 2020}}\n{{about|the musical group|the Bible book chapter|Acts 2}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = 2nd Chapter of Acts\n| image           = 2nd-Chapter-of-Acts.jpg\n| caption         = 2nd Chapter of Acts, c. 1985\n| image_size      = 280\n| background      = group_or_band\n| origin          = [[California]], U.S.\n| genre           = [[Contemporary Christian music|Contemporary Christian]], [[Jesus music]]\n| years_active    = 1973\u20131988\n| label           = [[Myrrh Records|Myrrh]], [[Sparrow Records|Sparrow]], Live Oak\n| associated_acts = [[Barry McGuire]], [[Phil Keaggy]], [[Michael Omartian|Michael]] and [[Stormie Omartian]]\n| website         = {{url|http://www.2ndchapterofacts.com/}}\n| past_members    =\n\n* [[Annie Herring]]\n* [[Nelly Greisen]]\n* [[Matthew Ward (singer)|Matthew Ward]]\n\n}}\n\nThe '''2nd Chapter of Acts''' was a [[Jesus music]] and early [[contemporary Christian music]] group composed of sisters [[Annie Herring]] and [[Nelly Greisen]] and brother [[Matthew Ward (singer)|Matthew Ward]]. They began performing in 1973 and enjoyed their period of greatest success during the 1970s. The group disbanded in 1988.\n\n== History ==\n\nThe 2nd Chapter of Acts began as a result of the trio singing at home together as Annie played the piano. Following the death of their parents (Elizabeth in 1968 and Walter Ward in 1970),<ref>Booklet included with compilation ''20'' (1992), chapter \"Simple Faith\", section \"Trouble at Home\".</ref> Nelly and Matthew, still [[minor (law)|minors]], moved in with their older sister, Annie, and her husband, recording engineer and producer, Buck Herring.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.matthewward.com/bio_past.shtml|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040610191228/http://www.matthewward.com/bio_past.shtml|url-status=dead|title=Matthew Ward Biography: 2nd Chapter of Acts|archivedate=Jun 10, 2004|accessdate=Apr 6, 2020}}</ref> Annie was a self-taught singer and songwriter who composed and played her songs around the family piano.  Her brother and sister would often join in as she played, and eventually they developed extremely tight and intricate harmonies.<ref name=\"EofCCM\">{{cite book |last=Powell |first=Mark Allan |title=Encyclopedia of Contemporary Christian Music |publisher=Hendrickson Publishers |year=2002 |location=Peabody, Massachusetts |isbn=1-56563-679-1 |page=801 |quote=\"2nd Chaper was better than any of those groups--they had a more consistent songeriter, stronger vocals and, especially, tighter harmonies\" }}</ref><ref name=\"2ndchapterofacts.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.2ndchapterofacts.com/articles/frame-picture.htm |title=The Frame Never Outdid the Picture: The 2nd Chapter of Acts Story |publisher=2ndchapterofacts.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-29}}{{Dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThey started singing for local coffee houses and small gatherings, then gained the notice of [[Pat Boone]] who arranged a contract to record and release two singles with MGM, \"Jesus Is\" (1972) and \"I'm So Happy\" (1973). The fledgling trio also came to the attention of 1960s folk singer [[Barry McGuire]], who had recently become a Christian and was preparing to record his first Christian music album, produced by Buck Herring. The siblings provided background vocals for ''Seeds'' and McGuire's 1974 follow-up ''Lighten Up''.\n\nThe trio released their debut album, ''[[With Footnotes]]'', in 1974. This album featured \"[[Easter Song]]\" which would become a signature piece for the group and has been recorded by many other artists since. This was followed up with ''[[In the Volume of the Book]]'' in 1975, the year that also saw the release of a live album with Barry McGuire, ''[[To the Bride]]'', which included \"[[a band called David]]\", who supported 2nd Chapter of Acts on tour. 2nd Chapter of Acts' first three releases were issued by [[Myrrh Records]], and the group toured with McGuire intermittently for three years.\n\nThe group went on a touring hiatus in 1976. Annie released her first solo record on the [[Sparrow Records]] label founded that year by the executive who had signed them to the Myrrh label, [[Billy Ray Hearn]]. For the summer of 1977, they were joined on an 18-city tour by [[Phil Keaggy]] and the result was the live triple album, ''[[How the West Was One (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|How the West Was One]]''. Their contract with Myrrh fulfilled, they moved as a group to Sparrow.<ref name=\"2ndchapterofacts.com\"/>\n\nTheir Sparrow debut, ''[[Mansion Builder]]'' (1978) was followed up with ''[[The Roar of Love]]'' (1980) (a concept album inspired by [[C. S. Lewis]]' ''[[The Lion, the Witch, and the Wardrobe]]''), ''[[Rejoice (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Rejoice]]'' (1981), ''[[Singer Sower]]'' (1983), and ''[[Together Live]]'' (1983) (with [[Michael Omartian|Michael]] and [[Stormie Omartian]]).  2nd Chapter moved to their own Live Oak label with the release of ''[[Night Light (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Night Light]]'' in 1985, and their final recording of original material, ''[[Far Away Places (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Faraway Places]]'' in 1987.\n\nTheir voices can be heard among other Christian artists on two benefit singles in 1985.  ''Do Something Now!'' credited to ''The Cause'' on [[Sparrow Records]] to aid famine relief in Africa and ''Fight the Fight, Rescue the Unborn'' which featured over 100 Christian artists, to benefit the Christian Pro-Life Movement, released on Live Oak.\n\n2nd Chapter of Acts broadened their appeal with the release of [[Hymns (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Hymns]] and [[Hymns 2]], reaching audiences with more traditional music. ''Hymns'' proved to be their best-selling release, receiving a [[Dove Award]] for \"Best Praise and Worship Album of the Year\" in 1987.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doveawards.com/history.php?x=artist |title=Dove Award History Artist |publisher=Doveawards.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120605031050/http://www.doveawards.com/history.php?x=artist |archivedate=2012-06-05 }}</ref>\n\nExcept for two sabbatical years in 1976 and 1983, 2nd Chapter of Acts continued to tour until 1988. Their final concert was in Houston, Texas on August 12 of that year.<ref name=\"2ndchapterofacts.com\"/>\n\n2nd Chapter was recognized by the Gospel Music Association in 1999 by their induction into its [[Gospel Music Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gmahalloffame.org/site/?page_id=84 |title=Gospel Music Hall of Fame: Year of 1999 |publisher=Gmahalloffame.org |accessdate=2011-11-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929144220/http://www.gmahalloffame.org/site/?page_id=84 |archive-date=2011-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAnnie and Matthew also recorded several solo projects during the 2nd Chapter of Acts years. Both have continued to release new material and perform concerts as of 2011.\n\n== Roles of group members ==\n\nAnnie was the main songwriter of the group and the only one who played an instrument (piano). Her admittedly unschooled compositional style, with its frequent irregular rhythms, added somewhat progressive rock-like elements to what was otherwise a soft-rock sound. Matthew and Nelly initially made the occasional small contribution to the lyrics, and Matthew developed as a songwriter for the group as his solo career grew.\n\nAnnie and Matthew sang most of the solo parts. Nelly \u2014 whose voice could be hard to distinguish from Annie's \u2014 usually sang lead only on songs where each member took a verse (\"Which Way The Wind Blows\", \"Something Tells Me\", \"Takin' The Easy Way\") or on solo pieces without the others singing backup (\"I Don't Wanna Go Home\", \"Make My Life a Prayer\" and \"Mountain Tops\"). Vocal leads such as in \"My Jesus I Love Thee\" and \"Sing Over Me\", where she was backed by the others, were rare exceptions. Her voice was considered the \"glue\" to the 2nd Chapter of Acts sound, and her harmony parts were generally the most difficult to sing.\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Albums ===\n\n* 1974: ''[[With Footnotes]]''  (Myrrh)\n* 1975: ''[[In the Volume of the Book]]'' (Myrrh)\n* 1975: ''[[To the Bride]]'' (two LPs; with Barry McGuire and \"a band called David\") (Myrrh). Most of this is by McGuire. The 2nd Chapter's section \u2014 one side plus two songs \u2014 consists mostly of songs they never released anywhere else.\n* 1976: ''Firewind'' (a \"dramatic musical\" based on Acts chapters 1-4) featuring Barry McGuire, Anne Herring, Terry Talbot, John Talbot, Nelly Ward, Keith Green and Matthew Ward, with narration by David Young (Sparrow SPR 1004) \n* 1977: ''[[How the West Was One (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|How the West Was One]]'' (Three LPs; with Phil Keaggy and \"a band called David\") (Myrrh). Half of this was by 2nd Chapter, half by Phil Keaggy. It was later reissued on two CDs.\n* 1978: ''[[Mansion Builder]]'' ([[Sparrow Records]])\n* 1980: ''[[The Roar of Love]]'' (Sparrow)\n* 1981: ''[[Rejoice (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Rejoice]]'' (Sparrow)\n* 1983: ''[[Singer Sower]]'' (Sparrow)\n* 1983: ''[[Together Live]]'' (Two LPs; with Michael and Stormie Omartian) (Sparrow). One side plus one song was by the Omartians; the rest was by 2nd Chapter. It includes one 2nd Chapter song that was never released anywhere else. This is the only 2nd Chapter album that has never been released on CD.\n* 1985: ''[[Night Light (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Night Light]]'' (Sparrow)\n* 1986: ''[[Hymns (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Hymns]]'' (Sparrow)\n* 1987: ''[[Far Away Places (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Far Away Places]]'' (Sparrow)\n* 1988: ''[[Hymns II (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Hymns II]]'' (Sparrow)\n* 1989: ''[[Hymns Instrumental]]'' (Sparrow)\n\n=== Compilations ===\n\n* 1981: ''[[Encores (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Encores]]'' (Myrrh)\n* 1992: ''[[20 (CD album)|20]]'' (Navarre) [includes a few unreleased songs] ''Issued on two CDs or two cassettes.''\n* 2006: ''[[Very Best of 2nd Chapter of Acts]]''\n\n=== Video ===\n\n* 1983: ''[[Together Live]]'' [with [[Michael Omartian|Michael]] and [[Stormie Omartian]]] (Sparrow)\n* 1998: ''[[First Love: a Historic Gathering of Jesus Music Pioneers|First Love]]''  Various Artists\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Official website|http://www.2ndchapterofacts.com}}\n* [http://www.musicmoz.org/Bands_and_Artists/2/2nd_Chapter_of_Acts/ Musicmoz:2nd Chapter of Acts]\n\n{{2nd Chapter of Acts}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2nd Chapter of Acts}}\n[[Category:1973 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:1988 disestablishments in California]]\n[[Category:Christian rock groups from California]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1988]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1973]]\n[[Category:Family musical groups]]\n", "text_old": "{{Third-party|date=April 2020}}\n{{about|the musical group|the Bible book chapter|Acts 2}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name            = 2nd Chapter of Acts\n| image           = 2nd-Chapter-of-Acts.jpg\n| caption         = 2nd Chapter of Acts, c. 1985\n| image_size      = 280\n| background      = group_or_band\n| origin          = [[California]], U.S.\n| genre           = [[Contemporary Christian music|Contemporary Christian]], [[Jesus music]]\n| years_active    = 1973\u20131988\n| label           = [[Myrrh Records|Myrrh]], [[Sparrow Records|Sparrow]], Live Oak\n| associated_acts = [[Barry McGuire]], [[Phil Keaggy]], [[Michael Omartian|Michael]] and [[Stormie Omartian]]\n| website         = {{url|http://www.2ndchapterofacts.com/}}\n| past_members    =\n\n* [[Annie Herring]]\n* [[Nelly Greisen]]\n* [[Matthew Ward (singer)|Matthew Ward]]\n\n}}\n\nThe '''2nd Chapter of Acts''' was a [[Jesus music]] and early [[contemporary Christian music]] group composed of sisters [[Annie Herring]] and [[Nelly Greisen]] and brother [[Matthew Ward (singer)|Matthew Ward]]. They began performing in 1973 and enjoyed their period of greatest success during the 1970s. The group disbanded in 1988.\n\n== History ==\n\nThe 2nd Chapter of Acts began as a result of the trio singing at home together as Annie played the piano. Following the death of their parents (Elizabeth in 1968 and Walter Ward in 1970),<ref>Booklet included with compilation ''20'' (1992), chapter \"Simple Faith\", section \"Trouble at Home\".</ref> Nelly and Matthew, still [[minor (law)|minors]], moved in with their older sister, Annie, and her husband, recording engineer and producer, Buck Herring.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.matthewward.com/bio_past.shtml|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040610191228/http://www.matthewward.com/bio_past.shtml|url-status=dead|title=Matthew Ward Biography: 2nd Chapter of Acts|archivedate=Jun 10, 2004|accessdate=Apr 6, 2020}}</ref> Annie was a self-taught singer and songwriter who composed and played her songs around the family piano.  Her brother and sister would often join in as she played, and eventually they developed extremely tight and intricate harmonies.<ref name=\"EofCCM\">{{cite book |last=Powell |first=Mark Allan |title=Encyclopedia of Contemporary Christian Music |publisher=Hendrickson Publishers |year=2002 |location=Peabody, Massachusetts |isbn=1-56563-679-1 |page=801 |quote=\"2nd Chaper was better than any of those groups--they had a more consistent songeriter, stronger vocals and, especially, tighter harmonies\" }}</ref><ref name=\"2ndchapterofacts.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.2ndchapterofacts.com/articles/frame-picture.htm |title=The Frame Never Outdid the Picture: The 2nd Chapter of Acts Story |publisher=2ndchapterofacts.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-29}}{{Dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThey started singing for local coffee houses and small gatherings, then gained the notice of [[Pat Boone]] who arranged a contract to record and release two singles with MGM, \"Jesus Is\" (1972) and \"I'm So Happy\" (1973). The fledgling trio also came to the attention of 1960s folk singer [[Barry McGuire]], who had recently become a Christian and was preparing to record his first Christian music album, produced by Buck Herring. The siblings provided background vocals for ''Seeds'' and McGuire's 1974 follow-up ''Lighten Up''.\n\nThe trio released their debut album, ''[[With Footnotes]]'', in 1974. This album featured \"[[Easter Song]]\" which would become a signature piece for the group and has been recorded by many other artists since. This was followed up with ''[[In the Volume of the Book]]'' in 1975, the year that also saw the release of a live album with Barry McGuire, ''[[To the Bride]]'', which included \"[[a band called David]]\", who supported 2nd Chapter of Acts on tour. 2nd Chapter of Acts' first three releases were issued by [[Myrrh Records]], and the group toured with McGuire intermittently for three years.\n\nThe group went on a touring hiatus in 1976. Annie released her first solo record on the [[Sparrow Records]] label founded that year by the executive who had signed them to the Myrrh label, [[Billy Ray Hearn]]. For the summer of 1977, they were joined on an 18-city tour by [[Phil Keaggy]] and the result was the live triple album, ''[[How the West Was One (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|How the West Was One]]''. Their contract with Myrrh fulfilled, they moved as a group to Sparrow.<ref name=\"2ndchapterofacts.com\"/>\n\nTheir Sparrow debut, ''[[Mansion Builder]]'' (1978) was followed up with ''[[The Roar of Love]]'' (1980) (a concept album inspired by [[C. S. Lewis]]' ''[[The Lion, the Witch, and the Wardrobe]]''), ''[[Rejoice (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Rejoice]]'' (1981), ''[[Singer Sower]]'' (1983), and ''[[Together Live]]'' (1983) (with [[Michael Omartian|Michael]] and [[Stormie Omartian]]).  2nd Chapter moved to their own Live Oak label with the release of ''[[Night Light (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Night Light]]'' in 1985, and their final recording of original material, ''[[Far Away Places (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Faraway Places]]'' in 1987.\n\nTheir voices can be heard among other Christian artists on two benefit singles in 1985.  ''Do Something Now!'' credited to ''The Cause'' on [[Sparrow Records]] to aid famine relief in Africa and ''Fight the Fight, Rescue the Unborn'' which featured over 100 Christian artists, to benefit the Christian Pro-Life Movement, released on Live Oak.\n\n2nd Chapter of Acts broadened their appeal with the release of [[Hymns (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Hymns]] and [[Hymns 2]], reaching audiences with more traditional music. ''Hymns'' proved to be their best-selling release, receiving a [[Dove Award]] for \"Best Praise and Worship Album of the Year\" in 1987.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.doveawards.com/history.php?x=artist |title=Dove Award History Artist |publisher=Doveawards.com |date= |accessdate=2011-11-29 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120605031050/http://www.doveawards.com/history.php?x=artist |archivedate=2012-06-05 }}</ref>\n\nExcept for two sabbatical years in 1976 and 1983, 2nd Chapter of Acts continued to tour until 1988. Their final concert was in Houston, Texas on August 12 of that year.<ref name=\"2ndchapterofacts.com\"/>\n\n2nd Chapter was recognized by the [[Gospel Music Association]] in 1999 by their induction into its [[Gospel Music Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gmahalloffame.org/site/?page_id=84 |title=Gospel Music Hall of Fame: Year of 1999 |publisher=Gmahalloffame.org |accessdate=2011-11-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929144220/http://www.gmahalloffame.org/site/?page_id=84 |archive-date=2011-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nAnnie and Matthew also recorded several solo projects during the 2nd Chapter of Acts years. Both have continued to release new material and perform concerts as of 2011.\n\n== Roles of group members ==\n\nAnnie was the main songwriter of the group and the only one who played an instrument (piano). Her admittedly unschooled compositional style, with its frequent irregular rhythms, added somewhat progressive rock-like elements to what was otherwise a soft-rock sound. Matthew and Nelly initially made the occasional small contribution to the lyrics, and Matthew developed as a songwriter for the group as his solo career grew.\n\nAnnie and Matthew sang most of the solo parts. Nelly \u2014 whose voice could be hard to distinguish from Annie's \u2014 usually sang lead only on songs where each member took a verse (\"Which Way The Wind Blows\", \"Something Tells Me\", \"Takin' The Easy Way\") or on solo pieces without the others singing backup (\"I Don't Wanna Go Home\", \"Make My Life a Prayer\" and \"Mountain Tops\"). Vocal leads such as in \"My Jesus I Love Thee\" and \"Sing Over Me\", where she was backed by the others, were rare exceptions. Her voice was considered the \"glue\" to the 2nd Chapter of Acts sound, and her harmony parts were generally the most difficult to sing.\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Albums ===\n\n* 1974: ''[[With Footnotes]]''  (Myrrh)\n* 1975: ''[[In the Volume of the Book]]'' (Myrrh)\n* 1975: ''[[To the Bride]]'' (two LPs; with Barry McGuire and \"a band called David\") (Myrrh). Most of this is by McGuire. The 2nd Chapter's section \u2014 one side plus two songs \u2014 consists mostly of songs they never released anywhere else.\n* 1976: ''Firewind'' (a \"dramatic musical\" based on Acts chapters 1-4) featuring Barry McGuire, Anne Herring, Terry Talbot, John Talbot, Nelly Ward, Keith Green and Matthew Ward, with narration by David Young (Sparrow SPR 1004) \n* 1977: ''[[How the West Was One (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|How the West Was One]]'' (Three LPs; with Phil Keaggy and \"a band called David\") (Myrrh). Half of this was by 2nd Chapter, half by Phil Keaggy. It was later reissued on two CDs.\n* 1978: ''[[Mansion Builder]]'' ([[Sparrow Records]])\n* 1980: ''[[The Roar of Love]]'' (Sparrow)\n* 1981: ''[[Rejoice (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Rejoice]]'' (Sparrow)\n* 1983: ''[[Singer Sower]]'' (Sparrow)\n* 1983: ''[[Together Live]]'' (Two LPs; with Michael and Stormie Omartian) (Sparrow). One side plus one song was by the Omartians; the rest was by 2nd Chapter. It includes one 2nd Chapter song that was never released anywhere else. This is the only 2nd Chapter album that has never been released on CD.\n* 1985: ''[[Night Light (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Night Light]]'' (Sparrow)\n* 1986: ''[[Hymns (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Hymns]]'' (Sparrow)\n* 1987: ''[[Far Away Places (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Far Away Places]]'' (Sparrow)\n* 1988: ''[[Hymns II (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Hymns II]]'' (Sparrow)\n* 1989: ''[[Hymns Instrumental]]'' (Sparrow)\n\n=== Compilations ===\n\n* 1981: ''[[Encores (2nd Chapter of Acts album)|Encores]]'' (Myrrh)\n* 1992: ''[[20 (CD album)|20]]'' (Navarre) [includes a few unreleased songs] ''Issued on two CDs or two cassettes.''\n* 2006: ''[[Very Best of 2nd Chapter of Acts]]''\n\n=== Video ===\n\n* 1983: ''[[Together Live]]'' [with [[Michael Omartian|Michael]] and [[Stormie Omartian]]] (Sparrow)\n* 1998: ''[[First Love: a Historic Gathering of Jesus Music Pioneers|First Love]]''  Various Artists\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Official website|http://www.2ndchapterofacts.com}}\n* [http://www.musicmoz.org/Bands_and_Artists/2/2nd_Chapter_of_Acts/ Musicmoz:2nd Chapter of Acts]\n\n{{2nd Chapter of Acts}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2nd Chapter of Acts}}\n[[Category:1973 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:1988 disestablishments in California]]\n[[Category:Christian rock groups from California]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1988]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1973]]\n[[Category:Family musical groups]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Gospel Music Associationclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2nd_Chapter_of_Acts"}
{"title_page": "Dino Kartsonakis", "text_new": "{{unreliable sources|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Dino Kartsonakis\n| image            = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| image_size       = \n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1942|07|20}}\n| birth_place      = [[New York City]], [[United States]]\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| genre            = [[Christian music|Christian]], [[Classical music|classical]]\n| occupation       = [[Pianist]], [[television host]]\n| instrument       = [[Piano]]\n| years_active     = 1963\u2013present\n| label            = [[Benson Records|Benson]]\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{URL|https://dinokartsonakismusic.com/}}\n}}\n \n'''Dino Kartsonakis''' (born July 20, 1942) is an American [[pianist]] of [[Greece|Greek]] heritage. He is known for his virtuosic arrangements of sacred music for the piano.\n\n==Biography==\nDino was born in [[New York City]] and attended Glad Tidings Tabernacle. He began playing his grandmother's piano at the age of three. The first song he had learned was \"At the Cross.\" He was enrolled in piano lessons at age five. Dino received his professional training at [[The King's College (New York)|The King's College]] as well as the [[Juilliard School]] of Music. For many years he served as pianist for the evangelist [[Kathryn Kuhlman]]. Dino has traveled extensively and produced well over 50 recordings on his own as well as mainstream labels. He has worked with various other evangelists. \n\nDino has hosted two television shows, the \"Dino and Debby Show\" in the 1970s with his first wife Deborah Keener and \"The Dino Show\" which formerly aired on the [[Trinity Broadcasting Network]].  Dino has described his style as combining the classical and the sacred. His technique has been described as fluid and brilliant and he has been termed the \"Christian Liberace\" because of his flair, costumes, pianos and jewelry.<ref name=\"The Christian Liberace\">{{cite web|last=Kartsonakis|first=Dino|title=Dino Dubbed \"The Christian Liberace\"|url=http://www.oldies.com/artist-view/Dino.html|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> \n\nMany of his works are religious-based or contemporary arrangements of classical works. Dino also performs in his own show in [[Branson, Missouri]].<ref name=\"Dino's Branson Shows\">{{cite web|last=Kartsonakis|first=Dino|title=Dino Performs in Branson|url=http://www.bransonshows.com/articles/DinosChristmasExtravaganzainBranson.htm|publisher=Bransonshows.com|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>  Among his accomplishments is production of what is known as the \"Peace Series\", a collection of CDs featuring more subdued piano arrangements against a backdrop of nature sounds. \n\nDino performed at [[Carnegie Hall]] on December 15, 2005. He has participated in an auction benefiting Music Cares, a charitable organization that helps struggling musicians and entertainers.<ref name=\"Kartsonakis Plays Carnegie Hall\">{{cite web|last=Kartsonakis|first=Dino|title=Dino Plays Carnegie Hall|url=http://www.assistnews.net/Stories/2005/s05120024.htm|publisher=assistnews.net|accessdate=13 October 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016044213/http://www.assistnews.net/Stories/2005/s05120024.htm|archivedate=16 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nDino received a participation [[Grammy Award]] in 1999 for his work on the soundtrack of the movie [[The Apostle]].<ref name=\"Dino wins Grammy for his participation in the movie soundtrack of The Apostle\">{{cite web|last=Kartsonakis|first=Dino|title=Dino  wins participation Grammy for the Apostle|url=http://www.awardsandshows.com/features/best-southern-country-bluegrass-gospel-317.html|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1974, Dino married his first wife, Deborah Keener, and together they have a daughter, Christina (who is now a singer-songwriter and producer, and goes by the stage name Sugar Dame).<ref name=\"Christina Kartsonakis as Sugar Dame\">{{cite web|last=Kartsonakis|first=Christina|title=Christina Kartsonakis as Sugar Dame|url=http://www.antimusic.com/morley/13/ChristinaKartsonakis.shtml|publisher=antimusic.com|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> After touring as Dino & Debby, the two divorced in 1981. In 1986, Dino married his second and current wife, Cheryl, who is the sister of [[Gospel music]] singer, Gary McSpadden, formerly of [[The Imperials]] and the [[Gaither Vocal Band]]. Cheryl has a daughter from a previous marriage.<ref name=\"Dino Kartsonakis divorces first wife\">{{cite web|last=Kartsonakis|first=Dino|title=Dino divorces first wife|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_3jqjSKHKcwC&pg=PA260&lpg=PA260&dq=dino+kartsonakis+divorce&source=bl&ots=a5m7KZQPHz&sig=xpbYGjroLEqvnpKvnWtduxDRxRg&hl=en&sa=X&ei=K41aUt_yKNHMkAe_nIDABg&ved=0CD0Q6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=dino%20kartsonakis%20divorce&f=false|publisher=google.com|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 Dino and his wife Cheryl opened a bakery in [[Branson, MO]] called Dino's Cake & Coffee Co. (Formally Dino's 24 Karrot Cake Company) Dino remarked that baking was his passion second only to performing his music. They are a major supplier to the [[Neiman Marcus]] stores and caf\u00e9s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bransoncake.com/|title=Dino's 24 Karrot Cake & Coffee Co. {{!}} Home of the 24Karrot Carrot Cake, Gourmet Cake, Coffees and Espresso|website=Dino's 24 Karrot Cake & Coffee Co. {{!}} Home of the 24Karrot Carrot Cake, Gourmet Cake, Coffees and Espresso|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 Dino and his wife Cheryl lost their home during a flood in the Branson, Missouri area. Dino lost all of his possessions such as his grand show pianos as well as all of his costumes, industry memorabilia and awards. The Kartsonakis' then started helping the community by doing fundraising concerts to help other victims rebuild their lives and homes.\n\n==GMA awards==\nEight Gospel Music Association [[Dove Awards]]:\n*1978, 1980, 1981, 1982, 1983, 1986: Instrumentalist of the Year<ref name=\"DOVE_IN\">\"[http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?cid=37 Dove Award Recipients for Instrumentalist] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061020022718/http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?cid=37 |date=2006-10-20 }}\". Published by the {{subst:^|<strong>}}Gospel Music Association{{subst:^|</strong>}}. Retrieved November 15, 2006.</ref>\n*1993, 1996: Instrumental Album of the Year<ref name=\"DOVE_INA\">\"[http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?cid=38 Dove Award Recipients for Instrumental Album] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010619003855/http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?cid=38 |date=2001-06-19 }}\". Published by the {{subst:^|<strong>}}Gospel Music Association{{subst:^|</strong>}}. Retrieved November 15, 2006.</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*1963: ''No Greater Love''\n*1964: ''Request by Dino''\n*1972: ''Alleluia''\n*1972: ''Kathryn Kuhlman Presents Dino''\n*1973: ''The Miracle with David Rose''\n*1973: ''With Love from Dino''\n*1974: ''He Touched Me''\n*1974: ''Salute to the United States of America''\n*1975: ''My Tribute''\n*1976: ''Folk Musical Themes''\n*1977: ''Classic Country''\n*1978: ''Dino on Tour''\n*1978: ''Love Song''\n*1979: ''Just Piano Praise''\n*1979: ''Rise Again''\n*1980: ''Rush Hour''\n*1981: ''Just Piano Praise II''\n*1982: ''Just Piano Praise III''\n*1983: ''Chariots of Fire''\n*1983: ''Majesty''\n*1984: ''A Christmas Gift''\n*1984: ''Great is the Lord''\n*1985: ''Regal Reign''\n*1986: ''A Place For Us''\n*1987: ''A Piano Portrait''\n*1987: ''A Wonderful Time of the Year''\n*1988: ''Dino Kartsonakis''\n*1989: ''Peace in the Midst of the Storm''\n*1990: ''All Creation Sings''\n*1991: ''Majestic Peace''\n*1992: ''Christmas...A Time For Peace''\n*1992: ''Somewhere in Time''\n*1993: ''Rhythm of Peace''\n*1994: ''Miracles''\n*1995: ''Classical Peace''\n*1996: ''Quiet Time''\n*1997: ''Moonlight Sonata''\n*1997: ''The Apostle Soundtrack''\n*1997: ''The Lord's Prayer''\n*1997: ''Unforgettable''\n*1998: ''A Christmas Celebration''\n*1999: ''Quiet Romance''\n*2000: ''Quiet Inspiration''\n*2002: ''Somewhere in Christmastime''\n*2007: ''Birthday of the King''\n\n===Compilations===\n*1976: ''Christmas with Dino''\n*1985: ''Encore''\n*1998: ''Dino Collector's Series''\n*2007: ''Sacred Piano Hymns''\n\n===Video===\n*1987: ''A Concert Spectacular''\n*1998: ''Music For All Time''\n*2000: ''Christmas Extravaganza''\n*2002: ''Easter Spring Spectacular''\n*2007: ''Birthday of the King''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.dinokartsonakismusic.com/ Official Website]\n*\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kartsonakis, Dino}}\n[[Category:American television evangelists]]\n[[Category:American performers of Christian music]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Performers of contemporary Christian music]]\n[[Category:People from Branson, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Musicians from New York City]]\n[[Category:Juilliard School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{unreliable sources|date=November 2018}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Dino Kartsonakis\n| image            = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| image_size       = \n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1942|07|20}}\n| birth_place      = [[New York City]], [[United States]]\n| death_date       = \n| death_place      = \n| genre            = [[Christian music|Christian]], [[Classical music|classical]]\n| occupation       = [[Pianist]], [[television host]]\n| instrument       = [[Piano]]\n| years_active     = 1963\u2013present\n| label            = [[Benson Records|Benson]]\n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = {{URL|https://dinokartsonakismusic.com/}}\n}}\n \n'''Dino Kartsonakis''' (born July 20, 1942) is an American [[pianist]] of [[Greece|Greek]] heritage. He is known for his virtuosic arrangements of sacred music for the piano.\n\n==Biography==\nDino was born in [[New York City]] and attended Glad Tidings Tabernacle. He began playing his grandmother's piano at the age of three. The first song he had learned was \"At the Cross.\" He was enrolled in piano lessons at age five. Dino received his professional training at [[The King's College (New York)|The King's College]] as well as the [[Juilliard School]] of Music. For many years he served as pianist for the evangelist [[Kathryn Kuhlman]]. Dino has traveled extensively and produced well over 50 recordings on his own as well as mainstream labels. He has worked with various other evangelists. \n\nDino has hosted two television shows, the \"Dino and Debby Show\" in the 1970s with his first wife Deborah Keener and \"The Dino Show\" which formerly aired on the [[Trinity Broadcasting Network]].  Dino has described his style as combining the classical and the sacred. His technique has been described as fluid and brilliant and he has been termed the \"Christian Liberace\" because of his flair, costumes, pianos and jewelry.<ref name=\"The Christian Liberace\">{{cite web|last=Kartsonakis|first=Dino|title=Dino Dubbed \"The Christian Liberace\"|url=http://www.oldies.com/artist-view/Dino.html|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> \n\nMany of his works are religious-based or contemporary arrangements of classical works. Dino also performs in his own show in [[Branson, Missouri]].<ref name=\"Dino's Branson Shows\">{{cite web|last=Kartsonakis|first=Dino|title=Dino Performs in Branson|url=http://www.bransonshows.com/articles/DinosChristmasExtravaganzainBranson.htm|publisher=Bransonshows.com|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>  Among his accomplishments is production of what is known as the \"Peace Series\", a collection of CDs featuring more subdued piano arrangements against a backdrop of nature sounds. \n\nDino performed at [[Carnegie Hall]] on December 15, 2005. He has participated in an auction benefiting Music Cares, a charitable organization that helps struggling musicians and entertainers.<ref name=\"Kartsonakis Plays Carnegie Hall\">{{cite web|last=Kartsonakis|first=Dino|title=Dino Plays Carnegie Hall|url=http://www.assistnews.net/Stories/2005/s05120024.htm|publisher=assistnews.net|accessdate=13 October 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016044213/http://www.assistnews.net/Stories/2005/s05120024.htm|archivedate=16 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nDino received a participation [[Grammy Award]] in 1999 for his work on the soundtrack of the movie [[The Apostle]].<ref name=\"Dino wins Grammy for his participation in the movie soundtrack of The Apostle\">{{cite web|last=Kartsonakis|first=Dino|title=Dino  wins participation Grammy for the Apostle|url=http://www.awardsandshows.com/features/best-southern-country-bluegrass-gospel-317.html|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1974, Dino married his first wife, Deborah Keener, and together they have a daughter, Christina (who is now a singer-songwriter and producer, and goes by the stage name Sugar Dame).<ref name=\"Christina Kartsonakis as Sugar Dame\">{{cite web|last=Kartsonakis|first=Christina|title=Christina Kartsonakis as Sugar Dame|url=http://www.antimusic.com/morley/13/ChristinaKartsonakis.shtml|publisher=antimusic.com|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref> After touring as Dino & Debby, the two divorced in 1981. In 1986, Dino married his second and current wife, Cheryl, who is the sister of [[Gospel music]] singer, Gary McSpadden, formerly of [[The Imperials]] and the [[Gaither Vocal Band]]. Cheryl has a daughter from a previous marriage.<ref name=\"Dino Kartsonakis divorces first wife\">{{cite web|last=Kartsonakis|first=Dino|title=Dino divorces first wife|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_3jqjSKHKcwC&pg=PA260&lpg=PA260&dq=dino+kartsonakis+divorce&source=bl&ots=a5m7KZQPHz&sig=xpbYGjroLEqvnpKvnWtduxDRxRg&hl=en&sa=X&ei=K41aUt_yKNHMkAe_nIDABg&ved=0CD0Q6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=dino%20kartsonakis%20divorce&f=false|publisher=google.com|accessdate=13 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007 Dino and his wife Cheryl opened a bakery in [[Branson, MO]] called Dino's Cake & Coffee Co. (Formally Dino's 24 Karrot Cake Company) Dino remarked that baking was his passion second only to performing his music. They are a major supplier to the [[Neiman Marcus]] stores and caf\u00e9s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bransoncake.com/|title=Dino's 24 Karrot Cake & Coffee Co. {{!}} Home of the 24Karrot Carrot Cake, Gourmet Cake, Coffees and Espresso|website=Dino's 24 Karrot Cake & Coffee Co. {{!}} Home of the 24Karrot Carrot Cake, Gourmet Cake, Coffees and Espresso|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 Dino and his wife Cheryl lost their home during a flood in the Branson, Missouri area. Dino lost all of his possessions such as his grand show pianos as well as all of his costumes, industry memorabilia and awards. The Kartsonakis' then started helping the community by doing fundraising concerts to help other victims rebuild their lives and homes.\n\n==GMA awards==\nEight [[Gospel Music Association]] [[Dove Awards]]:\n*1978, 1980, 1981, 1982, 1983, 1986: Instrumentalist of the Year<ref name=\"DOVE_IN\">\"[http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?cid=37 Dove Award Recipients for Instrumentalist] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061020022718/http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?cid=37 |date=2006-10-20 }}\". Published by the [[Gospel Music Association]]. Retrieved November 15, 2006.</ref>\n*1993, 1996: Instrumental Album of the Year<ref name=\"DOVE_INA\">\"[http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?cid=38 Dove Award Recipients for Instrumental Album] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010619003855/http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?cid=38 |date=2001-06-19 }}\". Published by the [[Gospel Music Association]]. Retrieved November 15, 2006.</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*1963: ''No Greater Love''\n*1964: ''Request by Dino''\n*1972: ''Alleluia''\n*1972: ''Kathryn Kuhlman Presents Dino''\n*1973: ''The Miracle with David Rose''\n*1973: ''With Love from Dino''\n*1974: ''He Touched Me''\n*1974: ''Salute to the United States of America''\n*1975: ''My Tribute''\n*1976: ''Folk Musical Themes''\n*1977: ''Classic Country''\n*1978: ''Dino on Tour''\n*1978: ''Love Song''\n*1979: ''Just Piano Praise''\n*1979: ''Rise Again''\n*1980: ''Rush Hour''\n*1981: ''Just Piano Praise II''\n*1982: ''Just Piano Praise III''\n*1983: ''Chariots of Fire''\n*1983: ''Majesty''\n*1984: ''A Christmas Gift''\n*1984: ''Great is the Lord''\n*1985: ''Regal Reign''\n*1986: ''A Place For Us''\n*1987: ''A Piano Portrait''\n*1987: ''A Wonderful Time of the Year''\n*1988: ''Dino Kartsonakis''\n*1989: ''Peace in the Midst of the Storm''\n*1990: ''All Creation Sings''\n*1991: ''Majestic Peace''\n*1992: ''Christmas...A Time For Peace''\n*1992: ''Somewhere in Time''\n*1993: ''Rhythm of Peace''\n*1994: ''Miracles''\n*1995: ''Classical Peace''\n*1996: ''Quiet Time''\n*1997: ''Moonlight Sonata''\n*1997: ''The Apostle Soundtrack''\n*1997: ''The Lord's Prayer''\n*1997: ''Unforgettable''\n*1998: ''A Christmas Celebration''\n*1999: ''Quiet Romance''\n*2000: ''Quiet Inspiration''\n*2002: ''Somewhere in Christmastime''\n*2007: ''Birthday of the King''\n\n===Compilations===\n*1976: ''Christmas with Dino''\n*1985: ''Encore''\n*1998: ''Dino Collector's Series''\n*2007: ''Sacred Piano Hymns''\n\n===Video===\n*1987: ''A Concert Spectacular''\n*1998: ''Music For All Time''\n*2000: ''Christmas Extravaganza''\n*2002: ''Easter Spring Spectacular''\n*2007: ''Birthday of the King''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.dinokartsonakismusic.com/ Official Website]\n*\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kartsonakis, Dino}}\n[[Category:American television evangelists]]\n[[Category:American performers of Christian music]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Performers of contemporary Christian music]]\n[[Category:People from Branson, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Musicians from New York City]]\n[[Category:Juilliard School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Gospel Music Associationclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dino_Kartsonakis"}
{"title_page": "Southern Gospel Music Association", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Southern Gospel Music Association|timestamp=20200404090125|year=2020|month=April|day=4|substed=yes}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Southern Gospel Music Association|date=4 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox company\n | name             = Southern Gospel Music Association\n | logo             =\n| type             = [[Privately held company|Private]] \n | genre            = [[Christian music|Christian]]\n | foundation       = \n | founder          = Glen Payne J.D.Sumner James Blackwood \n | location_city    = [[Pigeon Forge, Tennessee]]\n | location_country = [[United States]]\n | location         = \n | locations        = \n | area_served      = \n | key_people       = Raymond Brooks Eric Blackwood David Sutton Eric Bennett Lisa Fuller Ron Blackwood jr Daniel Justice Martina Blackwood\n | industry         = Southern gospel music \n | products         = \n | services         = \n | assets           = \n | equity           = \n | owner            = Southern Gospel Media\n | num_employees    = \n | parent           = Southern Gospel Media\n | divisions        = \n | subsid           = \n | slogan           = \n | homepage         = [http://www.sgma.org/ sgma.org]\n | footnotes        = \n | intl             = \n}}\nThe '''Southern Gospel Music Association''' (''SGMA'') is a non-profit corporation formed as an association of [[southern gospel]] music singers, songwriters, fans, and industry workers. Membership is acquired and maintained through payment of annual dues. The SGMA was formed in 1994, and states that its primary goal is \"to preserve, protect and promote Southern Gospel Music, its history and heritage\".\n\nThe Southern Gospel Music Association operates the [[Southern Gospel Museum and Hall of Fame]] in [[Pigeon Forge, Tennessee|Pigeon Forge]], a popular [[Tennessee]] tourist town, and also hosts the Southern Gospel Music Awards. The Hall of Fame and Museum was opened at the [[Dollywood]] theme park in 1999.\n\nLeadership of the SGMA is vested in a 23-member board of directors. The SGMA is responsible for the nomination, selection, and induction into the [[Southern Gospel Museum and Hall of Fame|Southern Gospel Music Hall of Fame]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Gospel Music Hall of Fame]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sgma.org/ sgma.org Official website]\n\n{{clr}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Southern Gospel Music Association}}\n[[Category:Southern gospel]]\n[[Category:Gospel music associations]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Music organizations based in the United States]]\n\n\n{{US-southern-gospel-stub}}\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Southern Gospel Music Association|timestamp=20200404090125|year=2020|month=April|day=4|substed=yes}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Southern Gospel Music Association|date=4 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox company\n | name             = Southern Gospel Music Association\n | logo             =\n| type             = [[Privately held company|Private]] \n | genre            = [[Christian music|Christian]]\n | foundation       = \n | founder          = Glen Payne J.D.Sumner James Blackwood \n | location_city    = [[Pigeon Forge, Tennessee]]\n | location_country = [[United States]]\n | location         = \n | locations        = \n | area_served      = \n | key_people       = Raymond Brooks Eric Blackwood David Sutton Eric Bennett Lisa Fuller Ron Blackwood jr Daniel Justice Martina Blackwood\n | industry         = Southern gospel music \n | products         = \n | services         = \n | assets           = \n | equity           = \n | owner            = Southern Gospel Media\n | num_employees    = \n | parent           = Southern Gospel Media\n | divisions        = \n | subsid           = \n | slogan           = \n | homepage         = [http://www.sgma.org/ sgma.org]\n | footnotes        = \n | intl             = \n}}\nThe '''Southern Gospel Music Association''' (''SGMA'') is a non-profit corporation formed as an association of [[southern gospel]] music singers, songwriters, fans, and industry workers. Membership is acquired and maintained through payment of annual dues. The SGMA was formed in 1994, and states that its primary goal is \"to preserve, protect and promote Southern Gospel Music, its history and heritage\".\n\nThe Southern Gospel Music Association operates the [[Southern Gospel Museum and Hall of Fame]] in [[Pigeon Forge, Tennessee|Pigeon Forge]], a popular [[Tennessee]] tourist town, and also hosts the Southern Gospel Music Awards. The Hall of Fame and Museum was opened at the [[Dollywood]] theme park in 1999.\n\nLeadership of the SGMA is vested in a 23-member board of directors. The SGMA is responsible for the nomination, selection, and induction into the [[Southern Gospel Museum and Hall of Fame|Southern Gospel Music Hall of Fame]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Gospel Music Association]]\n*[[Gospel Music Hall of Fame]]\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sgma.org/ sgma.org Official website]\n\n{{clr}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Southern Gospel Music Association}}\n[[Category:Southern gospel]]\n[[Category:Gospel music associations]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Music organizations based in the United States]]\n\n\n{{US-southern-gospel-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Gospel Music Associationclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Southern_Gospel_Music_Association"}
{"title_page": "Jignesh Mevani", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian politician and activist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Jignesh jhaatu Mevani\n| image = Jignesh Mevani.jpg\n| caption = At Gujarati Literature Festival, Ahmedabad on 16 December 2016\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1982|12|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Ahmedabad]], [[Gujarat]], [[India]]\n| nationality = [[India]]n\n| education = * [[Bachelor of Arts]]\n* [[Bachelor of Laws]]\n| alma_mater = [[Gujarat University]]\n| occupation = lawyer, social activist, politician\n| office = [[Member of Legislative assembly|MLA]] of [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly|Gujarat]]\n| term_start = December 2017\n| term_end = \n| party = Independent\n| religion = \n| constituency = [[Vadgam (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Vadgam]]\n| known_for = \n| signature = Jignesh Mevani autograph.svg\n}}\n'''Jignesh Mevani''' (born 11 December 1982)<ref name=\"A\">{{cite web |title=Jignesh Mevani: His Popularity Set To Hit A Roadblock In 2018, Predicts Ganesha |url=https://www.ganeshaspeaks.com/predictions/politics/jignesh-mevani-astrology-predictions/ |accessdate=15 August 2018|date=3 February 2017 }}</ref> is an Indian politician. He is a member representing [[Vadgam (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Vadgam]] constituency in [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]. He has worked as a social activist and lawyer. He had led [[Gujarat Dalit protests|protests by Dalit]]s, considered 'lower castes' in the [[caste system in India|Indian caste hierarchy]], in Gujarat in 2016.<ref name=\"India Today 2016\">{{cite web | title=10 things to know about Jignesh Mevani, the man leading Gujarats Dalit agitation | website=India Today | date=5 August 2016 | url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/jignesh-mevani-the-man-leading-gujarat-dalit-agitation/1/732862.html | accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nMevani was born on 11 December 1982 in [[Ahmedabad]], Gujarat to a Dalit family.<ref name=\"A\"/> His family is native of Meu, a village in [[Mehsana district]]. He completed his schooling from Swastik Vidyalaya and Vishwa Vidyalay Madhyamik Shala in Ahmedabad. He completed [[Bachelor of Arts]] in English literature in 2003 from H.K Arts College, Ahmedabad. In 2004, he received Diploma in Journalism and Mass Communication. From 2004 to 2007, he served as a reporter for ''Abhiyan'', a Gujarati magazine. In 2013, he received [[Bachelor of Laws]] from D. T. Law College, Ahmedabad.<ref name= \"mp\">{{cite magazine |last=Vankar |first=Devendra |date=October 2016 |title= Introduction article on Jignesh Mevani  |magazine=Sanvedana Samaj |editor1-last=Parmar |editor1-first=Anita |location= Ahmedabad |publisher= Kishor Makwana }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n=== Activism ===\n====2016 Gujarat Dalit unrest====\n{{main|Gujarat Dalit unrest}}\n\nAfter attack on Dalit men in [[Una, Gujarat|Una]] village in [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]] region of Gujarat by claimed members of cow protection group, protests broke out across Gujarat. Jignesh Mevani led the protest march called Dalit Asmita Yatra from Ahmedabad to Una, which culminated on 15 August 2016 and was attended by some 20,000 Dalits, including dalit women, who took a pledge to give up their traditional jobs of removing cow carcasses. He demanded the land for upliftment of Dalits.<ref name=\"India Today 2016\"/><ref name=\"Pathak 2016\">{{cite web | last=Pathak | first=Maulik | title=We plan to take our fight to other parts of India: Jignesh Mevani | website=LiveMint | date=7 October 2016 | url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/O5RJuV7wwud9iEOWOFXmjI/We-plan-to-take-our-fight-to-other-parts-of-India-Jignesh-M.html | accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Huffington Post India 2016\">{{cite web | title=The Leader Of The Fledgling Dalit Uprising In Gujarat Is Determined To Not Let It Die | website=Huffington Post India | date=4 August 2016 | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.in/2016/08/04/meet-the-face-of-the-rising-dalit-movement-in-gujarat/ | accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Politics===\nIn [[2017 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election]], he contested and won the election from [[Vadgam (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Vadgam]] constituency, running as an independent candidate with support of the [[Indian National Congress]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Dalit rising: Jignesh Mevani beats BJP by a handsome margin in Vadgam|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/gujarat-assembly-election-jignesh-mevani-wins-vadgam-beats-bjp/1/1112682.html|publisher=India Today|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alpesh Thakor And Jignesh Mevani, Big Congress Hopes, Win In Gujarat|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/alpesh-thakor-and-jignesh-mevani-big-congress-hopes-lead-in-gujarat-1789050|website=NDTV.com|publisher=NDTV|accessdate=18 December 2017|language=en}}</ref> and the [[Aam Aadmi Party]].\n[[File:Jignesh Mevani ( center) at Hunkar Rally, New Delhi, Jan 2018.jpg|left|thumb|Jignesh Mevani (center) at Youth Hunkar rally, Parliament Street, New Delhi, 9 January 2018.]]\n\n==Controversy==\nMevani was allegedly photographed receiving a cheque from members of the Social Democratic Party of India (SDPI), the political wing of the [[Popular Front of India]] (PFI), under the [[National Investigation Agency]] radar after many of its members were allegedly found fighting for the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]. In response, speaking to [[Times Now]], senior SDPI official Abrar Ahmed said, \"We are extending full support to Mevani. We will support any party which fights communal forces.\"<ref name=\"Economic Times\">{{cite news | title=Gujarat: Jignesh Mewani gets funds from radical outfit | newspaper=The Economic Times | date=9 December 2017 | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/radical-body-vows-support-to-mewani/articleshow/61994100.cms | accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref> When the BJP accused Mevani of terrorism links, Mevani denied the charges, and threatened to sue BJP for defamation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/elections/gujarat-assembly-elections-2017/accused-of-terror-link-fund-jignesh-mevani-threatens-to-sue-bjp-4975838/ |title=Accused of terror-link fund, Jignesh Mevani threatens to sue BJP |date=10 December 2017 |newspaper=Indian Express }}</ref> However two days after winning the Vadgam seat in the Gujarat Assembly election, speaking to [[CNN-News18]], he admitted that he had taken {{INR}} 51,000 as donation from the PFI for his campaign, and challenged the central government to ban the organisation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gujarat Assembly Elections: Jignesh Mevani admits to accepting Rs 51,000 as donation from PFI|url=http://www.firstpost.com/politics/gujarat-assembly-elections-jignesh-mevani-admits-to-accepting-rs-51000-as-donation-from-pfi-4267829.html|website=Firstpost|publisher=Firstpost|accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jignesh Mevani insults PM Modi|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SDIvhHI03Io|website=YouTube|publisher=CNN News18|accessdate=20 December 2017|ref=1:49}}</ref>\n\n;2018 Bhima Koregaon violence\n\n{{main|2018 Dalit protests in Maharashtra}}\nAlong with [[Umar Khalid]], Jignesh Mevani was booked under an FIR for giving 'provocative' speeches in [[Pune]]. The criminal offence against Mevani and Khalid was for promoting enmity between different groups through their speeches. The Elgaar Parishad rally, where this reportedly happened, was held in Pune to mark the 200th year of the [[Battle of Koregaon]], a place in present-day Pune district, which was fought between the then [[British Indian Army]] and the [[Peshwas]]. Besides Mevani and Khalid, the mother of [[Rohith Vemula]], Radhika Vemula, Dalit leader [[Prakash Yashwant Ambedkar]], Dalit activist [[Soni Sori]], and Bhim Army\u2019s Vinay Ratan Singh were among others who attended the conference.<ref>{{cite web | title=Bhima-Koregaon violence: FIR against Jignesh Mevani, Umar Khalid for 'provocative' speeches in Pune| website=Indian Express | date=4 January 2018 | url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/pune/fir-registered-against-jignesh-mevani-umar-khaid-for-provocative-speeches-in-pune-bhima-koregaon-5010950/ | accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mevani, Jignesh}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian social reformers]]\n[[Category:Dalit activists]]\n[[Category:Activists from Gujarat]]\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Gujarat]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian journalists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Writers from Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:Gujarat politicians]]\n[[Category:Gujarat University alumni]]\n[[Category:Gujarat MLAs 2017\u2013]]\n[[Category:Ambedkarites]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian politician and activist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Jignesh Mevani\n| image = Jignesh Mevani.jpg\n| caption = At Gujarati Literature Festival, Ahmedabad on 16 December 2016\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1982|12|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Ahmedabad]], [[Gujarat]], [[India]]\n| nationality = [[India]]n\n| education = * [[Bachelor of Arts]]\n* [[Bachelor of Laws]]\n| alma_mater = [[Gujarat University]]\n| occupation = lawyer, social activist, politician\n| office = [[Member of Legislative assembly|MLA]] of [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly|Gujarat]]\n| term_start = December 2017\n| term_end = \n| party = Independent\n| religion = \n| constituency = [[Vadgam (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Vadgam]]\n| known_for = \n| signature = Jignesh Mevani autograph.svg\n}}\n'''Jignesh Mevani''' (born 11 December 1982)<ref name=\"A\">{{cite web |title=Jignesh Mevani: His Popularity Set To Hit A Roadblock In 2018, Predicts Ganesha |url=https://www.ganeshaspeaks.com/predictions/politics/jignesh-mevani-astrology-predictions/ |accessdate=15 August 2018|date=3 February 2017 }}</ref> is an Indian politician. He is a member representing [[Vadgam (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Vadgam]] constituency in [[Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]. He has worked as a social activist and lawyer. He had led [[Gujarat Dalit protests|protests by Dalit]]s, considered 'lower castes' in the [[caste system in India|Indian caste hierarchy]], in Gujarat in 2016.<ref name=\"India Today 2016\">{{cite web | title=10 things to know about Jignesh Mevani, the man leading Gujarats Dalit agitation | website=India Today | date=5 August 2016 | url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/jignesh-mevani-the-man-leading-gujarat-dalit-agitation/1/732862.html | accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nMevani was born on 11 December 1982 in [[Ahmedabad]], Gujarat to a Dalit family.<ref name=\"A\"/> His family is native of Meu, a village in [[Mehsana district]]. He completed his schooling from Swastik Vidyalaya and Vishwa Vidyalay Madhyamik Shala in Ahmedabad. He completed [[Bachelor of Arts]] in English literature in 2003 from H.K Arts College, Ahmedabad. In 2004, he received Diploma in Journalism and Mass Communication. From 2004 to 2007, he served as a reporter for ''Abhiyan'', a Gujarati magazine. In 2013, he received [[Bachelor of Laws]] from D. T. Law College, Ahmedabad.<ref name= \"mp\">{{cite magazine |last=Vankar |first=Devendra |date=October 2016 |title= Introduction article on Jignesh Mevani  |magazine=Sanvedana Samaj |editor1-last=Parmar |editor1-first=Anita |location= Ahmedabad |publisher= Kishor Makwana }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n=== Activism ===\n====2016 Gujarat Dalit unrest====\n{{main|Gujarat Dalit unrest}}\n\nAfter attack on Dalit men in [[Una, Gujarat|Una]] village in [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]] region of Gujarat by claimed members of cow protection group, protests broke out across Gujarat. Jignesh Mevani led the protest march called Dalit Asmita Yatra from Ahmedabad to Una, which culminated on 15 August 2016 and was attended by some 20,000 Dalits, including dalit women, who took a pledge to give up their traditional jobs of removing cow carcasses. He demanded the land for upliftment of Dalits.<ref name=\"India Today 2016\"/><ref name=\"Pathak 2016\">{{cite web | last=Pathak | first=Maulik | title=We plan to take our fight to other parts of India: Jignesh Mevani | website=LiveMint | date=7 October 2016 | url=http://www.livemint.com/Politics/O5RJuV7wwud9iEOWOFXmjI/We-plan-to-take-our-fight-to-other-parts-of-India-Jignesh-M.html | accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Huffington Post India 2016\">{{cite web | title=The Leader Of The Fledgling Dalit Uprising In Gujarat Is Determined To Not Let It Die | website=Huffington Post India | date=4 August 2016 | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.in/2016/08/04/meet-the-face-of-the-rising-dalit-movement-in-gujarat/ | accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Politics===\nIn [[2017 Gujarat Legislative Assembly election]], he contested and won the election from [[Vadgam (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Vadgam]] constituency, running as an independent candidate with support of the [[Indian National Congress]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Dalit rising: Jignesh Mevani beats BJP by a handsome margin in Vadgam|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/gujarat-assembly-election-jignesh-mevani-wins-vadgam-beats-bjp/1/1112682.html|publisher=India Today|accessdate=18 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alpesh Thakor And Jignesh Mevani, Big Congress Hopes, Win In Gujarat|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/alpesh-thakor-and-jignesh-mevani-big-congress-hopes-lead-in-gujarat-1789050|website=NDTV.com|publisher=NDTV|accessdate=18 December 2017|language=en}}</ref> and the [[Aam Aadmi Party]].\n[[File:Jignesh Mevani ( center) at Hunkar Rally, New Delhi, Jan 2018.jpg|left|thumb|Jignesh Mevani (center) at Youth Hunkar rally, Parliament Street, New Delhi, 9 January 2018.]]\n\n==Controversy==\nMevani was allegedly photographed receiving a cheque from members of the Social Democratic Party of India (SDPI), the political wing of the [[Popular Front of India]] (PFI), under the [[National Investigation Agency]] radar after many of its members were allegedly found fighting for the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]. In response, speaking to [[Times Now]], senior SDPI official Abrar Ahmed said, \"We are extending full support to Mevani. We will support any party which fights communal forces.\"<ref name=\"Economic Times\">{{cite news | title=Gujarat: Jignesh Mewani gets funds from radical outfit | newspaper=The Economic Times | date=9 December 2017 | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/radical-body-vows-support-to-mewani/articleshow/61994100.cms | accessdate=9 December 2017}}</ref> When the BJP accused Mevani of terrorism links, Mevani denied the charges, and threatened to sue BJP for defamation.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/elections/gujarat-assembly-elections-2017/accused-of-terror-link-fund-jignesh-mevani-threatens-to-sue-bjp-4975838/ |title=Accused of terror-link fund, Jignesh Mevani threatens to sue BJP |date=10 December 2017 |newspaper=Indian Express }}</ref> However two days after winning the Vadgam seat in the Gujarat Assembly election, speaking to [[CNN-News18]], he admitted that he had taken {{INR}} 51,000 as donation from the PFI for his campaign, and challenged the central government to ban the organisation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gujarat Assembly Elections: Jignesh Mevani admits to accepting Rs 51,000 as donation from PFI|url=http://www.firstpost.com/politics/gujarat-assembly-elections-jignesh-mevani-admits-to-accepting-rs-51000-as-donation-from-pfi-4267829.html|website=Firstpost|publisher=Firstpost|accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jignesh Mevani insults PM Modi|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SDIvhHI03Io|website=YouTube|publisher=CNN News18|accessdate=20 December 2017|ref=1:49}}</ref>\n\n;2018 Bhima Koregaon violence\n\n{{main|2018 Dalit protests in Maharashtra}}\nAlong with [[Umar Khalid]], Jignesh Mevani was booked under an FIR for giving 'provocative' speeches in [[Pune]]. The criminal offence against Mevani and Khalid was for promoting enmity between different groups through their speeches. The Elgaar Parishad rally, where this reportedly happened, was held in Pune to mark the 200th year of the [[Battle of Koregaon]], a place in present-day Pune district, which was fought between the then [[British Indian Army]] and the [[Peshwas]]. Besides Mevani and Khalid, the mother of [[Rohith Vemula]], Radhika Vemula, Dalit leader [[Prakash Yashwant Ambedkar]], Dalit activist [[Soni Sori]], and Bhim Army\u2019s Vinay Ratan Singh were among others who attended the conference.<ref>{{cite web | title=Bhima-Koregaon violence: FIR against Jignesh Mevani, Umar Khalid for 'provocative' speeches in Pune| website=Indian Express | date=4 January 2018 | url=http://indianexpress.com/article/cities/pune/fir-registered-against-jignesh-mevani-umar-khaid-for-provocative-speeches-in-pune-bhima-koregaon-5010950/ | accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mevani, Jignesh}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian social reformers]]\n[[Category:Dalit activists]]\n[[Category:Activists from Gujarat]]\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Gujarat]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian journalists]]\n[[Category:Members of the Gujarat Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Writers from Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:Gujarat politicians]]\n[[Category:Gujarat University alumni]]\n[[Category:Gujarat MLAs 2017\u2013]]\n[[Category:Ambedkarites]]\n", "name_user": "2405:204:3487:a338:8d6:ddff:fe52:8e03", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jignesh_Mevani"}
{"title_page": "Andra\u00e9 Crouch", "text_new": "{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist \n| name             = Andra\u00e9 Crouch\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Andra\u00e9 Crouch cropped.JPG\n| caption          = Crouch in Stavanger, Norway in 2008\n| birth_name       = Andra\u00e9 Edward Crouch\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1942|7|1}}\n| birth_place      = [[San Francisco]], California, U.S.\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2015|1|8|1942|7|1}}\n| death_place      = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n| genre            = [[Gospel music|Gospel]], [[Contemporary Christian music|contemporary Christian]]\n| occupation       = Singer, songwriter, arranger, record producer, choir director, pastor\n| instrument       = Vocals, piano, organ\n| years_active     = 1966\u20132014\n| label            = [[Light Records|Light]], [[Qwest Records|Qwest]]/[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]], [[Verity Records|Verity]]/[[Jive Records|Jive]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Sandra Crouch]], [[T\u00e1ta Vega]], [[Danniebelle Hall]], [[Kristle Murden]]\n| website          = {{Facebook|andraecrouch}}\n| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n}}\n\n'''Andra\u00e9 Edward Crouch''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0251\u02d0|n|d|r|e\u026a}} (July 1, 1942&nbsp;\u2013 January 8, 2015) was an American [[Gospel music|gospel]] singer, songwriter, arranger, record producer and pastor. Referred to as \"the father of modern gospel music\" by [[Contemporary Christian Music|contemporary Christian]] and gospel music professionals,<ref>{{cite web|title=Andra\u00e9 Crouch, 'father of modern gospel music', dies|url=https://www.usatoday.com/videos/life/music/2015/01/09/21503643/|publisher=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=January 10, 2015}}</ref> Crouch was known for his compositions \"The Blood Will Never Lose Its Power\", \"My Tribute (To God Be the Glory)\" and \"Soon and Very Soon\". He collaborated on some of his recordings with artists, such as [[Stevie Wonder]], [[El DeBarge]], [[Philip Bailey]], [[Chaka Khan]], [[Sheila E.]] and vocal group [[Take 6]], and many recording artists covered his material, including, [[Bob Dylan]], [[Barbara Mandrell]], [[Paul Simon]], [[Elvis Presley]] and [[Little Richard]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/01/08/showbiz/andrae-crouch-obit/index.html|title=Gospel music legend Andrae Crouch dies |author1=Ed Payne |author2=Steve Almasy|publisher=CNN|accessdate=June 17, 2018}}</ref> In the 1980s and 1990s, he was known as the \"go to\" producer for superstars who sought a gospel choir sound in their recordings, appearing on a number of recordings, including [[Michael Jackson]]'s \"[[Man In the Mirror]]\", [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s \"[[Like a Prayer (song)|Like a Prayer]]\", and \"The Power\", a duet between [[Elton John]] and [[Little Richard]].<ref name=\"Brian Mansfield\">{{cite web | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2015/01/08/andrae-crouch-gospel-music-pioneer-dies/21262183/ | title=Gospel music pioneer Andra\u00e9 Crouch dies at 72 | publisher=USA Today | date=January 8, 2015 | accessdate=January 8, 2015 | author=Brian Mansfield}}</ref> Crouch was noted for his talent of incorporating contemporary secular music styles into the gospel music he grew up with. His efforts in this area helped pave the way for early American contemporary Christian music during the 1960s and 1970s.<ref name=\"Variety obit\">{{cite web | url=https://variety.com/2015/music/people-news/obituaries-people-news/gospel-music-legend-andrae-crouch-dies-at-72-1201396451/ | title=Gospel Music Legend Andrae Crouch Dies at 72 | publisher=Variety | date=January 8, 2015 | accessdate=January 9, 2015 |author1=Andrew Barker |author2=Senior Features Writer }}</ref>\n\nCrouch's original music arrangements were heard in the films ''[[The Color Purple (film)|The Color Purple]]'', for which he received an Oscar nomination, and Disney's ''[[The Lion King]]'', as well as the [[NBC]] television series ''[[Amen (TV series)|Amen]]''. Awards and honors received by him include seven [[Grammy Award]]s, induction into the Gospel Music Hall of Fame in 1998, and a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].<ref name=\"Variety obit\"/>\n\n== Early years ==\n\nAndra\u00e9 Edward Crouch was born, along with his twin sister, [[Sandra Crouch|Sandra]], on July 1, 1942, in San Francisco, California<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tributes.com/obituary/read/Andra%C3%A9-Crouch-102052107 | title=Andrae Crouch Obituary | publisher=The Associated Press | accessdate=April 5, 2015 | author=Rober Jablon}}</ref> to parents Benjamin and Catherine (n\u00e9e Hodnett) Crouch.<ref name=\"CM_Vol_51\"/> His father was a minister in the Church of God in Christ ([[COGIC]]) and pastored Christ Memorial Church of God in Christ in Pacoima, California. When he was young, Crouch's parents owned and operated Crouch Cleaners, a dry-cleaning business, as well as a restaurant business in [[Los Angeles]], California.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-04-11/local/me-291_1_sandra-crouch | title=Catherine D. Crouch; Singers' Mother | publisher=Los Angeles Times | date=April 11, 1992 | accessdate=January 8, 2015}}</ref> In addition to running the family's businesses, Crouch's parents also had a Christian street-preaching ministry and a hospital and prison ministry.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-12-23/local/me-4746_1_christ-memorial-church | title=Benjamin Crouch; Church Founder | publisher=Los Angeles Times | date=December 23, 1993 | accessdate=January 8, 2015}}</ref> When Crouch was 11, his father was invited to speak for several weeks at a small church as a guest preacher. Crouch's father and the church's congregation encouraged the young boy to play during the services. At the piano, Crouch found the key in which the congregation was singing and started to play. After this, Crouch honed his piano-playing skills and, in time, wanted to write his own music. When he was 14 years old, he wrote his first Gospel song.<ref name=\"Brian Mansfield\"/><ref name=\"Booth, John D. 1974, p. 3\">Booth, John D., The Music of Andrae Crouch and the Disciples. Masters of Church Music, New Orelans Baptist Theological Seminary, 1974, p. 3</ref><ref name=\"Carpenter, Bil 2005, page 107\">Carpenter, Bil. Uncloudy Days: The Gospel Music Encyclopedia, {{ISBN|978-0-87930-841-4}}, Backbeat Books, San Francisco, 2005, page 107</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Groups ===\n\nCrouch's first group musical effort was formed in 1960 as the Church of God in Christ Singers. The group included future recording artist and session musician [[Billy Preston]] on keyboards<ref name=\"CM_Vol_51\"/> and was the first to record Crouch's song \"The Blood Will Never Lose Its Power\". The song's popularity grew following the initial 1969 recording, becoming a standard in churches and hymnals worldwide.<ref name=\"Variety obit\"/> While attending [[Los Angeles Valley College|Valley Junior College]] in the San Fernando Valley to become a teacher, he formed gospel music group \"The Disciples\" in 1965 with fellow musicians Perry Morgan, Reuben Fernandez, and Bili Thedford.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gmahalloffame.org/site/andrae-crouch/ | title=Andre Crouch Biography | publisher=Gospel Music Association Hall of Fame | accessdate=January 9, 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109234121/http://www.gmahalloffame.org/site/andrae-crouch/ | archivedate=January 9, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The group became a frequent attraction at \"Monday Night Sing\" concerts in southern California put on by Audrey Mieir, a Christian minister and music composer who frequently sponsored new Christian music groups.<ref name=\"Carpenter, Bil 2005, page 107\"/> Following Mieir's introduction of Crouch to [[Manna Music Inc|Manna Music Publishing's]] founders Tim and Hal Spencer, Manna published Crouch's song \"The Blood Will Never Lose Its Power\", written when he was 15 years old. The Spencers helped launch Crouch's recording career by introducing them to [[Light Records]] founder and prolific Christian songwriter [[Ralph Carmichael]]. After the addition of [[Sherman Andrus]] to The Disciples, Light Records recorded and released the group's first album, ''Take the Message Everywhere'', in 1968.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MXNMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA57&lpg=PA57&q=andrae%20crouch%20Mieir%20tim%20spencer | title=This is My Story: 146 of the World's Greatest Gospel Singers | publisher=Thomas Nelson | work=This Is My Story: 146 of the World's Greatest Gospel Singers; Andrae Crouch | date=September 26, 2005 | accessdate=January 9, 2015 | author=Thomas Nelson | pages=57| isbn=9780529110329 }}</ref> Following the group's first album release, Crouch's twin sister, Sandra, joined The Disciples in 1970 after Fernandez' departure. Two more albums would follow, ''Keep On Singin{{'}}'' and ''Soulfully'', before a major change in the group's lineup in 1972.{{Citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nWhen [[Sherman Andrus]] left the Disciples to join [[the Imperials]] he was replaced by singer [[Danniebelle Hall]]. More musicians were being added and the group's membership by the early 1970s included Fletch Wiley on trumpet, Harlan Rogers on keyboards, Hadley Hockensmith on guitar, and Bill Maxwell on drums.<ref name=\"Carpenter, Bil 2005, page 107\"/> The group appeared on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]'' in 1972<ref name=\"Carpenter, Bil 2005, page 107\"/> and to sold-out crowds at [[Carnegie Hall]] in 1975 and 1979.<ref name=\"LA Times obit\">{{cite web | url=http://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-andrae-crouch-20150109-story.html | title=Andrae Crouch, Grammy-winning gospel singer and pioneer, dies at 72 | publisher=Los Angeles Times | date=January 8, 2015 | accessdate=January 9, 2015 | author=Steve Chawkins}}</ref> By 1985 they had also performed at the [[Hollywood Bowl]] and toured 68 countries.{{Citation needed|date=January 2015}} Crouch's most popular songs from this period include \"The Blood Will Never Lose Its Power\", \"Through It All\", \"Bless His Holy Name\", \"Soon and Very Soon\", \"Jesus is the Answer\", and \"My Tribute\".\n\n=== Solo career ===\n\nAfter The Disciples disbanded in 1979, Crouch continued on with a solo career. His backing ensemble included Howard Smith, Linda McCrary, [[T\u00e1ta Vega]], and [[Kristle Murden]], along with The Andra\u00e9 Crouch Singers. [[Joe Sample]], Wilton Felder, Dean Parks, [[David Paich]], [[Phillip Bailey]], [[Stevie Wonder]], [[El DeBarge]], and other secular artists were included in Crouch's recording sessions. With former Disciples drummer-turned-producer Bill Maxwell, Crouch co-produced projects for [[The Winans]], Danniebelle Hall, and Kristle Murden. Many musical acts and solo performers covered his more popular works, including [[Elvis Presley]] with ''I've Got Confidence''. In 1986, Crouch composed the theme music for the [[Sherman Hemsley]] sitcom ''[[Amen (TV series)|Amen]]'', sung by [[Vanessa Bell Armstrong]].\n\nIn 2006 Crouch released ''[[Mighty Wind]]'', a 40th anniversary album featuring guest performances by [[Lauren Evans]], [[Crystal Lewis]], [[Karen Clark Sheard]], T\u00e1ta Vega, and [[Marvin Winans]].\n\n=== Influence ===\n\nCrouch has been credited as a key figure in [[Jesus music]] of the 1960s and 1970s and, as a result, helping to bring about [[contemporary Christian music]] into the church.<ref name=\"NYT Obit, influence\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2015/01/08/us/ap-us-obit-andrae-crouch.html | title=Andrae Crouch, Legendary Gospel Figure, Dies at 72 | work=New York Times | date=January 9, 2015 | accessdate=January 10, 2015 | agency=Associated Press}}</ref> As well, he is also credited with helping to bridge the gap between black and white [[Christian music]] and revolutionizing the sound of [[urban Gospel]] music. Though sometimes criticized for diluting the Christian message by using contemporary music styles, his songs have become staples in churches and hymnals around the world and have been recorded by mainstream artists such as Elvis Presley and [[Paul Simon]].<ref name=\"CM_Vol_51\"/>\n\nHis affiliation with Light Records was instrumental in bringing Walter and [[Tramaine Hawkins]], [[Jessy Dixon]] and [[The Winans]] to the label, from where they all enjoyed successful gospel music careers.<ref name=\"L. Michael Gipson\">{{cite web | url=http://www.soultracks.com/story-andre-crouch-dies | title=Gospel legend Andrae Crouch dies at age 72 | publisher=Soul Tracks | date=January 9, 2015 | accessdate=January 10, 2015 | author=L. Michael Gipson}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Crouch and his music were honored on the [[Grammy Award]]-winning CD, ''Tribute: The Songs of Andra\u00e9 Crouch'', released by Warner Bros. Records. The album featured a wide range of artists performing Crouch's classic songs and featured [[Brooklyn Tabernacle Choir|the Brooklyn Tabernacle Choir]], [[Take 6]], [[Twila Paris]], and [[Michael W. Smith]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.religionnews.com/2015/01/09/contemporary-gospel-music-pioneer-andrae-crouch-dead-72/ | title=Contemporary gospel music pioneer Andrae Crouch dead at 72 | publisher=Religion News Service | date=January 9, 2015 | accessdate=January 10, 2015 | author=Adelle M. Banks}}</ref>\n\nCrouch and his sister Sandra had a friendship and music relationship with [[Michael Jackson]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.christiantoday.com/article/gospel.artists.say.they.did.not.lead.michael.jackson.to.christ/23735.htm | title=Gospel artists say they did not lead Michael Jackson to Christ | publisher=Christian Today | date=July 4, 2009 | accessdate=January 10, 2015}}</ref> In 1987, the Andra\u00e9 Crouch Choir sang background vocals along with [[Siedah Garrett]] and [[The Winans]] on Jackson's hit single \"[[Man in the Mirror]]\" from the ''[[Bad (album)|Bad]]'' album. The Andra\u00e9 Crouch Singers were also featured on the songs \"Keep the Faith\" and \"[[Will You Be There]]\" from Jackson's 1991 ''[[Dangerous (Michael Jackson album)|Dangerous]]'' album. On Jackson's ''[[HIStory: Past, Present and Future, Book I]]'' project in 1995, the Andra\u00e9 Crouch Choir is heard on \"[[Earth Song]].\" They are also heard on \"Morphine\" from ''HIStory'''s remix album ''[[Blood on the Dance Floor: HIStory in the Mix]]'', and one last time on \"[[Speechless (Michael Jackson song)|Speechless]]\" from the ''[[Invincible (Michael Jackson album)|Invincible]]'' album. Crouch's composition, \"Soon and Very Soon\" was performed by the Andra\u00e9 Crouch Choir at the public memorial service for Jackson held at the [[Staples Center]] in Los Angeles on July 7, 2009.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/08/us/08jackson.html | title=At Jackson Memorial, Music and Mourning | work=New York Times | date=July 7, 2009 | accessdate=January 10, 2015 | author=Randal C. Archibold}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nOn November 12, 1982, Crouch was arrested in Los Angeles for possession of cocaine after being stopped for erratic driving. Sheriff's deputies discovered a substance in the vehicle which Crouch said was instant chicken soup powder. After consenting to a search, he was found to be carrying a vial of cocaine in his pocket. Crouch was arrested and released several hours later on $2,500 bail, maintaining the drugs belonged to a friend who had been staying in his apartment. Police declined to press charges.<ref>{{cite news|author =UPI |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/11/15/us/police-arrest-gospel-singer-on-drug-possession-charge.html |title=Police Arrest Gospel Singer on Drug Possession Charge |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=November 15, 1982 |accessdate=October 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.todayschristianmusic.com/artists/andrae-crouch/features/the-ccm-interview-andrae-crouch/ |title=The CCM Interview: Andrae Crouch |publisher=CCM Magazine |accessdate=June 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130624183641/http://www.todayschristianmusic.com/artists/andrae-crouch/features/the-ccm-interview-andrae-crouch/ |archivedate=June 24, 2013  }}</ref>\n\nBetween 1993 and 1994, Crouch suffered the loss of his father, mother, and older brother.<ref name=\"CM_Vol_51\"/> After his father's death, Crouch and his sister took over the shared duty of senior pastor at the church his parents founded, Christ Memorial [[Church of God in Christ]] in [[Pacoima, California]].<ref name=\"CM_Vol_51\">{{cite book |author1=Manheim, James M. |author2=Belfiore, Michael |editor=Pilchak, Angela M. |title=Contemporary Musicians |series=Volume 51 |year=2005 |publisher=[[Gale Group]] |location=[[Farmington Hills]], [[Michigan]] |issn=1044-2197 |isbn=0-7876-8064-8 |chapter=Andra\u00e9 Crouch |pages=[https://archive.org/details/contemporarymusi0051unse/page/27 27\u201329] |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/contemporarymusi0051unse/page/27 }}</ref><ref name=\"New Christ Memorial COGIC\">{{cite web | url=http://newchristmemorial.org/pastors.html | title=Our Pastors | publisher=New Christ Memorial Church of God in Christ | accessdate=January 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Failing health and death ===\n\nCrouch survived a number of personal attacks from four different forms of cancer, which claimed the life of his mother, father and brother in 1993 and 1994. He was also hospitalized for complications from diabetes in his last few years of life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/01/08/reports-gospel-legend-andrae-crouch-dead-at-72/|title=Gospel legend Andrae Crouch dead at 72|first1=Fred|last1=Barbash|first2=Soraya Nadia|last2=McDonald|date=January 8, 2015|accessdate=June 17, 2018|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.cbn.com/music/andrae-crouch|title=Andrae Crouch|website=CBN.com - The Christian Broadcasting Network|accessdate=June 17, 2018}}</ref>  In early December 2014, Crouch was hospitalized for pneumonia and congestive heart failure. As a result, his December 2014 tour was postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2014/12/andrae_crouch_hospitalized_tri.html|title=Andrae Crouch hospitalized; tribute tour postponed to 2015, including show in Birmingham|publisher=AL.com|accessdate=January 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Death\" /> He was hospitalized again on January 3, 2015, in Los Angeles, as the result of a heart attack.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/11/arts/music/andra-crouch-72-who-infused-gospel-with-soul-dies.html| title=Andra\u00e9 Crouch, 72, Who Infused Gospel With Soul, Dies| work=New York Times | date=January 9, 2015 | accessdate=November 8, 2016 | author=Bruce Weber}}</ref>\n\nOn January 8, 2015, Crouch died at Northridge Hospital Medical Center.<ref name=\"LA Times obit\"/><ref name=\"Death\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2015/01/08/andrae-crouch-gospel-music-pioneer-dies/21262183/|title=Gospel music pioneer Andra\u00e9 Crouch dies at 72|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref> He was 72. On the same day, his sister, Sandra, released the following statement: \"Today my twin brother, womb-mate and best friend went home to be with the Lord. Please keep me, my family and our church family in your prayers. I tried to keep him here but God loved him best.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ktla.com/2015/01/08/legendary-gospel-artist-andrae-crouch-dies-at-72/ | title=Legendary Gospel Artist Andrae Crouch Dies at 72 | publisher=KTLA 5 | date=January 8, 2015 | accessdate=January 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Crouch's death, Christian recording artist [[Michael W. Smith]] told [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'' Magazine]], \"...I'll never forget hearing Andra\u00e9 for the first time. It was like someone had opened a whole new world of possibilities for me musically. I don't think there is anyone who inspired me more, growing up, than Andra\u00e9 Crouch. The depth of his influence on Christian music is incalculable. We all owe him so much and I'll forever be grateful for the times we got to work together.\"<ref name=\"Billboard Mag Remembering Crouch\">{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6436383/andrae-crouch-remembering-gospel-great-influence | title=R.I.P. Andrae Crouch: Remembering the Gospel Great's Immense Influence | publisher=Billboard Magazine | date=January 8, 2015 | accessdate=January 10, 2015 | author=Deborah Evans Price}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{main|Andra\u00e9 Crouch discography}}\n\n=== Andra\u00e9 Crouch and The Disciples ===\n\n* 1968: ''[[Take the Message Everywhere]]'' (Light)\n* 1971: ''[[Keep on Singin']]'' (Light)\n* 1972: ''Soulfully'' (Light)\n* 1973: ''Live at Carnegie Hall'' (Light)\n* 1975: ''[[Take Me Back (Andrae Crouch album)|Take Me Back]]'' (Light)\n* 1976: ''[[This Is Another Day]]'' (Light)\n* 1978: ''[[Live in London (Andra\u00e9 Crouch album)|Live in London]]'' (Light)\n\n=== Solo recordings ===\n\n* 1973: ''Just Andrae'' (Light)\n* 1979: ''[[I'll Be Thinking of You]]'' (Light)\n* 1981: ''Don't Give Up'' (Warner Bros.)\n* 1982: ''Finally'' (Light)\n* 1984: ''No Time to Lose'' (Light)\n* 1986: ''Autograph'' (Light)\n* 1994: ''Mercy'' (Qwest)\n* 1997: ''Pray'' (Qwest)\n* 1998: ''Gift of Christmas'' (Qwest)\n* 2006: ''[[Mighty Wind]]'' (Verity)\n* 2011: ''The Journey'' (Riverphlo Entertainment)\n* 2013: ''Live in Los Angeles''\n\n=== Other credits ===\n\nCrouch later worked as a producer or arranger with [[Michael Jackson]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Quincy Jones]], [[Mika (singer)|Mika]] (''We Are Golden''), [[Diana Ross]], [[Elton John]], [[Rick Astley]] (\"[[Cry for Help]]\") and [[Prefab Sprout]]. Crouch also had a long relationship with the [[Oslo Gospel Choir]], which he occasionally produced, arranged <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Oslo-Gospel-Choir-Get-Up/release/7169517|title=Oslo Gospel Choir - Get Up!|website=Discogs|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref> for and performed with.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Oslo-Gospel-Choir-Live-In-Paris/release/2760070|title=Oslo Gospel Choir - Live In Paris|website=Discogs|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n\nCrouch won numerous awards throughout his career that included seven [[Grammy Award]]s<ref name=\"L. Michael Gipson\"/> and four [[GMA Dove Awards]]. He was also the recipient of [[ASCAP]], ''[[Billboard Music Award|Billboard]]'', and [[NAACP]] Awards.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}} In 2004, he became the only living [[gospel music|Gospel]] artist \u2013 and just the third in history \u2013 to have a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nOn November 11, 2011, Sandra and Andrae Crouch were granted an honorary \"Artist-in-Residence\" Award by the International Center of Worship for Global Day of Worship Regent University, Virginia Beach, VA.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Graham|first1=Efrem|title=Gospel Legend Andra\u00e9 Crouch Dies|url=http://www.cbn.com/cbnnews/us/2015/January/Gospel-Legend-Andrae-Crouch-Dies/|publisher=Christian Broadcasting Network|accessdate=January 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Grammy Awards ===\n\nCrouch has won seven [[Grammy Award|Grammys]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=Andra%C3%A9+Crouch&title=&year=All&genre=All |title=Grammy Awards won by Andra\u00e9 Crouch |publisher=Grammy.com |date= |accessdate=October 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\n* 1975: Best Soul Gospel Performance \u2013 ''Take Me Back''\n* 1978: Best Contemporary Soul Gospel Album \u2013 ''Live in London''\n* 1979: Best Contemporary Soul Gospel Album \u2013 ''I'll Be Thinking of You''\n* 1980: Best Gospel Performance, Contemporary or Inspirational \u2013 \"The Lord's Prayer\" (collaborative)\n* 1981: Best Contemporary Soul Gospel Album \u2013 ''Don't Give Up''\n* 1984: Best Soul Gospel Performance, Male \u2013 \"Always Remember\"\n* 1994: Best Pop/Contemporary Gospel Album \u2013 ''Mercy''\n\n=== GMA Dove Awards ===\n\n* ''Soul/Black gospel album''\n** 1977 \u2013 ''This is another day''(Light)\n** 1978 \u2013 ''Live in London'' (Light)\n* ''Contemporary gospel album of the year''\n** 1985 \u2013 ''No Time to Lose'' (Light)\n** 1998 \u2013 ''Pray'' (Qwest/Warner Bros.)\n* ''Traditional gospel album of the year''\n** 1993 \u2013 ''With all of my heart''; Sandra Crouch and Friends (Sparrow)\n* ''Contemporary gospel recorded song of the year''\n** 1997 \u2013 \"Take me back\"; Tribute \u2013 The Songs of Andrae Crouch (songwriter) (Warner Alliance)\n* Inducted into the Gospel Music Association's [[Gospel Music Hall of Fame]] in 1998\n\n=== Other honors ===\n\n* 1985: [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] nomination for music compositions featured in ''[[The Color Purple]]''\n* 1997: Honorary Doctorate of Music from [[Berklee College of Music]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.berklee.edu/news/1790/doc-watson-receives-honorary-doctorate|title=Doc Watson Receives Honorary Doctorate - Berklee College of Music|website=www.berklee.edu|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref>\n* 2005: NARAS' Inaugural Salute to Gospel Music Lifetime Achievement Award recipient\n* 2007: Christian Music Hall of Fame and Museum inductee\n* 2012: How Sweet the Sound Living Legend Award\n\n=== Filmography ===\n\n; Film:\n* 1985: ''[[The Color Purple (1985 film)|The Color Purple]]'' songwriter: \"Maybe God's Trying to Tell You Something\"\n* 1993: ''[[Once Upon a Forest]]'' songwriter: \"He's Gone/He's Back\"\n* 1994:'' [[The Lion King]]'' arranger and choral conductor\n; Television:\n* 1980: ''[[Barbara Mandrell and the Mandrell Sisters#Acting career|Barbara Mandrell & The Mandrell Sisters]]'' special guest\n* 1982: ''[[The Jeffersons]]'' \"Men of the Cloth\" episode\n* 1982: ''[[Second City Television|SCTV Network 90]]'' Christmas special\n* 1986: ''[[Amen (TV series)|Amen]]'' theme writer, arranger\n* 1994: ''[[In Search of Dr. Seuss]]'' as [[Yertle the Turtle]]\n* 1998: [[Nickelodeon]]'s ''[[Cousin Skeeter]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Facebook|andraecrouch}}\n* {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p51905|label=Andra\u00e9 Crouch}}\n* {{IMDb name|189428}}\n\n{{Andra\u00e9 Crouch}}\n{{Black church}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crouch, Andrae}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Christians]]\n[[Category:African-American Christians]]\n[[Category:African-American male singers]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:African-American pianists]]\n[[Category:American organists]]\n[[Category:American gospel singers]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Church of God in Christ pastors]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Pentecostals from California]]\n[[Category:Qwest Records artists]]\n[[Category:Singers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist \n| name             = Andra\u00e9 Crouch\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Andra\u00e9 Crouch cropped.JPG\n| caption          = Crouch in Stavanger, Norway in 2008\n| birth_name       = Andra\u00e9 Edward Crouch\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1942|7|1}}\n| birth_place      = [[San Francisco]], California, U.S.\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2015|1|8|1942|7|1}}\n| death_place      = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S.\n| genre            = [[Gospel music|Gospel]], [[Contemporary Christian music|contemporary Christian]]\n| occupation       = Singer, songwriter, arranger, record producer, choir director, pastor\n| instrument       = Vocals, piano, organ\n| years_active     = 1966\u20132014\n| label            = [[Light Records|Light]], [[Qwest Records|Qwest]]/[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]], [[Verity Records|Verity]]/[[Jive Records|Jive]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Sandra Crouch]], [[T\u00e1ta Vega]], [[Danniebelle Hall]], [[Kristle Murden]]\n| website          = {{Facebook|andraecrouch}}\n| <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n}}\n\n'''Andra\u00e9 Edward Crouch''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0251\u02d0|n|d|r|e\u026a}} (July 1, 1942&nbsp;\u2013 January 8, 2015) was an American [[Gospel music|gospel]] singer, songwriter, arranger, record producer and pastor. Referred to as \"the father of modern gospel music\" by [[Contemporary Christian Music|contemporary Christian]] and gospel music professionals,<ref>{{cite web|title=Andra\u00e9 Crouch, 'father of modern gospel music', dies|url=https://www.usatoday.com/videos/life/music/2015/01/09/21503643/|publisher=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=January 10, 2015}}</ref> Crouch was known for his compositions \"The Blood Will Never Lose Its Power\", \"My Tribute (To God Be the Glory)\" and \"Soon and Very Soon\". He collaborated on some of his recordings with artists, such as [[Stevie Wonder]], [[El DeBarge]], [[Philip Bailey]], [[Chaka Khan]], [[Sheila E.]] and vocal group [[Take 6]], and many recording artists covered his material, including, [[Bob Dylan]], [[Barbara Mandrell]], [[Paul Simon]], [[Elvis Presley]] and [[Little Richard]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2015/01/08/showbiz/andrae-crouch-obit/index.html|title=Gospel music legend Andrae Crouch dies |author1=Ed Payne |author2=Steve Almasy|publisher=CNN|accessdate=June 17, 2018}}</ref> In the 1980s and 1990s, he was known as the \"go to\" producer for superstars who sought a gospel choir sound in their recordings, appearing on a number of recordings, including [[Michael Jackson]]'s \"[[Man In the Mirror]]\", [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]'s \"[[Like a Prayer (song)|Like a Prayer]]\", and \"The Power\", a duet between [[Elton John]] and [[Little Richard]].<ref name=\"Brian Mansfield\">{{cite web | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2015/01/08/andrae-crouch-gospel-music-pioneer-dies/21262183/ | title=Gospel music pioneer Andra\u00e9 Crouch dies at 72 | publisher=USA Today | date=January 8, 2015 | accessdate=January 8, 2015 | author=Brian Mansfield}}</ref> Crouch was noted for his talent of incorporating contemporary secular music styles into the gospel music he grew up with. His efforts in this area helped pave the way for early American contemporary Christian music during the 1960s and 1970s.<ref name=\"Variety obit\">{{cite web | url=https://variety.com/2015/music/people-news/obituaries-people-news/gospel-music-legend-andrae-crouch-dies-at-72-1201396451/ | title=Gospel Music Legend Andrae Crouch Dies at 72 | publisher=Variety | date=January 8, 2015 | accessdate=January 9, 2015 |author1=Andrew Barker |author2=Senior Features Writer }}</ref>\n\nCrouch's original music arrangements were heard in the films ''[[The Color Purple (film)|The Color Purple]]'', for which he received an Oscar nomination, and Disney's ''[[The Lion King]]'', as well as the [[NBC]] television series ''[[Amen (TV series)|Amen]]''. Awards and honors received by him include seven [[Grammy Award]]s, induction into the Gospel Music Hall of Fame in 1998, and a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].<ref name=\"Variety obit\"/>\n\n== Early years ==\n\nAndra\u00e9 Edward Crouch was born, along with his twin sister, [[Sandra Crouch|Sandra]], on July 1, 1942, in San Francisco, California<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.tributes.com/obituary/read/Andra%C3%A9-Crouch-102052107 | title=Andrae Crouch Obituary | publisher=The Associated Press | accessdate=April 5, 2015 | author=Rober Jablon}}</ref> to parents Benjamin and Catherine (n\u00e9e Hodnett) Crouch.<ref name=\"CM_Vol_51\"/> His father was a minister in the Church of God in Christ ([[COGIC]]) and pastored Christ Memorial Church of God in Christ in Pacoima, California. When he was young, Crouch's parents owned and operated Crouch Cleaners, a dry-cleaning business, as well as a restaurant business in [[Los Angeles]], California.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-04-11/local/me-291_1_sandra-crouch | title=Catherine D. Crouch; Singers' Mother | publisher=Los Angeles Times | date=April 11, 1992 | accessdate=January 8, 2015}}</ref> In addition to running the family's businesses, Crouch's parents also had a Christian street-preaching ministry and a hospital and prison ministry.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://articles.latimes.com/1993-12-23/local/me-4746_1_christ-memorial-church | title=Benjamin Crouch; Church Founder | publisher=Los Angeles Times | date=December 23, 1993 | accessdate=January 8, 2015}}</ref> When Crouch was 11, his father was invited to speak for several weeks at a small church as a guest preacher. Crouch's father and the church's congregation encouraged the young boy to play during the services. At the piano, Crouch found the key in which the congregation was singing and started to play. After this, Crouch honed his piano-playing skills and, in time, wanted to write his own music. When he was 14 years old, he wrote his first Gospel song.<ref name=\"Brian Mansfield\"/><ref name=\"Booth, John D. 1974, p. 3\">Booth, John D., The Music of Andrae Crouch and the Disciples. Masters of Church Music, New Orelans Baptist Theological Seminary, 1974, p. 3</ref><ref name=\"Carpenter, Bil 2005, page 107\">Carpenter, Bil. Uncloudy Days: The Gospel Music Encyclopedia, {{ISBN|978-0-87930-841-4}}, Backbeat Books, San Francisco, 2005, page 107</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Groups ===\n\nCrouch's first group musical effort was formed in 1960 as the Church of God in Christ Singers. The group included future recording artist and session musician [[Billy Preston]] on keyboards<ref name=\"CM_Vol_51\"/> and was the first to record Crouch's song \"The Blood Will Never Lose Its Power\". The song's popularity grew following the initial 1969 recording, becoming a standard in churches and hymnals worldwide.<ref name=\"Variety obit\"/> While attending [[Los Angeles Valley College|Valley Junior College]] in the San Fernando Valley to become a teacher, he formed gospel music group \"The Disciples\" in 1965 with fellow musicians Perry Morgan, Reuben Fernandez, and Bili Thedford.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gmahalloffame.org/site/andrae-crouch/ | title=Andre Crouch Biography | publisher=Gospel Music Association Hall of Fame | accessdate=January 9, 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150109234121/http://www.gmahalloffame.org/site/andrae-crouch/ | archivedate=January 9, 2015 | df=mdy-all }}</ref> The group became a frequent attraction at \"Monday Night Sing\" concerts in southern California put on by Audrey Mieir, a Christian minister and music composer who frequently sponsored new Christian music groups.<ref name=\"Carpenter, Bil 2005, page 107\"/> Following Mieir's introduction of Crouch to [[Manna Music Inc|Manna Music Publishing's]] founders Tim and Hal Spencer, Manna published Crouch's song \"The Blood Will Never Lose Its Power\", written when he was 15 years old. The Spencers helped launch Crouch's recording career by introducing them to [[Light Records]] founder and prolific Christian songwriter [[Ralph Carmichael]]. After the addition of [[Sherman Andrus]] to The Disciples, Light Records recorded and released the group's first album, ''Take the Message Everywhere'', in 1968.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MXNMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA57&lpg=PA57&q=andrae%20crouch%20Mieir%20tim%20spencer | title=This is My Story: 146 of the World's Greatest Gospel Singers | publisher=Thomas Nelson | work=This Is My Story: 146 of the World's Greatest Gospel Singers; Andrae Crouch | date=September 26, 2005 | accessdate=January 9, 2015 | author=Thomas Nelson | pages=57| isbn=9780529110329 }}</ref> Following the group's first album release, Crouch's twin sister, Sandra, joined The Disciples in 1970 after Fernandez' departure. Two more albums would follow, ''Keep On Singin{{'}}'' and ''Soulfully'', before a major change in the group's lineup in 1972.{{Citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nWhen [[Sherman Andrus]] left the Disciples to join [[the Imperials]] he was replaced by singer [[Danniebelle Hall]]. More musicians were being added and the group's membership by the early 1970s included Fletch Wiley on trumpet, Harlan Rogers on keyboards, Hadley Hockensmith on guitar, and Bill Maxwell on drums.<ref name=\"Carpenter, Bil 2005, page 107\"/> The group appeared on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]'' in 1972<ref name=\"Carpenter, Bil 2005, page 107\"/> and to sold-out crowds at [[Carnegie Hall]] in 1975 and 1979.<ref name=\"LA Times obit\">{{cite web | url=http://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-andrae-crouch-20150109-story.html | title=Andrae Crouch, Grammy-winning gospel singer and pioneer, dies at 72 | publisher=Los Angeles Times | date=January 8, 2015 | accessdate=January 9, 2015 | author=Steve Chawkins}}</ref> By 1985 they had also performed at the [[Hollywood Bowl]] and toured 68 countries.{{Citation needed|date=January 2015}} Crouch's most popular songs from this period include \"The Blood Will Never Lose Its Power\", \"Through It All\", \"Bless His Holy Name\", \"Soon and Very Soon\", \"Jesus is the Answer\", and \"My Tribute\".\n\n=== Solo career ===\n\nAfter The Disciples disbanded in 1979, Crouch continued on with a solo career. His backing ensemble included Howard Smith, Linda McCrary, [[T\u00e1ta Vega]], and [[Kristle Murden]], along with The Andra\u00e9 Crouch Singers. [[Joe Sample]], Wilton Felder, Dean Parks, [[David Paich]], [[Phillip Bailey]], [[Stevie Wonder]], [[El DeBarge]], and other secular artists were included in Crouch's recording sessions. With former Disciples drummer-turned-producer Bill Maxwell, Crouch co-produced projects for [[The Winans]], Danniebelle Hall, and Kristle Murden. Many musical acts and solo performers covered his more popular works, including [[Elvis Presley]] with ''I've Got Confidence''. In 1986, Crouch composed the theme music for the [[Sherman Hemsley]] sitcom ''[[Amen (TV series)|Amen]]'', sung by [[Vanessa Bell Armstrong]].\n\nIn 2006 Crouch released ''[[Mighty Wind]]'', a 40th anniversary album featuring guest performances by [[Lauren Evans]], [[Crystal Lewis]], [[Karen Clark Sheard]], T\u00e1ta Vega, and [[Marvin Winans]].\n\n=== Influence ===\n\nCrouch has been credited as a key figure in [[Jesus music]] of the 1960s and 1970s and, as a result, helping to bring about [[contemporary Christian music]] into the church.<ref name=\"NYT Obit, influence\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2015/01/08/us/ap-us-obit-andrae-crouch.html | title=Andrae Crouch, Legendary Gospel Figure, Dies at 72 | work=New York Times | date=January 9, 2015 | accessdate=January 10, 2015 | agency=Associated Press}}</ref> As well, he is also credited with helping to bridge the gap between black and white [[Christian music]] and revolutionizing the sound of [[urban Gospel]] music. Though sometimes criticized for diluting the Christian message by using contemporary music styles, his songs have become staples in churches and hymnals around the world and have been recorded by mainstream artists such as Elvis Presley and [[Paul Simon]].<ref name=\"CM_Vol_51\"/>\n\nHis affiliation with Light Records was instrumental in bringing Walter and [[Tramaine Hawkins]], [[Jessy Dixon]] and [[The Winans]] to the label, from where they all enjoyed successful gospel music careers.<ref name=\"L. Michael Gipson\">{{cite web | url=http://www.soultracks.com/story-andre-crouch-dies | title=Gospel legend Andrae Crouch dies at age 72 | publisher=Soul Tracks | date=January 9, 2015 | accessdate=January 10, 2015 | author=L. Michael Gipson}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Crouch and his music were honored on the [[Grammy Award]]-winning CD, ''Tribute: The Songs of Andra\u00e9 Crouch'', released by Warner Bros. Records. The album featured a wide range of artists performing Crouch's classic songs and featured [[Brooklyn Tabernacle Choir|the Brooklyn Tabernacle Choir]], [[Take 6]], [[Twila Paris]], and [[Michael W. Smith]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.religionnews.com/2015/01/09/contemporary-gospel-music-pioneer-andrae-crouch-dead-72/ | title=Contemporary gospel music pioneer Andrae Crouch dead at 72 | publisher=Religion News Service | date=January 9, 2015 | accessdate=January 10, 2015 | author=Adelle M. Banks}}</ref>\n\nCrouch and his sister Sandra had a friendship and music relationship with [[Michael Jackson]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.christiantoday.com/article/gospel.artists.say.they.did.not.lead.michael.jackson.to.christ/23735.htm | title=Gospel artists say they did not lead Michael Jackson to Christ | publisher=Christian Today | date=July 4, 2009 | accessdate=January 10, 2015}}</ref> In 1987, the Andra\u00e9 Crouch Choir sang background vocals along with [[Siedah Garrett]] and [[The Winans]] on Jackson's hit single \"[[Man in the Mirror]]\" from the ''[[Bad (album)|Bad]]'' album. The Andra\u00e9 Crouch Singers were also featured on the songs \"Keep the Faith\" and \"[[Will You Be There]]\" from Jackson's 1991 ''[[Dangerous (Michael Jackson album)|Dangerous]]'' album. On Jackson's ''[[HIStory: Past, Present and Future, Book I]]'' project in 1995, the Andra\u00e9 Crouch Choir is heard on \"[[Earth Song]].\" They are also heard on \"Morphine\" from ''HIStory'''s remix album ''[[Blood on the Dance Floor: HIStory in the Mix]]'', and one last time on \"[[Speechless (Michael Jackson song)|Speechless]]\" from the ''[[Invincible (Michael Jackson album)|Invincible]]'' album. Crouch's composition, \"Soon and Very Soon\" was performed by the Andra\u00e9 Crouch Choir at the public memorial service for Jackson held at the [[Staples Center]] in Los Angeles on July 7, 2009.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/08/us/08jackson.html | title=At Jackson Memorial, Music and Mourning | work=New York Times | date=July 7, 2009 | accessdate=January 10, 2015 | author=Randal C. Archibold}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\nOn November 12, 1982, Crouch was arrested in Los Angeles for possession of cocaine after being stopped for erratic driving. Sheriff's deputies discovered a substance in the vehicle which Crouch said was instant chicken soup powder. After consenting to a search, he was found to be carrying a vial of cocaine in his pocket. Crouch was arrested and released several hours later on $2,500 bail, maintaining the drugs belonged to a friend who had been staying in his apartment. Police declined to press charges.<ref>{{cite news|author =UPI |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/11/15/us/police-arrest-gospel-singer-on-drug-possession-charge.html |title=Police Arrest Gospel Singer on Drug Possession Charge |publisher=NYTimes.com |date=November 15, 1982 |accessdate=October 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.todayschristianmusic.com/artists/andrae-crouch/features/the-ccm-interview-andrae-crouch/ |title=The CCM Interview: Andrae Crouch |publisher=CCM Magazine |accessdate=June 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130624183641/http://www.todayschristianmusic.com/artists/andrae-crouch/features/the-ccm-interview-andrae-crouch/ |archivedate=June 24, 2013  }}</ref>\n\nBetween 1993 and 1994, Crouch suffered the loss of his father, mother, and older brother.<ref name=\"CM_Vol_51\"/> After his father's death, Crouch and his sister took over the shared duty of senior pastor at the church his parents founded, Christ Memorial [[Church of God in Christ]] in [[Pacoima, California]].<ref name=\"CM_Vol_51\">{{cite book |author1=Manheim, James M. |author2=Belfiore, Michael |editor=Pilchak, Angela M. |title=Contemporary Musicians |series=Volume 51 |year=2005 |publisher=[[Gale Group]] |location=[[Farmington Hills]], [[Michigan]] |issn=1044-2197 |isbn=0-7876-8064-8 |chapter=Andra\u00e9 Crouch |pages=[https://archive.org/details/contemporarymusi0051unse/page/27 27\u201329] |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/contemporarymusi0051unse/page/27 }}</ref><ref name=\"New Christ Memorial COGIC\">{{cite web | url=http://newchristmemorial.org/pastors.html | title=Our Pastors | publisher=New Christ Memorial Church of God in Christ | accessdate=January 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Failing health and death ===\n\nCrouch survived a number of personal attacks from four different forms of cancer, which claimed the life of his mother, father and brother in 1993 and 1994. He was also hospitalized for complications from diabetes in his last few years of life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/01/08/reports-gospel-legend-andrae-crouch-dead-at-72/|title=Gospel legend Andrae Crouch dead at 72|first1=Fred|last1=Barbash|first2=Soraya Nadia|last2=McDonald|date=January 8, 2015|accessdate=June 17, 2018|via=www.washingtonpost.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.cbn.com/music/andrae-crouch|title=Andrae Crouch|website=CBN.com - The Christian Broadcasting Network|accessdate=June 17, 2018}}</ref>  In early December 2014, Crouch was hospitalized for pneumonia and congestive heart failure. As a result, his December 2014 tour was postponed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2014/12/andrae_crouch_hospitalized_tri.html|title=Andrae Crouch hospitalized; tribute tour postponed to 2015, including show in Birmingham|publisher=AL.com|accessdate=January 4, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Death\" /> He was hospitalized again on January 3, 2015, in Los Angeles, as the result of a heart attack.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/11/arts/music/andra-crouch-72-who-infused-gospel-with-soul-dies.html| title=Andra\u00e9 Crouch, 72, Who Infused Gospel With Soul, Dies| work=New York Times | date=January 9, 2015 | accessdate=November 8, 2016 | author=Bruce Weber}}</ref>\n\nOn January 8, 2015, Crouch died at Northridge Hospital Medical Center.<ref name=\"LA Times obit\"/><ref name=\"Death\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/music/2015/01/08/andrae-crouch-gospel-music-pioneer-dies/21262183/|title=Gospel music pioneer Andra\u00e9 Crouch dies at 72|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref> He was 72. On the same day, his sister, Sandra, released the following statement: \"Today my twin brother, womb-mate and best friend went home to be with the Lord. Please keep me, my family and our church family in your prayers. I tried to keep him here but God loved him best.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ktla.com/2015/01/08/legendary-gospel-artist-andrae-crouch-dies-at-72/ | title=Legendary Gospel Artist Andrae Crouch Dies at 72 | publisher=KTLA 5 | date=January 8, 2015 | accessdate=January 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Crouch's death, Christian recording artist [[Michael W. Smith]] told [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'' Magazine]], \"...I'll never forget hearing Andra\u00e9 for the first time. It was like someone had opened a whole new world of possibilities for me musically. I don't think there is anyone who inspired me more, growing up, than Andra\u00e9 Crouch. The depth of his influence on Christian music is incalculable. We all owe him so much and I'll forever be grateful for the times we got to work together.\"<ref name=\"Billboard Mag Remembering Crouch\">{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6436383/andrae-crouch-remembering-gospel-great-influence | title=R.I.P. Andrae Crouch: Remembering the Gospel Great's Immense Influence | publisher=Billboard Magazine | date=January 8, 2015 | accessdate=January 10, 2015 | author=Deborah Evans Price}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{main|Andra\u00e9 Crouch discography}}\n\n=== Andra\u00e9 Crouch and The Disciples ===\n\n* 1968: ''[[Take the Message Everywhere]]'' (Light)\n* 1971: ''[[Keep on Singin']]'' (Light)\n* 1972: ''Soulfully'' (Light)\n* 1973: ''Live at Carnegie Hall'' (Light)\n* 1975: ''[[Take Me Back (Andrae Crouch album)|Take Me Back]]'' (Light)\n* 1976: ''[[This Is Another Day]]'' (Light)\n* 1978: ''[[Live in London (Andra\u00e9 Crouch album)|Live in London]]'' (Light)\n\n=== Solo recordings ===\n\n* 1973: ''Just Andrae'' (Light)\n* 1979: ''[[I'll Be Thinking of You]]'' (Light)\n* 1981: ''Don't Give Up'' (Warner Bros.)\n* 1982: ''Finally'' (Light)\n* 1984: ''No Time to Lose'' (Light)\n* 1986: ''Autograph'' (Light)\n* 1994: ''Mercy'' (Qwest)\n* 1997: ''Pray'' (Qwest)\n* 1998: ''Gift of Christmas'' (Qwest)\n* 2006: ''[[Mighty Wind]]'' (Verity)\n* 2011: ''The Journey'' (Riverphlo Entertainment)\n* 2013: ''Live in Los Angeles''\n\n=== Other credits ===\n\nCrouch later worked as a producer or arranger with [[Michael Jackson]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Quincy Jones]], [[Mika (singer)|Mika]] (''We Are Golden''), [[Diana Ross]], [[Elton John]], [[Rick Astley]] (\"[[Cry for Help]]\") and [[Prefab Sprout]]. Crouch also had a long relationship with the [[Oslo Gospel Choir]], which he occasionally produced, arranged <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Oslo-Gospel-Choir-Get-Up/release/7169517|title=Oslo Gospel Choir - Get Up!|website=Discogs|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref> for and performed with.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Oslo-Gospel-Choir-Live-In-Paris/release/2760070|title=Oslo Gospel Choir - Live In Paris|website=Discogs|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n\nCrouch won numerous awards throughout his career that included seven [[Grammy Award]]s<ref name=\"L. Michael Gipson\"/> and four [[GMA Dove Awards]]. He was also the recipient of [[ASCAP]], ''[[Billboard Music Award|Billboard]]'', and [[NAACP]] Awards.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}} In 2004, he became the only living [[gospel music|Gospel]] artist \u2013 and just the third in history \u2013 to have a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nOn November 11, 2011, Sandra and Andrae Crouch were granted an honorary \"Artist-in-Residence\" Award by the International Center of Worship for Global Day of Worship Regent University, Virginia Beach, VA.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Graham|first1=Efrem|title=Gospel Legend Andra\u00e9 Crouch Dies|url=http://www.cbn.com/cbnnews/us/2015/January/Gospel-Legend-Andrae-Crouch-Dies/|publisher=Christian Broadcasting Network|accessdate=January 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Grammy Awards ===\n\nCrouch has won seven [[Grammy Award|Grammys]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=Andra%C3%A9+Crouch&title=&year=All&genre=All |title=Grammy Awards won by Andra\u00e9 Crouch |publisher=Grammy.com |date= |accessdate=October 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\n* 1975: Best Soul Gospel Performance \u2013 ''Take Me Back''\n* 1978: Best Contemporary Soul Gospel Album \u2013 ''Live in London''\n* 1979: Best Contemporary Soul Gospel Album \u2013 ''I'll Be Thinking of You''\n* 1980: Best Gospel Performance, Contemporary or Inspirational \u2013 \"The Lord's Prayer\" (collaborative)\n* 1981: Best Contemporary Soul Gospel Album \u2013 ''Don't Give Up''\n* 1984: Best Soul Gospel Performance, Male \u2013 \"Always Remember\"\n* 1994: Best Pop/Contemporary Gospel Album \u2013 ''Mercy''\n\n=== GMA Dove Awards ===\n\n* ''Soul/Black gospel album''\n** 1977 \u2013 ''This is another day''(Light)\n** 1978 \u2013 ''Live in London'' (Light)\n* ''Contemporary gospel album of the year''\n** 1985 \u2013 ''No Time to Lose'' (Light)\n** 1998 \u2013 ''Pray'' (Qwest/Warner Bros.)\n* ''Traditional gospel album of the year''\n** 1993 \u2013 ''With all of my heart''; Sandra Crouch and Friends (Sparrow)\n* ''Contemporary gospel recorded song of the year''\n** 1997 \u2013 \"Take me back\"; Tribute \u2013 The Songs of Andrae Crouch (songwriter) (Warner Alliance)\n* Inducted into the [[Gospel Music Association]]'s [[Gospel Music Hall of Fame]] in 1998\n\n=== Other honors ===\n\n* 1985: [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] nomination for music compositions featured in ''[[The Color Purple]]''\n* 1997: Honorary Doctorate of Music from [[Berklee College of Music]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.berklee.edu/news/1790/doc-watson-receives-honorary-doctorate|title=Doc Watson Receives Honorary Doctorate - Berklee College of Music|website=www.berklee.edu|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref>\n* 2005: NARAS' Inaugural Salute to Gospel Music Lifetime Achievement Award recipient\n* 2007: Christian Music Hall of Fame and Museum inductee\n* 2012: How Sweet the Sound Living Legend Award\n\n=== Filmography ===\n\n; Film:\n* 1985: ''[[The Color Purple (1985 film)|The Color Purple]]'' songwriter: \"Maybe God's Trying to Tell You Something\"\n* 1993: ''[[Once Upon a Forest]]'' songwriter: \"He's Gone/He's Back\"\n* 1994:'' [[The Lion King]]'' arranger and choral conductor\n; Television:\n* 1980: ''[[Barbara Mandrell and the Mandrell Sisters#Acting career|Barbara Mandrell & The Mandrell Sisters]]'' special guest\n* 1982: ''[[The Jeffersons]]'' \"Men of the Cloth\" episode\n* 1982: ''[[Second City Television|SCTV Network 90]]'' Christmas special\n* 1986: ''[[Amen (TV series)|Amen]]'' theme writer, arranger\n* 1994: ''[[In Search of Dr. Seuss]]'' as [[Yertle the Turtle]]\n* 1998: [[Nickelodeon]]'s ''[[Cousin Skeeter]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n\n* {{Facebook|andraecrouch}}\n* {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p51905|label=Andra\u00e9 Crouch}}\n* {{IMDb name|189428}}\n\n{{Andra\u00e9 Crouch}}\n{{Black church}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Crouch, Andrae}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Christians]]\n[[Category:African-American Christians]]\n[[Category:African-American male singers]]\n[[Category:American male singers]]\n[[Category:African-American pianists]]\n[[Category:American organists]]\n[[Category:American gospel singers]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Church of God in Christ pastors]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Pentecostals from California]]\n[[Category:Qwest Records artists]]\n[[Category:Singers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:20th-century male singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Gospel Music Associationclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andra%C3%A9_Crouch"}
{"title_page": "Whitecross (band)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Other uses|Whitecross (disambiguation){{!}}White Cross}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Whitecross\n| image               = File:Whitecross-EoR2013-02.jpg\n| caption             = Whitecross in 2013\n| landscape           = yes\n| background          = group_or_band\n| genre               = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]], [[Christian metal]], [[hard rock]]\n| origin              = [[Waukegan, Illinois|Waukegan]], [[Illinois]], US\n| years_active        = 1985\u2013present\n| label               = Pure Metal, [[Star Song Records|Star Song]]\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = \n| current_members     =\n* Scott Wenzel\n* [[Rex Carroll]]\n* Michael Feighan\n* Benny Ramos\n| past_members        = \n}}\n\n'''Whitecross''' is an American [[Christian metal]] band from Illinois, formed in 1985 by singer Scott Wenzel and guitarist [[Rex Carroll]], and re-formed in 2000. The band won three [[Dove Award]]s in the 1990s. Its latest album is [[Nineteen Eighty Seven]], released in 2005.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Whitecross-EoR2013-01.jpg|thumb|upright=.8|Scott Wenzel on stage in 2013]]\nWhitecross formed in 1985 in [[Waukegan, Illinois]], releasing their first recording in 1987. Their early albums, which often invite comparisons to [[Ratt]], are laced with fast, technical [[electric guitar|guitar]] work. In 1994, Rex Carroll split with lead vocalist Scott Wenzel. Wenzel retained the use of the name \"Whitecross\" while Carroll went on to form King James with Jimi Bennett (see below). At this point the band's sound underwent a drastic change.\n\nWhitecross has won three [[Dove Award]]s with ''Triumphant Return'' (in 1990) and ''In the Kingdom'' (in 1992) winning \"Metal Album of the Year\"<ref name=\"DOVE_HM\">{{cite web |url=http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?cid=31 |title=Dove Award Recipients for Hard Music Album |accessdate=March 12, 2007 |publisher=Gospel Music Association |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061020022738/http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?cid=31 |archivedate=October 20, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and ''Come unto the Light'' from the ''Unveiled'' album winning \"Hard Music Recorded Song of the Year\" at the [[25th GMA Dove Awards]] in 1994.<ref name=\"DOVE_95\">{{cite web |url=http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?year=1995 |title=Dove Award Recipients for 1995 |accessdate=March 12, 2007 |publisher=Gospel Music Association |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311040429/http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?year=1995 |archivedate=March 11, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 1994 prior to work starting on the ''Unveiled'' album, guitarist Rex Carroll left to form the band [[King James (band)|King James]] and pursue other musical ventures. In 1998, singer Scott Wenzel took a two-year break to do [[missionary|mission]] work in Paraguay, [[South America]]. During this time, Whitecross went on hiatus before re-emerging at Cornerstone Festival in 2000 when Carroll and Wenzel re-formed the band with Carroll, Wenzel, Michael Feighan and newcomer [[Benny Ramos]] providing bass, keyboards and vocals. Finally having achieved a long-sought lineup stability, the band started performing on a regular basis.\n\nIn 2005, the band went back into the studio to record ''Nineteen Eighty Seven'', which featured re-recordings of nine of the ten songs from the band's self-titled debut album (''You're Mine'' being the exclusion), as well as a re-recording of the song ''Love on the Line'' (previously unavailable on CD) and a new guitar instrumental by Rex Carroll.\n\nOn April 5, 2008, they played at the [[Legends of Rock]] festival in [[Ennepetal]], Germany. Beginning in July 2008, they played the first of several short tours in Guatemala featuring shows in [[Guatemala City]], [[Panajachel]], [[Huehuetenango]] and other cities.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\nIn 2017, Carroll and Feighan joined with David Bach and [[Jamie Rowe]] of [[Guardian (band)|Guardian]] to record ''Revival'', a new compilation of Whitecross and Guardian tracks and went on a short tour to promote the project. <ref>{{cite web|title=Guardian + Whitecross - About |url= https://guardianwhitecross.com/about |website= guardianwhitecross.com |accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Albums==\n\n===With Rex Carroll===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=40% align=\"left\"|Album\n!width=20% align=\"left\"|Year\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Whitecross (album)|Whitecross]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1987\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Love on the Line (EP)]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1988\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Hammer & Nail]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1988\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Triumphant Return]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1989\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[In the Kingdom]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1991\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[High Gear (Whitecross album)|High Gear]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1992\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Nineteen Eighty Seven]]''\n|align=\"center\"|2005\n|}\n\n===Without Rex Carroll===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=40% align=\"left\"|Album\n!width=20% align=\"left\"|Year\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Unveiled (Whitecross album)|Unveiled]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1994\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Equilibrium (Whitecross album)|Equilibrium]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1995\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Flytrap (Whitecross album)|Flytrap]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1996\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''Unveiled'' (re-issue)\n|align=\"center\"|2005\n|}\n\n===Compilations===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=40% align=\"left\"|Album\n!width=20% align=\"left\"|Year\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''At Their Best''\n|align=\"center\"|1991\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''To the Limit''\n|align=\"center\"|1993\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''By Demand''\n|align=\"center\"|1995\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''One More Encore''\n|align=\"center\"|1998\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''Mega 3 Collection''\n|align=\"center\"|2005\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''The Very Best of Whitecross''\n|align=\"center\"|2006\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''Their Classic Hits''\n|align=\"center\"|2009\n|}\n\n==Videos==\n*[[The Reign Goes On]] - 45 minute [[VHS]], 1992 [[Star Song Communications]] (extremely rare)\n\n==Members of Whitecross==\n\n; Current\n* Scott Wenzel \u2013 lead vocals (1985\u2013present)\n* [[Rex Carroll]] \u2013 guitar, vocals (1985\u20131993, 2000\u2013present)\n* Michael Feighan \u2013 drums, vocals (1991\u20131995, 2000\u2013present)\n* [[Benny Ramos]] \u2013 bass guitar, vocals (2000\u2013present)\n\n; Former\n;Guitars\n*Barry Graul ([[MercyMe]]) (1994\u20131995)\n*Quinton Gibson (1996)\n\n; Drums\n*Mark Hedl (1987\u20131988)\n*Mike Elliott (1989)\n*Troy Stone (1996)\n\n; bass guitar\n*Jon Sproule (1987\u20131988)\n*Rick Armstrong (1989)\n*Butch Dillon (1991)\n*Scott Harper (1992\u20131993)\n*[[Tracy Ferrie]] (1994\u20131995)\n*Brent Denny (1996)\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| width=\"10%\" |\n! width=\"10%\" |''[[Whitecross (album)|Whitecross]]''\n! width=\"10%\" |''[[Hammer & Nail]]''\n! width=\"10%\" |''[[Triumphant Return]]''\n! width=\"10%\" |''[[In the Kingdom]]''\n! width=\"10%\" |''[[High Gear (Whitecross album)|High Gear]]''\n! width=\"10%\" |''[[Unveiled (Whitecross album)|Unveiled]]''\n! width=\"10%\" |''[[Equilibrium (Whitecross album)|Equilibrium]]''\n! width=\"10%\" |''[[Flytrap (Whitecross album)|Flytrap]]''\n! width=\"10%\" |''[[Nineteen Eighty Seven]]''\n|-\n! Vocals\n| colspan=\"9\" | Scott Wenzel\n|-\n! Guitars\n| colspan=\"5\" | Rex Carroll\n| colspan=\"2\" | Barry Graul\n| Quinton Gibson\n| Rex Carroll\n|-\n! Drums\n| colspan=\"2\" | Mark Hedl\n| Mike Elliott\n| colspan=\"4\" | Mike Feighan\n| Troy Stone\n| Mike Feighan\n|-\n! Bass\n| colspan=\"2\" | Jon Sproule\n| Rick Armstrong\n| Butch Dillon\n| Scott Harper\n| colspan=\"2\" | Tracy Ferrie \t\n| Brent Denny\n| Rex Carroll\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Contemporary Christian music]]\n*[[Glam metal]]\n*[[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite book |last=Powell |first=Mark Allan |title=Encyclopedia of Contemporary Christian Music |year=2002 |publisher=Hendrickson Publishers |location=[[Peabody, Massachusetts|Peabody]], [[Massachusetts]] |isbn=1-56563-679-1 |edition=First printing |pages=[https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofco00mark/page/1030 1030\u20131033] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofco00mark/page/1030 }}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100503042704/http://www.shoutlife.com/whitecrossmusic Whitecross @ ShoutLife Tribute]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100430224626/http://www.shoutlife.com/scottwenzelmusic Scott Wenzel @ ShoutLife Tribute]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060816070159/http://www.allium-sativum.com/c2k2/Whitecross/content.html Pictures from the reunion gig at Cornerstone 2002] archived copy taken March 4, 2006\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040630133650/http://www.80sretromusic.com/biography/W/whitecross.htm Brief Whitecross biography]\n\n{{Whitecross}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:American Christian metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Christian rock groups from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal musical groups from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1985]]\n[[Category:1985 establishments in Illinois]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Other uses|Whitecross (disambiguation){{!}}White Cross}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Whitecross\n| image               = File:Whitecross-EoR2013-02.jpg\n| caption             = Whitecross in 2013\n| landscape           = yes\n| background          = group_or_band\n| genre               = [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]], [[Christian metal]], [[hard rock]]\n| origin              = [[Waukegan, Illinois|Waukegan]], [[Illinois]], US\n| years_active        = 1985\u2013present\n| label               = Pure Metal, [[Star Song Records|Star Song]]\n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = \n| current_members     =\n* Scott Wenzel\n* [[Rex Carroll]]\n* Michael Feighan\n* Benny Ramos\n| past_members        = \n}}\n\n'''Whitecross''' is an American [[Christian metal]] band from Illinois, formed in 1985 by singer Scott Wenzel and guitarist [[Rex Carroll]], and re-formed in 2000. The band won three [[Dove Award]]s in the 1990s. Its latest album is [[Nineteen Eighty Seven]], released in 2005.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Whitecross-EoR2013-01.jpg|thumb|upright=.8|Scott Wenzel on stage in 2013]]\nWhitecross formed in 1985 in [[Waukegan, Illinois]], releasing their first recording in 1987. Their early albums, which often invite comparisons to [[Ratt]], are laced with fast, technical [[electric guitar|guitar]] work. In 1994, Rex Carroll split with lead vocalist Scott Wenzel. Wenzel retained the use of the name \"Whitecross\" while Carroll went on to form King James with Jimi Bennett (see below). At this point the band's sound underwent a drastic change.\n\nWhitecross has won three [[Dove Award]]s with ''Triumphant Return'' (in 1990) and ''In the Kingdom'' (in 1992) winning \"Metal Album of the Year\"<ref name=\"DOVE_HM\">{{cite web |url=http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?cid=31 |title=Dove Award Recipients for Hard Music Album |accessdate=March 12, 2007 |publisher=[[Gospel Music Association]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061020022738/http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?cid=31 |archivedate=October 20, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and ''Come unto the Light'' from the ''Unveiled'' album winning \"Hard Music Recorded Song of the Year\" at the [[25th GMA Dove Awards]] in 1994.<ref name=\"DOVE_95\">{{cite web |url=http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?year=1995 |title=Dove Award Recipients for 1995 |accessdate=March 12, 2007 |publisher=[[Gospel Music Association]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070311040429/http://www.doveawards.com/history/browse.cfm?year=1995 |archivedate=March 11, 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 1994 prior to work starting on the ''Unveiled'' album, guitarist Rex Carroll left to form the band [[King James (band)|King James]] and pursue other musical ventures. In 1998, singer Scott Wenzel took a two-year break to do [[missionary|mission]] work in Paraguay, [[South America]]. During this time, Whitecross went on hiatus before re-emerging at Cornerstone Festival in 2000 when Carroll and Wenzel re-formed the band with Carroll, Wenzel, Michael Feighan and newcomer [[Benny Ramos]] providing bass, keyboards and vocals. Finally having achieved a long-sought lineup stability, the band started performing on a regular basis.\n\nIn 2005, the band went back into the studio to record ''Nineteen Eighty Seven'', which featured re-recordings of nine of the ten songs from the band's self-titled debut album (''You're Mine'' being the exclusion), as well as a re-recording of the song ''Love on the Line'' (previously unavailable on CD) and a new guitar instrumental by Rex Carroll.\n\nOn April 5, 2008, they played at the [[Legends of Rock]] festival in [[Ennepetal]], Germany. Beginning in July 2008, they played the first of several short tours in Guatemala featuring shows in [[Guatemala City]], [[Panajachel]], [[Huehuetenango]] and other cities.{{Citation needed|date=May 2011}}\n\nIn 2017, Carroll and Feighan joined with David Bach and [[Jamie Rowe]] of [[Guardian (band)|Guardian]] to record ''Revival'', a new compilation of Whitecross and Guardian tracks and went on a short tour to promote the project. <ref>{{cite web|title=Guardian + Whitecross - About |url= https://guardianwhitecross.com/about |website= guardianwhitecross.com |accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Albums==\n\n===With Rex Carroll===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=40% align=\"left\"|Album\n!width=20% align=\"left\"|Year\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Whitecross (album)|Whitecross]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1987\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Love on the Line (EP)]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1988\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Hammer & Nail]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1988\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Triumphant Return]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1989\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[In the Kingdom]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1991\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[High Gear (Whitecross album)|High Gear]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1992\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Nineteen Eighty Seven]]''\n|align=\"center\"|2005\n|}\n\n===Without Rex Carroll===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=40% align=\"left\"|Album\n!width=20% align=\"left\"|Year\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Unveiled (Whitecross album)|Unveiled]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1994\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Equilibrium (Whitecross album)|Equilibrium]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1995\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''[[Flytrap (Whitecross album)|Flytrap]]''\n|align=\"center\"|1996\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''Unveiled'' (re-issue)\n|align=\"center\"|2005\n|}\n\n===Compilations===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!width=40% align=\"left\"|Album\n!width=20% align=\"left\"|Year\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''At Their Best''\n|align=\"center\"|1991\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''To the Limit''\n|align=\"center\"|1993\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''By Demand''\n|align=\"center\"|1995\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''One More Encore''\n|align=\"center\"|1998\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''Mega 3 Collection''\n|align=\"center\"|2005\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''The Very Best of Whitecross''\n|align=\"center\"|2006\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|''Their Classic Hits''\n|align=\"center\"|2009\n|}\n\n==Videos==\n*[[The Reign Goes On]] - 45 minute [[VHS]], 1992 [[Star Song Communications]] (extremely rare)\n\n==Members of Whitecross==\n\n; Current\n* Scott Wenzel \u2013 lead vocals (1985\u2013present)\n* [[Rex Carroll]] \u2013 guitar, vocals (1985\u20131993, 2000\u2013present)\n* Michael Feighan \u2013 drums, vocals (1991\u20131995, 2000\u2013present)\n* [[Benny Ramos]] \u2013 bass guitar, vocals (2000\u2013present)\n\n; Former\n;Guitars\n*Barry Graul ([[MercyMe]]) (1994\u20131995)\n*Quinton Gibson (1996)\n\n; Drums\n*Mark 