p://www.shoutlife.com/scottwenzelmusic Scott Wenzel @ ShoutLife Tribute]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060816070159/http://www.allium-sativum.com/c2k2/Whitecross/content.html Pictures from the reunion gig at Cornerstone 2002] archived copy taken March 4, 2006\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040630133650/http://www.80sretromusic.com/biography/W/whitecross.htm Brief Whitecross biography]\n\n{{Whitecross}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:American Christian metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Christian rock groups from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal musical groups from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1985]]\n[[Category:1985 establishments in Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Gospel Music Associationclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whitecross_(band)"}
{"title_page": "WFSH-FM", "text_new": "{{short description|Contemporary Christian music radio station in Athens, Georgia, United States}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| image            = WFSHFM.png\n| name             = WFSH-FM\n| city             = [[Athens, Georgia]]\n| area             = [[Atlanta metropolitan area]]\n| branding         = 104.7 The Fish\n| slogan           = Safe for the Whole Family\n| frequency        = 104.7 [[Megahertz|MHz]]\n| airdate          = January 1964 (as WDOL-FM)\n| format           = [[Contemporary Christian music]]\n| erp              = 24,000 [[watt]]s\n| haat             = {{convert|505|m|ft|0|abbr=off}}\n| class            = C1\n| facility_id      = 56390\n| callsign_meaning ='''W''' '''F'''i'''SH''' (representing the Christian [[Ichthys]] symbol)\n| former_callsigns = WDOL-FM (1964-1970s) <BR>WJSR (1970s-1976)<br>WAGQ (1976-1989)<br>WALR (1989-1995)<br>[[WALR-FM]] (1995-2000)\n| owner            = [[Salem Media Group]]\n| licensee         = Salem Communications Holding Corporation\n| sister_stations  = [[WAFS (AM)|WAFS]], [[WDWD]], [[WGKA]], [[WLTA]], [[WNIV]]\n| webcast          = [http://saleminteractivemedia.com/ListenLive/Player/WFSHFM Listen Live]\n| website          = [http://www.thefishatlanta.com/ TheFishAtlanta.com]\n}}\n'''WFSH-FM''' (104.7 [[Hertz|MHz]]) is an [[FM radio|FM]] [[radio station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Athens, Georgia]], and serving [[Atlanta metropolitan area|Metro Atlanta]].  The station is owned by [[Salem Media Group]] and it airs a [[Christian contemporary]] [[radio format]].  It is branded as ''The Fish 104.7'' and describes itself as \"Safe For The Whole Family.\"  Between [[Thanksgiving (US)|Thanksgiving]] and the weekend after [[Christmas]], the station plays all [[Christmas music]], both religious and secular.\n\nWFSH-FM has its offices and [[radio studio]]s in the [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]] district of Atlanta.  The [[transmitter]] is on the tallest [[list of Atlanta broadcast stations by location|radio tower]] in Georgia, located off Piney Grove Road in [[Loganville, Georgia|Loganville]], about {{convert|30|mi|km|-1}} east of Atlanta.<ref>[https://radio-locator.com/cgi-bin/finder?call=wfsh&x=0&y=0&sr=Y&s=C Radio-Locator.com/WFSH-FM]</ref>  The [[height above average terrain]] (HAAT) of this tower allows the station to better penetrate [[office building]]s in Atlanta.  The [[effective radiated power]] (ERP) is 24,000 [[watt]]s.<ref>[https://transition.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/fmq?call=wfsh&arn=&state=&city=&freq=0.0&fre2=107.9&serv=&vac=&facid=&asrn=&class=&list=0&ThisTab=Results+to+This+Page%2FTab&dist=&dlat2=&mlat2=&slat2=&NS=N&dlon2=&mlon2=&slon2=&EW=W&size=9 FCC.gov/WFSH-FM]</ref>\n\n==Programming==\nWFSH-FM is one of three Christian Contemporary stations serving Metro Atlanta, along with 106.7 [[WAKL (FM)|WAKL]] and 93.3 [[WVFJ]].  Unlike its competitors, which are run by [[non-profit organization]]s and seek donations, WFSH-FM is a [[commercial radio]] station.  Salem uses \"The Fish\" as the moniker for several of its Christian Contemporary stations, including [[KFSH-FM|KFSH]] [[Los Angeles]], [[WFHM-FM]] [[Cleveland]] and [[WFFH]] [[Nashville]]. The fish, called the [[Ichthys]], was used as a symbol of the early [[Christian Church]].\n\n==History==\n===WDOL-FM and WJSR===\nIn January 1964, the station [[sign-on|signed on]] as '''WDOL-FM'''.<REF>[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1965/B-All-Radio-1965-YB-All.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1965 page B-39]</REF>  It was the FM counterpart of [[AM 1470]] WDOL (now [[WXAG]]).  Both stations were owned by James S. Rivers, who served as the president.  Because WDOL was a [[daytimer]],  WDOL-FM [[simulcast]]ed the AM station's [[country music]] format during the day and continued on its own after sunset when WDOL had to be off the air.  WDOL-FM was powered at only 3,500 watts, limiting its signal to Athens and adjacent communities, not hitting the larger Atlanta [[media market|radio market]]..\n\nIn the 1970s, the station got a boost to 50,000 watts.  As more people acquired FM radios, WDOL-FM switched its [[call sign]] to '''WJSR''' and aired a [[progressive rock]] format, while co-owned WDOL continued as a country outlet.\n\n===Top 40 WAGQ===\nIn 1976, WJSR was acquired by Broadcast Properties, Inc.<ref>[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1980/1980-BC-YB.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1980 page C-52]</ref>  The station flipped to [[contemporary hit radio|Top 40]] hits, as '''WAGQ''', and became an [[network affiliate|affiliate]] of the [[ABC News Radio|ABC Contemporary Network]]. Even though the station had a 50,000 watt signal on a 230 foot [[Radio masts and towers|tower]], it was still limited to serving Athens and its surrounding towns.\n\nIn the mid-1980s, WAGQ asked the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) for a [[construction permit]] to double its power to 100,000 watts and greatly increase its [[height above average terrain|antenna height]] to over 1,000 feet, using to a tower closer to Atlanta.  This would make WAGQ a \"move-in station,\" serving the more lucrative Atlanta market.  The FCC granted the request, making WAGQ a [[list of broadcast station classes|Class C1]] station.\n\n===Urban AC WALR===\nIn 1989, the station was sold to Ring Radio, Inc., which also owned [[WCNN]].<ref>[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1991/B-Radio-All-1991-B&W-3.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1991 page B-79]</ref>  \"Music Radio 104.7\" debuted, with a [[hot adult contemporary]] format.  The station switched its call sign to '''WALR''' in July 1990.\n\nOn October 8, 1990, [[WALR-FM]] was relaunched with an [[urban adult contemporary]] format as \"Love 104.7\", then later on as \"Kiss 104.7\".<ref>[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1990s/1990/RR-1990-10-19.pdf]</ref>  This was the second incarnation of the \"Kiss\" branding, after it was previously used in the mid-1980s on WEKS (the former call sign on 104.1).  Under this format, it was the first permanent competitor to attempt to chip away at the [[African-American]] audience enjoyed by heritage urban station [[WVEE (FM)|WVEE]].\n\n===Switching Frequencies===\nOn August 30, 2000, WALR and its adult urban format moved to 104.1, now known as \"Kiss 104.1,\" to make room for [[Christian Contemporary]] \"104.7 the Fish.\"  The swap was part of an asset exchange between [[Cox Media Group]] and [[Salem Communications]].\n\nWFSH-FM hosts \"Celebrate Freedom Atlanta\" each year on [[Labor Day (US)|Labor Day]] weekend.  The free outdoor [[concert]] features 15 to 20 artists and takes place at Jim R. Miller Park in [[Marietta, Georgia]].  The concert had an attendance of 42,000 its first year in 2007.\n\n==Personalities==\nWFSH-FM is unusual in having all weekday air shifts hosted by women [[disc jockey|DJ]]s.  The morning show is co-hosted by a man and a woman.\n\n*Kevin & Taylor mornings (since WFSH-FM's debut)\n*Parks Stamper middays (since WFSH-FM's debut)\n*Beth Bacall afternoons\n*Penny Faulkner evenings\n*Uncle Buck, Margaret Cheeley, Kim Fitz, Mark Harp and Curt Zehner weekends\n\n==Awards==\n*2002 Gospel Music Association \"Station of the Year\"\n*2002, 2003 and 2005 [[Georgia Association of Broadcasters]] \"Station of the Year\"\n*Kevin and Taylor in the Morning, 2003 and 2004 ''[[Radio and Records]]'' \"Personalities of the Year\"\n*Kevin and Taylor in the Morning, 2006 and 2007 ''[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' \"Best Morning Drive Show\"\n\n==Gallery==\nCelebrate Freedom concert on September 1, 2007.\n\n<center>\n<gallery>\nImage:Celebrate freedom 2007 main stand.jpg|Celebrate Freedom 2007 main stage.\nImage:Jumbotron with the Fish.jpg|The Jumbotron to the right of the main stage with The FISH banner.\nImage:The FISH booth - GIHP.jpg|An unidentified employee with the FISH at a booth at the Georgia International Horse Park during the concert.\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of radio stations in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thefishatlanta.com 104.7 The Fish]\n*{{FM station data|WFSH}}\n\n{{Athens Radio}}\n{{Atlanta Radio}}\n{{Religious Radio Stations in Georgia}}\n{{Salem Media Group}}\n\n{{coord|33.867|N|83.829|W|type:landmark_region:US_source:FCC|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Christian radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Contemporary Christian radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Athens, Georgia|FSH-FM]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1964]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Salem Media Group properties]]\n[[Category:Christian radio stations in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Contemporary Christian music radio station in Athens, Georgia, United States}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| image            = WFSHFM.png\n| name             = WFSH-FM\n| city             = [[Athens, Georgia]]\n| area             = [[Atlanta metropolitan area]]\n| branding         = 104.7 The Fish\n| slogan           = Safe for the Whole Family\n| frequency        = 104.7 [[Megahertz|MHz]]\n| airdate          = January 1964 (as WDOL-FM)\n| format           = [[Contemporary Christian music]]\n| erp              = 24,000 [[watt]]s\n| haat             = {{convert|505|m|ft|0|abbr=off}}\n| class            = C1\n| facility_id      = 56390\n| callsign_meaning ='''W''' '''F'''i'''SH''' (representing the Christian [[Ichthys]] symbol)\n| former_callsigns = WDOL-FM (1964-1970s) <BR>WJSR (1970s-1976)<br>WAGQ (1976-1989)<br>WALR (1989-1995)<br>[[WALR-FM]] (1995-2000)\n| owner            = [[Salem Media Group]]\n| licensee         = Salem Communications Holding Corporation\n| sister_stations  = [[WAFS (AM)|WAFS]], [[WDWD]], [[WGKA]], [[WLTA]], [[WNIV]]\n| webcast          = [http://saleminteractivemedia.com/ListenLive/Player/WFSHFM Listen Live]\n| website          = [http://www.thefishatlanta.com/ TheFishAtlanta.com]\n}}\n'''WFSH-FM''' (104.7 [[Hertz|MHz]]) is an [[FM radio|FM]] [[radio station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Athens, Georgia]], and serving [[Atlanta metropolitan area|Metro Atlanta]].  The station is owned by [[Salem Media Group]] and it airs a [[Christian contemporary]] [[radio format]].  It is branded as ''The Fish 104.7'' and describes itself as \"Safe For The Whole Family.\"  Between [[Thanksgiving (US)|Thanksgiving]] and the weekend after [[Christmas]], the station plays all [[Christmas music]], both religious and secular.\n\nWFSH-FM has its offices and [[radio studio]]s in the [[Buckhead (Atlanta)|Buckhead]] district of Atlanta.  The [[transmitter]] is on the tallest [[list of Atlanta broadcast stations by location|radio tower]] in Georgia, located off Piney Grove Road in [[Loganville, Georgia|Loganville]], about {{convert|30|mi|km|-1}} east of Atlanta.<ref>[https://radio-locator.com/cgi-bin/finder?call=wfsh&x=0&y=0&sr=Y&s=C Radio-Locator.com/WFSH-FM]</ref>  The [[height above average terrain]] (HAAT) of this tower allows the station to better penetrate [[office building]]s in Atlanta.  The [[effective radiated power]] (ERP) is 24,000 [[watt]]s.<ref>[https://transition.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/fmq?call=wfsh&arn=&state=&city=&freq=0.0&fre2=107.9&serv=&vac=&facid=&asrn=&class=&list=0&ThisTab=Results+to+This+Page%2FTab&dist=&dlat2=&mlat2=&slat2=&NS=N&dlon2=&mlon2=&slon2=&EW=W&size=9 FCC.gov/WFSH-FM]</ref>\n\n==Programming==\nWFSH-FM is one of three Christian Contemporary stations serving Metro Atlanta, along with 106.7 [[WAKL (FM)|WAKL]] and 93.3 [[WVFJ]].  Unlike its competitors, which are run by [[non-profit organization]]s and seek donations, WFSH-FM is a [[commercial radio]] station.  Salem uses \"The Fish\" as the moniker for several of its Christian Contemporary stations, including [[KFSH-FM|KFSH]] [[Los Angeles]], [[WFHM-FM]] [[Cleveland]] and [[WFFH]] [[Nashville]]. The fish, called the [[Ichthys]], was used as a symbol of the early [[Christian Church]].\n\n==History==\n===WDOL-FM and WJSR===\nIn January 1964, the station [[sign-on|signed on]] as '''WDOL-FM'''.<REF>[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1965/B-All-Radio-1965-YB-All.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1965 page B-39]</REF>  It was the FM counterpart of [[AM 1470]] WDOL (now [[WXAG]]).  Both stations were owned by James S. Rivers, who served as the president.  Because WDOL was a [[daytimer]],  WDOL-FM [[simulcast]]ed the AM station's [[country music]] format during the day and continued on its own after sunset when WDOL had to be off the air.  WDOL-FM was powered at only 3,500 watts, limiting its signal to Athens and adjacent communities, not hitting the larger Atlanta [[media market|radio market]]..\n\nIn the 1970s, the station got a boost to 50,000 watts.  As more people acquired FM radios, WDOL-FM switched its [[call sign]] to '''WJSR''' and aired a [[progressive rock]] format, while co-owned WDOL continued as a country outlet.\n\n===Top 40 WAGQ===\nIn 1976, WJSR was acquired by Broadcast Properties, Inc.<ref>[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1980/1980-BC-YB.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1980 page C-52]</ref>  The station flipped to [[contemporary hit radio|Top 40]] hits, as '''WAGQ''', and became an [[network affiliate|affiliate]] of the [[ABC News Radio|ABC Contemporary Network]]. Even though the station had a 50,000 watt signal on a 230 foot [[Radio masts and towers|tower]], it was still limited to serving Athens and its surrounding towns.\n\nIn the mid-1980s, WAGQ asked the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) for a [[construction permit]] to double its power to 100,000 watts and greatly increase its [[height above average terrain|antenna height]] to over 1,000 feet, using to a tower closer to Atlanta.  This would make WAGQ a \"move-in station,\" serving the more lucrative Atlanta market.  The FCC granted the request, making WAGQ a [[list of broadcast station classes|Class C1]] station.\n\n===Urban AC WALR===\nIn 1989, the station was sold to Ring Radio, Inc., which also owned [[WCNN]].<ref>[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1991/B-Radio-All-1991-B&W-3.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1991 page B-79]</ref>  \"Music Radio 104.7\" debuted, with a [[hot adult contemporary]] format.  The station switched its call sign to '''WALR''' in July 1990.\n\nOn October 8, 1990, [[WALR-FM]] was relaunched with an [[urban adult contemporary]] format as \"Love 104.7\", then later on as \"Kiss 104.7\".<ref>[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1990s/1990/RR-1990-10-19.pdf]</ref>  This was the second incarnation of the \"Kiss\" branding, after it was previously used in the mid-1980s on WEKS (the former call sign on 104.1).  Under this format, it was the first permanent competitor to attempt to chip away at the [[African-American]] audience enjoyed by heritage urban station [[WVEE (FM)|WVEE]].\n\n===Switching Frequencies===\nOn August 30, 2000, WALR and its adult urban format moved to 104.1, now known as \"Kiss 104.1,\" to make room for [[Christian Contemporary]] \"104.7 the Fish.\"  The swap was part of an asset exchange between [[Cox Media Group]] and [[Salem Communications]].\n\nWFSH-FM hosts \"Celebrate Freedom Atlanta\" each year on [[Labor Day (US)|Labor Day]] weekend.  The free outdoor [[concert]] features 15 to 20 artists and takes place at Jim R. Miller Park in [[Marietta, Georgia]].  The concert had an attendance of 42,000 its first year in 2007.\n\n==Personalities==\nWFSH-FM is unusual in having all weekday air shifts hosted by women [[disc jockey|DJ]]s.  The morning show is co-hosted by a man and a woman.\n\n*Kevin & Taylor mornings (since WFSH-FM's debut)\n*Parks Stamper middays (since WFSH-FM's debut)\n*Beth Bacall afternoons\n*Penny Faulkner evenings\n*Uncle Buck, Margaret Cheeley, Kim Fitz, Mark Harp and Curt Zehner weekends\n\n==Awards==\n*2002 [[Gospel Music Association]] \"Station of the Year\"\n*2002, 2003 and 2005 [[Georgia Association of Broadcasters]] \"Station of the Year\"\n*Kevin and Taylor in the Morning, 2003 and 2004 ''[[Radio and Records]]'' \"Personalities of the Year\"\n*Kevin and Taylor in the Morning, 2006 and 2007 ''[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' \"Best Morning Drive Show\"\n\n==Gallery==\nCelebrate Freedom concert on September 1, 2007.\n\n<center>\n<gallery>\nImage:Celebrate freedom 2007 main stand.jpg|Celebrate Freedom 2007 main stage.\nImage:Jumbotron with the Fish.jpg|The Jumbotron to the right of the main stage with The FISH banner.\nImage:The FISH booth - GIHP.jpg|An unidentified employee with the FISH at a booth at the Georgia International Horse Park during the concert.\n</gallery>\n</center>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of radio stations in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thefishatlanta.com 104.7 The Fish]\n*{{FM station data|WFSH}}\n\n{{Athens Radio}}\n{{Atlanta Radio}}\n{{Religious Radio Stations in Georgia}}\n{{Salem Media Group}}\n\n{{coord|33.867|N|83.829|W|type:landmark_region:US_source:FCC|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Christian radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Contemporary Christian radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Athens, Georgia|FSH-FM]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1964]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Salem Media Group properties]]\n[[Category:Christian radio stations in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Gospel Music Associationclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WFSH-FM"}
{"title_page": "Bible Belt", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Other uses|Bible Belt (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Bible Belt\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| settlement_type = Cultural region of the United States\n| image_flag =\n| flag_alt =\n| image_seal =\n| seal_alt =\n| image_shield =\n| shield_alt =\n| nickname =\n| motto =\n| image_map = File:BibleBelt.png\n| map_alt =\n| map_caption = The area roughly considered to constitute the Bible Belt\n| subdivision_type = Country\n| subdivision_name =\n| subdivision_type1 = Subregion\n| subdivision_type2 = Subregion\n| subdivision_type3 =\n| subdivision_name1 = \n| subdivision_type4  = Country\n| subdivision_name4  = {{flag|United States}}\n| subdivision_type5 = States\n| subdivision_name5 = {{flag|Alabama}}<br /> {{flag|Arkansas}}<br /> {{flag|Florida}}<br /> {{flag|Georgia (U.S. state)|name=Georgia}}<br /> {{flag|Kentucky}}<br /> {{flag|Louisiana}}<br /> {{flag|Mississippi}}<br /> {{flag|Missouri}}<br /> {{flag|North Carolina}}<br /> {{flag|Oklahoma}}<br /> {{flag|South Carolina}}<br /> {{flag|Tennessee}}<br /> {{flag|Texas}}<br /> {{flag|Virginia}}<br /> {{flag|West Virginia}}<br /> \nand parts of: \n{{flag|Illinois}}<br /> {{flag|Indiana}}<br /> {{flag|Ohio}}<br />\n}}\nThe '''Bible Belt''' is an informal region in the [[Southern United States]] in which [[Social conservatism|socially conservative]] [[Evangelicalism in the United States|evangelical Protestantism]] plays a strong role in society and politics, and [[church attendance]] across the denominations is generally higher than the nation's average.\n\nThe region contrasts with the religiously diverse [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]] and [[Great Lakes region|Great Lakes]], the [[Mormon Corridor]] in [[Utah]] and [[southern Idaho]], and the relatively [[Secularism|secular]] [[Western United States|Western]] and [[New England]] regions of the [[United States]]. Whereas the state with the highest percentage of residents identifying as non-religious is the New England state of [[Vermont]] at 37%, in the Bible Belt state of [[Alabama]] it is just 12%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/religious-tradition/unaffiliated-religious-nones/|title=The Unaffiliated|date=May 11, 2015|work=Pew Research Center's Religion & Public Life Project}}</ref> [[Tennessee]] has the highest proportion of Evangelical Protestants, at 52%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/state/tennessee/|title=Adults in Tennessee|date=May 11, 2015|work=Pew Research Center's Religion & Public Life Project}}</ref> The Evangelical influence is strongest in northern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Tennessee]], [[Alabama]], [[Mississippi]], [[North Carolina]], Southern and Western [[Virginia]], [[West Virginia]], [[South Carolina]], and almost all of [[Texas]].  \n\nThe earliest known usage of the term \"Bible Belt\" was by American journalist and social commentator [[H. L. Mencken]], who in 1924 wrote in the ''[[Chicago Tribune|Chicago Daily Tribune]]'': \"The old game, I suspect, is beginning to play out in the Bible Belt.\"<ref>Fred R. Shapiro (ed.). ''Yale Book of Quotations''. [[Yale University Press]] (2006). {{ISBN|978-0-300-10798-2}}.</ref> In 1927, Mencken claimed the term as his invention.<ref>[http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/images/detail/h-l-mencken-letter-to-charles-green-shaw-9819 H. L. Mencken letter to Charles Green Shaw, 1927 Dec. 2 .] Charles Green Shaw papers, Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution. See also, http://www.lettersofnote.com/2011/06/human-race-is-incurably-idiotic.html</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThe name \"Bible Belt\" has been applied historically to the South and parts of the Midwest, but is more commonly identified with the South. In a 1961 study, [[Wilbur Zelinsky]] delineated the region as the area in which Protestant denominations, especially Southern Baptist, Methodist, and evangelical, are the predominant religious affiliation. The region thus defined included most of the Southern United States, including most of [[Texas]] and [[Oklahoma]], and in the states south of the [[Ohio River]], and extending east to include central West Virginia and Virginia, from the [[Shenandoah Valley]] southward into [[Southside Virginia]] and [[North Carolina]]. In addition, the Bible Belt covers most of [[Missouri]] and [[Kentucky]] and southern parts of [[Illinois]], [[Indiana]], and [[Ohio]]. On the other hand, areas in the South which are ''not'' considered part of the Bible Belt include heavily Catholic Southern Louisiana, central and southern Florida, which have been settled mainly by immigrants and Americans from elsewhere in the country, and overwhelmingly Hispanic South Texas. A 1978 study by Charles Heatwole identified the Bible Belt as the region dominated by 24 fundamentalist Protestant denominations, corresponding to essentially the same area mapped by Zelinsky.<ref>Barry Vann (2008), ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=_cx6NMWOqKQC&pg=PA138&lpg=PA138&dq=bible+belt+charles+heatwole&source=bl&ots=s_3pBjUyyC&sig=58XbseF5_V9de4OW2ZOX34mqwTw&hl=en&ei=0Z8zS-zxDtWztgeb4Jj9CA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=13&ved=0CD4Q6AEwDA#v=onepage&q=bible%20belt%20charles%20heatwole&f=false In search of Ulster-Scots land: the birth and geotheological imagings of a transatlantic people, 1603-1703]'', Univ of South Carolina Press, {{ISBN|1-57003-708-6}}, {{ISBN|978-1-57003-708-5}}. Pages 138-140.</ref>\n\nAccording to Stephen W. Tweedie, an Associate Professor Emeritus in the Department of Geography at [[Oklahoma State University]], the Bible Belt is now viewed in terms of numerical concentration of the audience for religious television.<ref name=Carney_Fast_Food>{{cite book|last1=Carney|first1=edited by George O.|title=Fast food, stock cars and rock'n'roll: place and space in American pop culture|date=1995|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|location=Lanham|isbn=9780847680801|page=131|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aJnNasHzjN0C&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> He finds two belts: one more eastern that stretches from Florida, (excluding Miami, [[Tampa]] and South Florida), through [[Alabama]], [[Tennessee]], Kentucky, [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], the Carolinas, and into [[Southside Virginia]]; and another concentrated in Texas (excluding [[El Paso]], and [[South Texas]]), [[Arkansas]], [[Louisiana]], (excluding [[New Orleans]] and [[Acadiana]]), Oklahoma, Missouri (excluding [[St. Louis]]), [[Kansas]], and [[Mississippi]].<ref>Tweedie, S.W. (1978) Viewing the Bible Belt. [[Journal of Popular Culture]] 11; 865-76</ref>  \"[H]is research also broke the Bible Belt into two core regions, a western region and an eastern region. Tweedie's western Bible Belt was focused on a core that extended from Little Rock, Arkansas to Tulsa, Oklahoma. His eastern Bible Belt was focused on a core that included the major population centers of Virginia and North Carolina.<ref name=About_BibleBelt>{{cite news|last1=Rosenberg|first1=Matt|title=The Bible Belt Extends Throughout the American South (And Perhaps Beyond?)|url=http://geography.about.com/od/culturalgeography/fl/The-Bible-Belt.htm|accessdate=June 11, 2015|agency=About Education|publisher=About.com|ref=Rosenberg}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bible-minded Cities map.PNG|thumb|Bible-minded cities map]]\nA study was commissioned by the [[American Bible Society]] to survey the importance of the Bible in the metropolitan areas of the United States. The report was based on 42,855 interviews conducted between 2005 and 2012. It determined the 10 most \"Bible-minded\" cities were [[Knoxville, Tennessee]]; [[Shreveport, Louisiana]]; [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]]; [[Birmingham, Alabama]]; [[Jackson, Mississippi]]; [[Springfield, Missouri]]; [[Charlotte, North Carolina]]; [[Lynchburg, Virginia]]; [[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville-Decatur, Alabama]]; and [[Charleston, West Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cities.barna.org/americas-most-and-least-bible-minded-cities/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328095729/http://cities.barna.org/americas-most-and-least-bible-minded-cities/|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 28, 2013|title=America's Most and Least Bible-Minded Cities|accessdate=July 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the South, there is a smaller Bible Belt in [[West Michigan]], centered on the heavily Dutch-influenced cities of [[Holland, Michigan|Holland]] and [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]]. Christian colleges in that region include [[Calvin College]], [[Hope College]], [[Cornerstone University]], [[Grace Bible College]], and [[Kuyper College]]. West Michigan is generally fiscally and socially conservative.\n\n=== By state ===\n[[File:Importance of Religion in the United States of America.svg|thumb|350px|Percentage of respondents in the USA stating that religion is \"very important\" or \"somewhat important\" to their lives, 2014<ref name=\"Pew\"/>]]\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\n|+ Proportion of Evangelical Protestants per state in the [[American South]]<ref>https://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/state/</ref>|| \n|-\n!State !! Baptist !! Pentecostal !! Restorationist !! Presbyterian !! Other !! Total !! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:1px;\" style=\"background:grey;\"| !! valign=\"top\"|Share indicating that<br />religion is \"important\"<ref name=\"Pew\">[http://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/state/alabama/#importance-of-religion-by-state Importance of religion by state] Pew forum (sum of \"very important\" and \"something important\")</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Alabama}} || 31% || 5% || 3% || 2% || 8% || '''49%''' || class=\"unsortable\" rowspan=\"18\" style=\"width:1px;\" style=\"background:grey;\"| || 90%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Arkansas}} || 25% || 5% || 5% || 2% || 9% || '''46%''' || 86%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Delaware}} || 7% || 1% || 3% || 1% || 3% || '''15%''' || 77%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|District of Columbia|name=Washington, D.C.}} || 2% || 1% || 1% || 1% || 3% || '''8%''' || 71%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Florida}} || 8% || 4% || 2% || 1% || 9% || '''24%''' || 78%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Georgia (U.S. state)|name=Georgia}} || 21% || 4% || 2% || 1% || 10% || '''38%''' || 84%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Kentucky}} || 29% || 7% || 3% || 1% || 9% || '''49%''' || 86%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Louisiana}} || 16% || 3% || 1% || <1% || 7% || '''27%''' || 90%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Maryland}} || 5% || 3% || 1% || <1% || 9% || '''18%''' || 75%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Mississippi}} || 26% || 4% || 2% || 1% || 8% || '''41%''' || 89% \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Missouri}} || 15% || 6% || 3% || 1% || 11% || '''36%''' || 82% \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|North Carolina}} || 20% || 4% || 1% || 1% || 9% || '''35%''' || 84%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Oklahoma}} || 23% || 6% || 4% || <1% || 14% || '''47%''' || 87%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|South Carolina}} || 22% || 4% || 1% || 1% || 7% || '''35%''' || 85%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Tennessee}} || 33% || 4% || 6% || 2% || 7% || '''52%''' || 89%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Texas}} || 14% || 4% || 2% || <1% || 11% || '''31%''' || 86%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Virginia}} || 15% || 5% || <1% || 1% || 9% || '''30%''' || 81%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|West Virginia}} || 19% || 7% || 2% || <1% || 11% || '''39%''' || 86%\n|}\n\n==History==\nDuring the [[Thirteen Colonies|colonial period]] (1607\u20131776), the South was a stronghold of the [[Church of England|Anglican church]]. Its transition to a stronghold of non-Anglican Protestantism occurred gradually over the next century as a series of religious revival movements, many associated with the Baptist denomination, gained great popularity in the region.<ref name=Jeynes>{{cite book|last1=Murray|first1=William H. Jeynes ; foreword by William J.|title=A call for character education and prayer in the schools|date=2009|publisher=Praeger|location=Santa Barbara, Calif.|isbn=978-0313351044|pages=122\u2013123|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VmlFCQAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIt seems a link between the colonial Bible Belt (the North, especially [[New England]] with its Puritan heritage) and the later Southern Bible Belt may be seen in the impact which some Northern figures had on the religious development of the South (perhaps not incomparable to the origins of [[Mormonism]] in the North, in spite of its later association with [[Utah]]). \"The centre of Particular Baptist activity in early America was in the [[Middle Colonies]]. In 1707 five churches in New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Delaware were united to form the Philadelphia Baptist Association, and through the association they embarked upon vigorous missionary activity. By 1760 the Philadelphia association included churches located in the present states of Connecticut, New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Delaware, Virginia, and West Virginia; and by 1767 further multiplication of churches had necessitated the formation of two subsidiary associations, the Warren in New England and the Ketochton in Virginia. The Philadelphia association also provided leadership in organizing the Charleston Association in the Carolinas in 1751.\"<ref name=\"Britannica\">{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Baptist|title=Baptist - History, Beliefs, Denominations, & Facts|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref> \n\nAn influential figure was [[Shubal Stearns]]: \"Shubael Stearns, a New England Separate Baptist, migrated to Sandy Creek, North Carolina, in 1755 and initiated a revival that quickly penetrated the entire Piedmont region. The churches he organized were brought together in 1758 to form the Sandy Creek Association\".<ref name=\"Britannica\" /> Stearns was brother-in-law of Daniel Marshall, who was born in Windsor, Connecticut and \"is generally considered the first great Baptist leader in Georgia. He founded Kiokee Baptist Church, the oldest continuing Baptist congregation in the state\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/arts-culture/daniel-marshall-1706-1784|title=Daniel Marshall (1706-1784) - New Georgia Encyclopedia|publisher=}}</ref> Also, Wait Palmer, of Toland, Connecticut,<ref name=\"Sobel\">{{cite book|title=Trabelin' on: The Slave Journey to an Afro-Baptist Faith|last=Sobel|first=Mechal|url=https://archive.org/details/trabelinonslavej0000sobe|url-access=registration|year=1988|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=0691006032}}</ref>{{rp|84 - 85}} may have influenced African American Christianity in the South: \"The Silver Bluff, South Carolina, revival was a seminal development, whose role among blacks rivalled that played by the Sandy Creek revival of the Separate Baptists, to which it was indirectly related. It was probably the same Wait Palmer who had baptized Shubal Stearns in 1751 who came to Silver Bluff in 1775, baptizing and constituting a church. Abraham Marshall, who encouraged the later offshoots, was a Separate Baptist of the Sandy Creek school. The revival at the Silver Bluff plantation of George Galphin (some twelve miles from Augusta, Georgia) had brought David George to the Afro-Baptist faith and had provided a ministry for [[George Liele]]\".<ref name=\"Sobel\" />{{rp|188}} \n\nAccording to Thomas S. Kidd, \"As early as 1758, Sandy Creek missionaries helped organize a slave congregation, the Bluestone Church, on the plantation of William Byrd III, which may have been the first independently functioning African American church in North America. The church did not last long, but it reflected the Baptists' commitment to evangelizing African Americans\".<ref>{{cite book|title=The Great Awakening: The Roots of Evangelical Christianity in Colonial America|last=Kidd|first=Thomas S.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xPCrZa70--AC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=2007|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0300148251}}</ref>{{rp|249}} According to Gayraud S. Wilmore, \"The preaching of New England Congregationalists such as Jonathan Edwards about the coming millennium, and his conviction that Christians were called to prepare for it, reached the slaves through the far-ranging missionary work of white evangelists such as Shubal Stearns, Wait Palmer, and Matthew Moore - all of whom left Congregationalism and became Separatist Baptist preachers in the plantation country of Virginia, North and South Carolina, and Georgia\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Pragmatic Spirituality: The Christian Faith through an Africentric Lens|last=Wilmore|first=Gayraud S.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4Wy_DAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=2004|publisher=New York University Press|isbn=9781479884247}}</ref>{{rp|168}}\n\n==Buckle==\n[[File:Go to church....jpg|thumb|A billboard near the center of [[Alabama]] ]]\n\nSeveral locations are occasionally referred to as \"the Buckle of the Bible Belt\":\n*[[Abilene, Texas]] a city of 117,000, is home to three Protestant universities: the Baptist affiliated [[Hardin-Simmons University]], the Church of Christ's [[Abilene Christian University]], and Methodist founded [[McMurry University]].<ref name=\"encyclopedia of the great plains\">{{cite web|url=http://plainshumanities.unl.edu/encyclopedia/doc/egp.ct.002|title=Encyclopedia of the Great Plains - ABILENE, TEXAS|work=unl.edu|accessdate=March 27, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Nashville, Tennessee]], sometimes referred to as \"the Protestant Vatican\",<ref>{{cite book|title=Insiders' Guide to Nashville|first1=Cindy Stooksbury|last1=Guier|first2=Jackie Sheckler|last2=Finch|year=2007|edition=6th|pages=13, 35, 396}}</ref> has over 700 churches,<ref name=\"nashcity1\">{{cite web |url=http://nashcity.com/religious-institutions/christian-churches/index.shtml |title=Nashville Area Churches |work=NashCity.com |accessdate=April 30, 2008}}</ref> several seminaries, and a number of Christian schools, colleges and universities, including [[Belmont University]], [[Trevecca Nazarene University]], [[Lipscomb University]], [[Free Will Baptist Bible College]] and [[American Baptist College]]. Nashville is the seat of the [[National Baptist Convention, USA]], the headquarters of the [[Southern Baptist Convention]], the [[National Association of Free Will Baptists]], the [[Gideons International]], the Gospel Music Association, and [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]], the world's largest producer of Bibles.<ref name=\"road&travel\">{{cite web |url=http://www.roadandtravel.com/travel%20directory/Tennessee/nashvillestory.htm |title=Nashville: Sophisticated Southern City with a Country Edge |work=RoadandTravel.com |first=Rachel L |last=Miller |date=April 14, 2008 |accessdate=April 30, 2008}}</ref>\n*[[Tulsa, Oklahoma]] is a city where Protestant and, in particular, [[Southern Baptist]] and other [[evangelical]] Christian traditions are very prominent. Tulsa is home to [[Oral Roberts University]], and [[RHEMA Bible Training Center|RHEMA Bible Training College]] (in [[Broken Arrow, Oklahoma|Broken Arrow]]). A number of prominent Protestant Christians have lived or studied in Tulsa, including [[Joel Osteen]], [[Kenneth E. Hagin]], [[Carlton Pearson]], [[Kenneth Copeland]], [[Billy Joe Daugherty]], [[Smokie Norful]] and [[Billy James Hargis]]. Tulsa is also home to a number of vibrant [[Mainline Protestant]] congregations. Some of these congregations were founded during the oil boom of the early twentieth century and their facilities are noted for striking architecture, such as the art deco [[Boston Avenue Methodist Church]] and [[First Presbyterian Church (Tulsa)|First Presbyterian Church of Tulsa]].\n*[[Greenville, South Carolina]] is a city where many Baptist, particularly [[Independent Baptists]] are located.  Greenville has 124 Baptist churches<ref>\"Churches in Greenville\"> https://www.churchangel.com/WEBSC/greenville.htm</ref> in the Greenville area, as well as [[Bob Jones University]]. It also is the home of WTBI radio station which plays old-fashioned [[Christian Music]] and preaching 24 hours a day.\n\n==Political and cultural context==\nThere has been research that links evangelical Protestantism with social conservatism.<ref>http://www.allacademic.com/meta/p_mla_apa_research_citation/0/6/8/0/6/p68068_index.html{{deadlink|date=May 2018}}</ref> In 1950, President [[Harry S. Truman]] told Catholic leaders he wanted to send an ambassador to the [[Vatican City|Vatican]]. Truman said the leading Democrats in Congress approved, but they warned him, \"it would defeat Democratic Senators and Congressmen in the Bible Belt.\"<ref>Amanda Smith, ''Hostage of Fortune'' (2001) p. 604</ref>{{clarify|date=December 2019}}\n\nIn presidential elections, the Bible Belt states of Alabama, Mississippi, South Carolina, and Texas have voted for the Republican candidate in all elections since 1980; Oklahoma has supported the Republican presidential candidate in every election since 1968. Other Bible Belt states have voted for the Republican presidential candidate in the majority of elections since 1980, but have gone to the Democratic candidate either once or twice since then. However, with the exception of Mississippi, historical geographer Barry Vann shows that counties in the upland areas of the Appalachians and the Ozarks have a more conservative voting pattern than the counties located in the coastal plains.<ref>Barry Vann, In Search of Ulster Scots Land; Barry Vann, \"Natural Liberty in the Bible Belt,\" Nomocracy in Politics (February 2014), http://nomocracyinpolitics.com/2014/02/03/natural-liberty-in-the-bible-belt-an-explanation-of-conservative-voting-patterns-in-southern-appalachia-by-barry-a-vann/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203064959/http://nomocracyinpolitics.com/2014/02/03/natural-liberty-in-the-bible-belt-an-explanation-of-conservative-voting-patterns-in-southern-appalachia-by-barry-a-vann/ |date=February 3, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Outside the United States==\n<!-- Any material that is unreferenced or not supported by the source, will be removed. Please make sure to provide appropriate sources for all the material added! -->\n\n===Australia===\nIn [[Australia]], the term \"Bible Belt\" has been used to refer to areas within individual cities, which have a high concentration of Christians, usually centralised around a [[megachurch]], for example:<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/09/14/1094927585127.html | location=Melbourne | work=The Age | title=Bible Belt wants to tighten a grip on power | date=September 15, 2004}}</ref>\n* the northwestern suburbs of [[Sydney]] focusing on The [[Hills District]], where [[Hillsong Church]] is located\n* the outer-eastern suburbs of [[Melbourne]], where [[CityLife Church]], [[Crossway Baptist Church]], Stairway Church and Discovery Church are located.\n* the northeastern suburbs of [[Adelaide]] focusing on [[Paradise, South Australia|Paradise]], [[Modbury, South Australia|Modbury]] and [[Golden Grove, South Australia|Golden Grove]], where [[Influencers Church]] is located\n* the southeastern region of [[Queensland]] comprising the towns of [[Laidley, Queensland|Laidley]], [[Gatton, Queensland|Gatton]] and [[Toowoomba]].\n* the Brisbane southern suburbs of Mansfield, Springwood, Carindale and Mount Gravatt.  Garden City Assembly of God church, Citipointe church, Clark Taylor's Worship Centre, and Brisbane Hillsong are notable mega-churches in this area.\n* More recently,{{when|date=January 2020}} the far northern suburbs of [[Perth]] are forming this reputation, with the focus being on One Church and Globalheart in the suburbs of [[Merriwa, Western Australia|Merriwa]] and [[Joondalup]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web |title=Perth suburbs by religion: evangelicals head to the northern suburbs |url=https://thewest.com.au/news/wa/evangelicals-migrate-to-northern-suburbs-ng-b88534387z |website=The West Australian |accessdate=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Toowoomba]] city in [[Queensland]] has long been regarded as fertile ground for Christian fundamentalist right-wing movements <ref name=\"espace.library.uq.edu.au\">https://espace.library.uq.edu.au/view/UQ:8027/HARRISON_eprint_.pdf</ref> that adhere to biblical literalism, particularly those within the Pentecostal and charismatic stream of Christianity.  This was exemplified by the highly publicised rise and subsequent fall of [[Howard Carter (evangelist)|Howard Carter]]<ref>http://www.lifemessenger.org/HTML/AboutUs/TheMessenger/TheStory.php{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and the [[Logos Foundation (Australia)|Logos Foundation]] in the 1980s. The Logos Foundation and other similar movements that have followed it, operate in a controlling, authoritarian and almost cultish manner, contributing to their notoriety.<ref name=\"espace.library.uq.edu.au\"/> Other similarly conservative Pentecostal churches within the city have, since that time, banded together into a loose federation known as the Toowoomba Christian Leaders' Network.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.onechurch.org.au/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 17, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214181124/http://www.onechurch.org.au/ |archive-date=February 14, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> (note - most traditional church denominations have their own, separate ecumenical group) This network views itself as having a divine mission to 'take the city for the Lord' and as such, endorses elements of religious right-wing political advocacy, such as the [[Australian Christian Lobby]] (ACL).{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nACL's former managing director who was raised in the Logos Foundation and is a former Toowoomba City councillor is [[Lyle Shelton (Australian lobbyist)|Lyle Shelton]].  These church groups are strongly associated with North American trends such as the [[New Apostolic Reformation]], [[Dominion theology]], Five-fold ministry thinking, [[Kingdom Now theology]] and [[revivalism]].  They support the achievement of a type of theocratic society where conservative and literal interpretations of the bible are the dominant drivers of government, education, the Arts, the media and entertainment. Churches involved in this group currently include the successor organization to the Logos Foundation, the Toowoomba City Church, along with the Range Christian Fellowship, Spring Street Assembly of God, Christian Outreach Centre, Hume Ridge Church of Christ, Revival Ministries of Australia Shiloh Centre, the Edge Christian Centre and many others.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Canada===\nThe province of [[Saskatchewan]] has been referred to as Canada's Bible Belt with a significant [[Catholic]], [[Anabaptist]] population and other [[Protestants]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wells|first1=Kristopher|title=Progressive Albertans are challenging province's Bible Belt stereotypes|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/progressive-albertans-are-challenging-provinces-bible-belt-stereotypes/article28361567/|website=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=August 22, 2017}}</ref> Certain areas of Canada's east coast region, such as the province of New Brunswick, also contain significant populations of Catholic, Baptist, Anglican and United faith adherents, up to 85% overall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://worldpopulationreview.com/canadian-provinces/new-brunswick-population/|title=New Brunswick Population 2020|website=worldpopulationreview.com|access-date=August 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Estonia===\n[[Demographics of Estonia#Religion|Census results]] show religious belief in the country is more prevalent in the east running from north to south along the border with Russia, particularly in those areas with large populations of [[Russian Orthodox Church|Russian Orthodox]], [[Estonian Apostolic Orthodox Church|Estonian Orthodox]] and [[Old Believers|Orthodox Old Believers]].\n\n===Finland===\n[[Conservative Laestadianism]], a Finnish Lutheran revival, is widespread in northern ([[Northern Ostrobothnia]] and [[Lapland (Finland)]]) and central parts ([[Northern Savonia]]) of [[Finland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.helsinki.fi/maantiede/geofi/fennia/demo/pages/fig_pages/raento_cd4.htm|title=FENNIA 2002|website=www.helsinki.fi|accessdate=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Germany===\nRural portions of Bavaria, approximately stretching from [[Franconia]] into [[W\u00fcrttemberg]], constitute Germany's Bible Belt with mostly [[Catholics]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.statistik.bayern.de/presse/archiv/2013/216_2013.php|title=According to a 2011 census, Bavaria is still predominatly Catholic.|publisher=}}</ref>, some [[Lutherans]] and [[Reformed]] [[Protestants]].\nAn area in [[Erzgebirge]] in [[Saxony]] has been described also as the \"Saxon Bible Belt\" with a notable [[evangelical Protestant]]/[[Christian fundamentalist]]/[[free church]] community, as well as some conservative [[Lutheran]] parishes that are opposed to [[same-sex marriage]]. Nevertheless, the [[Evangelical-Lutheran Church of Saxony]] approved church resolutions regarding the issue regardless of opinions within those parishes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weiterdenken.de/sites/default/files/downloads/ErklaerungKirchgemeinden.pdf|title=Erkl\u00e4rung 144 s\u00e4chsischer Kirchgemeinden zum famili\u00e4ren Zusammenleben im Pfarrhaus|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weiterdenken.de/de/2014/06/01/evangelikale-sachsen-ein-bericht|title=Evangelikale in Sachsen - Ein Bericht|website=Weiterdenken - Heinrich-B\u00f6ll-Stiftung Sachsen}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weiterdenken.de/sites/default/files/evangelikale_download_2014-08-19.pdf|title=Jennifer Stange: Evangelikale in Sachsen, Dresden 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://www.evlks.de/aktuelles/nachrichten/31864.html Evlks.de:\u201eSegnung von Paaren in Eingetragener Lebenspartnerschaft\u201c in Sachsen m\u00f6glich \u2013 Beschluss der Kirchenleitung vom 27.&nbsp;Oktober 2016] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019081429/http://www.evlks.de/aktuelles/nachrichten/31864.html |date=October 19, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.evangelisch.de/inhalte/139413/18-10-2016/saechsische-kirche-ermoeglicht-segnung-homosexueller-im-gottesdienst|title=S\u00e4chsische Kirche erm\u00f6glicht Segnung Homosexueller im Gottesdienst|website=www.evangelisch.de}}</ref>\n\n===Netherlands===\nThe [[Bible Belt (Netherlands)|Bible Belt of the Netherlands]] stretches from [[Zeeland]], through the West-[[Betuwe]] and [[Veluwe]], to the northern parts of the province [[Overijssel]]. In this region, orthodox Calvinists prevail.\n\n===New Zealand===\nIn New Zealand, Mount Roskill, Auckland, contains the highest number of churches per capita in the country, and is the home of several Christian political candidates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emigratenz.org/forum/archive/index.php/t-2606.html|title=New Zealand|work=emigratenz.org|accessdate=March 27, 2015}}</ref> The electorate was one of the last in the country to go \"wet\", in 1999, having formerly been a dry area where the selling of alcohol was prohibited.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/71757291/tawa-ditches-prohibition-a-century-after-banning-alcohol--150-years-of-news|title=Tawa ditches prohibition a century after banning alcohol - 150 years of news|website=Stuff|accessdate=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2013 New Zealand census]], the Mangere\u2013Otahuhu local board area of Auckland had the highest concentration of Christians in New Zealand, with 67.7 percent of the local board's 71,000 residents identifying as such.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stats.govt.nz/~/media/Statistics/Census/2013%20Census/profile-and-summary-reports/quickstats-culture-identity/tables.xls |title=Table 33: Religious affiliation (total responses) by territorial authority area, Auckland local board area, and sex \u2013 2013 Census QuickStats about culture and identity |publisher=[[Statistics New Zealand]] |date=April 15, 2014 |accessdate=July 18, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524102811/http://www.stats.govt.nz/~/media/Statistics/Census/2013%20Census/profile-and-summary-reports/quickstats-culture-identity/tables.xls |archivedate=May 24, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn contrast to other bible belts, both areas tend to vote for left-wing candidates and are both currently represented in parliament by the governing centre-left [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]].{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Norway===\nThe [[Bible Belt (Norway)|Bible Belt of Norway]] is located mainly in [[Western Norway|the western]] and [[Southern Norway|southern parts of the country]], and contains numerous devout Lutherans.\n\n===Poland===\nSouth and East parts of Poland are much more religious than North and West.<ref>Wojciech Sadlon (ed.), [http://iskk.pl/images/stories/Instytut/dokumenty/Annuarium_Statisticum_2018.pdf Annuarium Statisticum Ecclesiae in Polonia AD 2018] </ref> See [[Poland A and B]].\n\n===Slovakia===\nIn the eastern and northern parts of [[Slovakia]], Christians comprise a majority, in some towns and villages almost 100%.<ref name=\"SVKCHFCK\">{{cite journal|url=http://portal.statistics.sk/files/Sekcie/sek_600/Demografia/SODB/Tabulky/tab13.pdf |title=Religious statistics in Slovakia |author=Statisticky urad SR |journal=None |year=2001 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522011958/http://portal.statistics.sk/files/Sekcie/sek_600/Demografia/SODB/Tabulky/tab13.pdf |archivedate=May 22, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Soviet Union===\nBefore its independence, [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Soviet Ukraine]] was known as the Bible Belt of the Soviet Union with a significant proportion of [[Baptists in Ukraine|Baptists]].<ref name=\"NCEEER\">{{cite journal | url=http://www.ucis.pitt.edu/nceeer/2006_819_19g_Wanner.pdf | title=Evangelicalism and the Resurgence of Religion in Ukraine | author=Wanne, Catherine | journal=The National Council for Eurasian and East European Research | year=2006}}</ref>\n\n===Sweden===\nThe area normally called the [[Bible Belt (Sweden)|Bible Belt of Sweden]] is centered on [[J\u00f6nk\u00f6ping]] in southern Sweden and contains numerous [[Free church|free churches]]. There are also numerous conservative Lutheran [[Laestadianism|Laestadians]] in the [[Me\u00e4nmaa|Torne valley]] area in the far north of the country.\n\n===United Kingdom and Ireland===\n\nIn [[Northern Ireland]], the area in [[County Antrim]] stretching from roughly [[Ballymoney]] to [[Larne]] and centred in the area of [[Ballymena]] is often referred to as a Bible Belt. This is because the area is heavily Protestant with a large [[evangelicalism|evangelical]] community. From 1970 to 2010, the MP for [[North Antrim (UK Parliament constituency)|North Antrim]] was [[Ian Paisley]], a [[Free Presbyterian Church of Ulster|Free Presbyterian]] minister well known for his theological fundamentalism. The town of Ballymena, the largest town in the constituency, is often referred to as the \"buckle\" of the Bible Belt. In the [[Republic of Ireland]], [[County Wicklow]] and western parts of [[County Cork]] have the highest population of Protestants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sluggerotoole.com/2005/07/29/more_news_from_the_bible_belt/|title=More news from the Bible Belt\u2026|first=Belfast|last=Gonzo|date=July 29, 2005|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|Christianity}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Banana Belt]]\n*[[Blue wall (politics)|Blue wall]]\n*[[Born again|Born again (Christianity)]]\n*[[Christian right]]\n*[[Deep South]]\n*[[Great Awakening]]\n*[[Jesusland map]]\n*[[List of belt regions of the United States]]\n*[[List of U.S. states by religiosity]]\n*[[Southern Baptist Convention]]\n*[[Quran Belt]]\n*[[Rust Belt]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n* Balmer, Randall H. (2002). Encyclopedia of Evangelicalism. Westminster John Knox Press.\n* Christine Leigh H, (1997), Southern Cross: The Beginnings of the Bible Belt. Knopf.\n* Denman, Stan. (2004). Political Playing for the Soul of the American South: Theater and the Maintenance of Cultural Hegemony in the American Bible Belt. Southern Quarterly, 42(3), 64-72.\n* Hayes, Turner Elizabeth. (1997). Women, Culture and Community: Religion and Reform in Galveston 1880-1920, Oxford University Press.\n* Heatwole, Charles A. (1978). The Bible Belt; a problem of regional definition. Journal of Geography, 77, 50-55.\n* Hill, Samuel S., Lippy, Charles H. & Wilson, Charles R. (2005). Encyclopedia Of Religion In The South. Mercer University Press.\n* Lippy, Charles, H. (1993). Religion in South Carolina. University of South Carolina.\n* Marsden, George M. (1982). Fundamentalism and American Culture: The Shaping of Twentieth-Century Evangelicalism, 1870-1925. Oxford University Press.\n* Moran, Jeffrey P. (2004). The Scopes Trial and Southern Fundamentalism in Black and White: Race, Region, and Religion. Journal of Southern History, 70(1), 95.\n* Park, Chris C. (1994). Sacred Worlds: An Introduction to Geography and Religion. Routledge.\n* Pettersson, Thorleif & Hamberg, Eva M. (1997). Denominational Pluralism and Church Membership in Contemporary Sweden. Journal of Empirical Theology, 10(2), 61-78.\n* Sparks, Randy J. (2001). Religion in Mississippi. University Press of Mississippi for the Mississippi Historical Society.\n* Stacey, Williams A. & Shupe, Anson. (1984). Religious Values and Religiosity in the Textbook Adoption Controversy in Texas, 1981. Review of Religious Research. 25(4), 321-333.\n* Tweedie, Stephen W. (1978). Viewing the Bible Belt. THE Journal of Popular Culture, 11(4), 865-876.\n{{refend}}\n{{Regions of the world}}\n{{U.S. Belt regions}}\n\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1920s]]\n[[Category:Cultural regions]]\n[[Category:Christianity in the United States]]\n[[Category:Evangelicalism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Christian fundamentalism]]\n[[Category:Religion in the Southern United States]]\n[[Category:Regions of the Southern United States]]\n[[Category:Belt regions of the United States]]\n[[Category:Conservatism in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Other uses|Bible Belt (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Bible Belt\n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| settlement_type = Cultural region of the United States\n| image_flag =\n| flag_alt =\n| image_seal =\n| seal_alt =\n| image_shield =\n| shield_alt =\n| nickname =\n| motto =\n| image_map = File:BibleBelt.png\n| map_alt =\n| map_caption = The area roughly considered to constitute the Bible Belt\n| subdivision_type = Country\n| subdivision_name =\n| subdivision_type1 = Subregion\n| subdivision_type2 = Subregion\n| subdivision_type3 =\n| subdivision_name1 = \n| subdivision_type4  = Country\n| subdivision_name4  = {{flag|United States}}\n| subdivision_type5 = States\n| subdivision_name5 = {{flag|Alabama}}<br /> {{flag|Arkansas}}<br /> {{flag|Florida}}<br /> {{flag|Georgia (U.S. state)|name=Georgia}}<br /> {{flag|Kentucky}}<br /> {{flag|Louisiana}}<br /> {{flag|Mississippi}}<br /> {{flag|Missouri}}<br /> {{flag|North Carolina}}<br /> {{flag|Oklahoma}}<br /> {{flag|South Carolina}}<br /> {{flag|Tennessee}}<br /> {{flag|Texas}}<br /> {{flag|Virginia}}<br /> {{flag|West Virginia}}<br /> \nand parts of: \n{{flag|Illinois}}<br /> {{flag|Indiana}}<br /> {{flag|Ohio}}<br />\n}}\nThe '''Bible Belt''' is an informal region in the [[Southern United States]] in which [[Social conservatism|socially conservative]] [[Evangelicalism in the United States|evangelical Protestantism]] plays a strong role in society and politics, and [[church attendance]] across the denominations is generally higher than the nation's average.\n\nThe region contrasts with the religiously diverse [[Midwestern United States|Midwest]] and [[Great Lakes region|Great Lakes]], the [[Mormon Corridor]] in [[Utah]] and [[southern Idaho]], and the relatively [[Secularism|secular]] [[Western United States|Western]] and [[New England]] regions of the [[United States]]. Whereas the state with the highest percentage of residents identifying as non-religious is the New England state of [[Vermont]] at 37%, in the Bible Belt state of [[Alabama]] it is just 12%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/religious-tradition/unaffiliated-religious-nones/|title=The Unaffiliated|date=May 11, 2015|work=Pew Research Center's Religion & Public Life Project}}</ref> [[Tennessee]] has the highest proportion of Evangelical Protestants, at 52%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/state/tennessee/|title=Adults in Tennessee|date=May 11, 2015|work=Pew Research Center's Religion & Public Life Project}}</ref> The Evangelical influence is strongest in northern [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], [[Tennessee]], [[Alabama]], [[Mississippi]], [[North Carolina]], Southern and Western [[Virginia]], [[West Virginia]], [[South Carolina]], and almost all of [[Texas]].  \n\nThe earliest known usage of the term \"Bible Belt\" was by American journalist and social commentator [[H. L. Mencken]], who in 1924 wrote in the ''[[Chicago Tribune|Chicago Daily Tribune]]'': \"The old game, I suspect, is beginning to play out in the Bible Belt.\"<ref>Fred R. Shapiro (ed.). ''Yale Book of Quotations''. [[Yale University Press]] (2006). {{ISBN|978-0-300-10798-2}}.</ref> In 1927, Mencken claimed the term as his invention.<ref>[http://www.aaa.si.edu/collections/images/detail/h-l-mencken-letter-to-charles-green-shaw-9819 H. L. Mencken letter to Charles Green Shaw, 1927 Dec. 2 .] Charles Green Shaw papers, Archives of American Art, Smithsonian Institution. See also, http://www.lettersofnote.com/2011/06/human-race-is-incurably-idiotic.html</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nThe name \"Bible Belt\" has been applied historically to the South and parts of the Midwest, but is more commonly identified with the South. In a 1961 study, [[Wilbur Zelinsky]] delineated the region as the area in which Protestant denominations, especially Southern Baptist, Methodist, and evangelical, are the predominant religious affiliation. The region thus defined included most of the Southern United States, including most of [[Texas]] and [[Oklahoma]], and in the states south of the [[Ohio River]], and extending east to include central West Virginia and Virginia, from the [[Shenandoah Valley]] southward into [[Southside Virginia]] and [[North Carolina]]. In addition, the Bible Belt covers most of [[Missouri]] and [[Kentucky]] and southern parts of [[Illinois]], [[Indiana]], and [[Ohio]]. On the other hand, areas in the South which are ''not'' considered part of the Bible Belt include heavily Catholic Southern Louisiana, central and southern Florida, which have been settled mainly by immigrants and Americans from elsewhere in the country, and overwhelmingly Hispanic South Texas. A 1978 study by Charles Heatwole identified the Bible Belt as the region dominated by 24 fundamentalist Protestant denominations, corresponding to essentially the same area mapped by Zelinsky.<ref>Barry Vann (2008), ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=_cx6NMWOqKQC&pg=PA138&lpg=PA138&dq=bible+belt+charles+heatwole&source=bl&ots=s_3pBjUyyC&sig=58XbseF5_V9de4OW2ZOX34mqwTw&hl=en&ei=0Z8zS-zxDtWztgeb4Jj9CA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=13&ved=0CD4Q6AEwDA#v=onepage&q=bible%20belt%20charles%20heatwole&f=false In search of Ulster-Scots land: the birth and geotheological imagings of a transatlantic people, 1603-1703]'', Univ of South Carolina Press, {{ISBN|1-57003-708-6}}, {{ISBN|978-1-57003-708-5}}. Pages 138-140.</ref>\n\nAccording to Stephen W. Tweedie, an Associate Professor Emeritus in the Department of Geography at [[Oklahoma State University]], the Bible Belt is now viewed in terms of numerical concentration of the audience for religious television.<ref name=Carney_Fast_Food>{{cite book|last1=Carney|first1=edited by George O.|title=Fast food, stock cars and rock'n'roll: place and space in American pop culture|date=1995|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|location=Lanham|isbn=9780847680801|page=131|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aJnNasHzjN0C&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> He finds two belts: one more eastern that stretches from Florida, (excluding Miami, [[Tampa]] and South Florida), through [[Alabama]], [[Tennessee]], Kentucky, [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], the Carolinas, and into [[Southside Virginia]]; and another concentrated in Texas (excluding [[El Paso]], and [[South Texas]]), [[Arkansas]], [[Louisiana]], (excluding [[New Orleans]] and [[Acadiana]]), Oklahoma, Missouri (excluding [[St. Louis]]), [[Kansas]], and [[Mississippi]].<ref>Tweedie, S.W. (1978) Viewing the Bible Belt. [[Journal of Popular Culture]] 11; 865-76</ref>  \"[H]is research also broke the Bible Belt into two core regions, a western region and an eastern region. Tweedie's western Bible Belt was focused on a core that extended from Little Rock, Arkansas to Tulsa, Oklahoma. His eastern Bible Belt was focused on a core that included the major population centers of Virginia and North Carolina.<ref name=About_BibleBelt>{{cite news|last1=Rosenberg|first1=Matt|title=The Bible Belt Extends Throughout the American South (And Perhaps Beyond?)|url=http://geography.about.com/od/culturalgeography/fl/The-Bible-Belt.htm|accessdate=June 11, 2015|agency=About Education|publisher=About.com|ref=Rosenberg}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bible-minded Cities map.PNG|thumb|Bible-minded cities map]]\nA study was commissioned by the [[American Bible Society]] to survey the importance of the Bible in the metropolitan areas of the United States. The report was based on 42,855 interviews conducted between 2005 and 2012. It determined the 10 most \"Bible-minded\" cities were [[Knoxville, Tennessee]]; [[Shreveport, Louisiana]]; [[Chattanooga, Tennessee]]; [[Birmingham, Alabama]]; [[Jackson, Mississippi]]; [[Springfield, Missouri]]; [[Charlotte, North Carolina]]; [[Lynchburg, Virginia]]; [[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville-Decatur, Alabama]]; and [[Charleston, West Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cities.barna.org/americas-most-and-least-bible-minded-cities/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328095729/http://cities.barna.org/americas-most-and-least-bible-minded-cities/|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 28, 2013|title=America's Most and Least Bible-Minded Cities|accessdate=July 31, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the South, there is a smaller Bible Belt in [[West Michigan]], centered on the heavily Dutch-influenced cities of [[Holland, Michigan|Holland]] and [[Grand Rapids, Michigan|Grand Rapids]]. Christian colleges in that region include [[Calvin College]], [[Hope College]], [[Cornerstone University]], [[Grace Bible College]], and [[Kuyper College]]. West Michigan is generally fiscally and socially conservative.\n\n=== By state ===\n[[File:Importance of Religion in the United States of America.svg|thumb|350px|Percentage of respondents in the USA stating that religion is \"very important\" or \"somewhat important\" to their lives, 2014<ref name=\"Pew\"/>]]\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\n|+ Proportion of Evangelical Protestants per state in the [[American South]]<ref>https://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/state/</ref>|| \n|-\n!State !! Baptist !! Pentecostal !! Restorationist !! Presbyterian !! Other !! Total !! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:1px;\" style=\"background:grey;\"| !! valign=\"top\"|Share indicating that<br />religion is \"important\"<ref name=\"Pew\">[http://www.pewforum.org/religious-landscape-study/state/alabama/#importance-of-religion-by-state Importance of religion by state] Pew forum (sum of \"very important\" and \"something important\")</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Alabama}} || 31% || 5% || 3% || 2% || 8% || '''49%''' || class=\"unsortable\" rowspan=\"18\" style=\"width:1px;\" style=\"background:grey;\"| || 90%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Arkansas}} || 25% || 5% || 5% || 2% || 9% || '''46%''' || 86%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Delaware}} || 7% || 1% || 3% || 1% || 3% || '''15%''' || 77%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|District of Columbia|name=Washington, D.C.}} || 2% || 1% || 1% || 1% || 3% || '''8%''' || 71%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Florida}} || 8% || 4% || 2% || 1% || 9% || '''24%''' || 78%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Georgia (U.S. state)|name=Georgia}} || 21% || 4% || 2% || 1% || 10% || '''38%''' || 84%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Kentucky}} || 29% || 7% || 3% || 1% || 9% || '''49%''' || 86%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Louisiana}} || 16% || 3% || 1% || <1% || 7% || '''27%''' || 90%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Maryland}} || 5% || 3% || 1% || <1% || 9% || '''18%''' || 75%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Mississippi}} || 26% || 4% || 2% || 1% || 8% || '''41%''' || 89% \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Missouri}} || 15% || 6% || 3% || 1% || 11% || '''36%''' || 82% \n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|North Carolina}} || 20% || 4% || 1% || 1% || 9% || '''35%''' || 84%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Oklahoma}} || 23% || 6% || 4% || <1% || 14% || '''47%''' || 87%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|South Carolina}} || 22% || 4% || 1% || 1% || 7% || '''35%''' || 85%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Tennessee}} || 33% || 4% || 6% || 2% || 7% || '''52%''' || 89%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Texas}} || 14% || 4% || 2% || <1% || 11% || '''31%''' || 86%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|Virginia}} || 15% || 5% || <1% || 1% || 9% || '''30%''' || 81%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{flag|West Virginia}} || 19% || 7% || 2% || <1% || 11% || '''39%''' || 86%\n|}\n\n==History==\nDuring the [[Thirteen Colonies|colonial period]] (1607\u20131776), the South was a stronghold of the [[Church of England|Anglican church]]. Its transition to a stronghold of non-Anglican Protestantism occurred gradually over the next century as a series of religious revival movements, many associated with the Baptist denomination, gained great popularity in the region.<ref name=Jeynes>{{cite book|last1=Murray|first1=William H. Jeynes ; foreword by William J.|title=A call for character education and prayer in the schools|date=2009|publisher=Praeger|location=Santa Barbara, Calif.|isbn=978-0313351044|pages=122\u2013123|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VmlFCQAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=June 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIt seems a link between the colonial Bible Belt (the North, especially [[New England]] with its Puritan heritage) and the later Southern Bible Belt may be seen in the impact which some Northern figures had on the religious development of the South (perhaps not incomparable to the origins of [[Mormonism]] in the North, in spite of its later association with [[Utah]]). \"The centre of Particular Baptist activity in early America was in the [[Middle Colonies]]. In 1707 five churches in New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Delaware were united to form the Philadelphia Baptist Association, and through the association they embarked upon vigorous missionary activity. By 1760 the Philadelphia association included churches located in the present states of Connecticut, New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Delaware, Virginia, and West Virginia; and by 1767 further multiplication of churches had necessitated the formation of two subsidiary associations, the Warren in New England and the Ketochton in Virginia. The Philadelphia association also provided leadership in organizing the Charleston Association in the Carolinas in 1751.\"<ref name=\"Britannica\">{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Baptist|title=Baptist - History, Beliefs, Denominations, & Facts|website=Encyclopedia Britannica}}</ref> \n\nAn influential figure was [[Shubal Stearns]]: \"Shubael Stearns, a New England Separate Baptist, migrated to Sandy Creek, North Carolina, in 1755 and initiated a revival that quickly penetrated the entire Piedmont region. The churches he organized were brought together in 1758 to form the Sandy Creek Association\".<ref name=\"Britannica\" /> Stearns was brother-in-law of Daniel Marshall, who was born in Windsor, Connecticut and \"is generally considered the first great Baptist leader in Georgia. He founded Kiokee Baptist Church, the oldest continuing Baptist congregation in the state\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.georgiaencyclopedia.org/articles/arts-culture/daniel-marshall-1706-1784|title=Daniel Marshall (1706-1784) - New Georgia Encyclopedia|publisher=}}</ref> Also, Wait Palmer, of Toland, Connecticut,<ref name=\"Sobel\">{{cite book|title=Trabelin' on: The Slave Journey to an Afro-Baptist Faith|last=Sobel|first=Mechal|url=https://archive.org/details/trabelinonslavej0000sobe|url-access=registration|year=1988|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=0691006032}}</ref>{{rp|84 - 85}} may have influenced African American Christianity in the South: \"The Silver Bluff, South Carolina, revival was a seminal development, whose role among blacks rivalled that played by the Sandy Creek revival of the Separate Baptists, to which it was indirectly related. It was probably the same Wait Palmer who had baptized Shubal Stearns in 1751 who came to Silver Bluff in 1775, baptizing and constituting a church. Abraham Marshall, who encouraged the later offshoots, was a Separate Baptist of the Sandy Creek school. The revival at the Silver Bluff plantation of George Galphin (some twelve miles from Augusta, Georgia) had brought David George to the Afro-Baptist faith and had provided a ministry for [[George Liele]]\".<ref name=\"Sobel\" />{{rp|188}} \n\nAccording to Thomas S. Kidd, \"As early as 1758, Sandy Creek missionaries helped organize a slave congregation, the Bluestone Church, on the plantation of William Byrd III, which may have been the first independently functioning African American church in North America. The church did not last long, but it reflected the Baptists' commitment to evangelizing African Americans\".<ref>{{cite book|title=The Great Awakening: The Roots of Evangelical Christianity in Colonial America|last=Kidd|first=Thomas S.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=xPCrZa70--AC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=2007|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0300148251}}</ref>{{rp|249}} According to Gayraud S. Wilmore, \"The preaching of New England Congregationalists such as Jonathan Edwards about the coming millennium, and his conviction that Christians were called to prepare for it, reached the slaves through the far-ranging missionary work of white evangelists such as Shubal Stearns, Wait Palmer, and Matthew Moore - all of whom left Congregationalism and became Separatist Baptist preachers in the plantation country of Virginia, North and South Carolina, and Georgia\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Pragmatic Spirituality: The Christian Faith through an Africentric Lens|last=Wilmore|first=Gayraud S.|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=4Wy_DAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=2004|publisher=New York University Press|isbn=9781479884247}}</ref>{{rp|168}}\n\n==Buckle==\n[[File:Go to church....jpg|thumb|A billboard near the center of [[Alabama]] ]]\n\nSeveral locations are occasionally referred to as \"the Buckle of the Bible Belt\":\n*[[Abilene, Texas]] a city of 117,000, is home to three Protestant universities: the Baptist affiliated [[Hardin-Simmons University]], the Church of Christ's [[Abilene Christian University]], and Methodist founded [[McMurry University]].<ref name=\"encyclopedia of the great plains\">{{cite web|url=http://plainshumanities.unl.edu/encyclopedia/doc/egp.ct.002|title=Encyclopedia of the Great Plains - ABILENE, TEXAS|work=unl.edu|accessdate=March 27, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Nashville, Tennessee]], sometimes referred to as \"the Protestant Vatican\",<ref>{{cite book|title=Insiders' Guide to Nashville|first1=Cindy Stooksbury|last1=Guier|first2=Jackie Sheckler|last2=Finch|year=2007|edition=6th|pages=13, 35, 396}}</ref> has over 700 churches,<ref name=\"nashcity1\">{{cite web |url=http://nashcity.com/religious-institutions/christian-churches/index.shtml |title=Nashville Area Churches |work=NashCity.com |accessdate=April 30, 2008}}</ref> several seminaries, and a number of Christian schools, colleges and universities, including [[Belmont University]], [[Trevecca Nazarene University]], [[Lipscomb University]], [[Free Will Baptist Bible College]] and [[American Baptist College]]. Nashville is the seat of the [[National Baptist Convention, USA]], the headquarters of the [[Southern Baptist Convention]], the [[National Association of Free Will Baptists]], the [[Gideons International]], the [[Gospel Music Association]], and [[Thomas Nelson (publisher)|Thomas Nelson]], the world's largest producer of Bibles.<ref name=\"road&travel\">{{cite web |url=http://www.roadandtravel.com/travel%20directory/Tennessee/nashvillestory.htm |title=Nashville: Sophisticated Southern City with a Country Edge |work=RoadandTravel.com |first=Rachel L |last=Miller |date=April 14, 2008 |accessdate=April 30, 2008}}</ref>\n*[[Tulsa, Oklahoma]] is a city where Protestant and, in particular, [[Southern Baptist]] and other [[evangelical]] Christian traditions are very prominent. Tulsa is home to [[Oral Roberts University]], and [[RHEMA Bible Training Center|RHEMA Bible Training College]] (in [[Broken Arrow, Oklahoma|Broken Arrow]]). A number of prominent Protestant Christians have lived or studied in Tulsa, including [[Joel Osteen]], [[Kenneth E. Hagin]], [[Carlton Pearson]], [[Kenneth Copeland]], [[Billy Joe Daugherty]], [[Smokie Norful]] and [[Billy James Hargis]]. Tulsa is also home to a number of vibrant [[Mainline Protestant]] congregations. Some of these congregations were founded during the oil boom of the early twentieth century and their facilities are noted for striking architecture, such as the art deco [[Boston Avenue Methodist Church]] and [[First Presbyterian Church (Tulsa)|First Presbyterian Church of Tulsa]].\n*[[Greenville, South Carolina]] is a city where many Baptist, particularly [[Independent Baptists]] are located.  Greenville has 124 Baptist churches<ref>\"Churches in Greenville\"> https://www.churchangel.com/WEBSC/greenville.htm</ref> in the Greenville area, as well as [[Bob Jones University]]. It also is the home of WTBI radio station which plays old-fashioned [[Christian Music]] and preaching 24 hours a day.\n\n==Political and cultural context==\nThere has been research that links evangelical Protestantism with social conservatism.<ref>http://www.allacademic.com/meta/p_mla_apa_research_citation/0/6/8/0/6/p68068_index.html{{deadlink|date=May 2018}}</ref> In 1950, President [[Harry S. Truman]] told Catholic leaders he wanted to send an ambassador to the [[Vatican City|Vatican]]. Truman said the leading Democrats in Congress approved, but they warned him, \"it would defeat Democratic Senators and Congressmen in the Bible Belt.\"<ref>Amanda Smith, ''Hostage of Fortune'' (2001) p. 604</ref>{{clarify|date=December 2019}}\n\nIn presidential elections, the Bible Belt states of Alabama, Mississippi, South Carolina, and Texas have voted for the Republican candidate in all elections since 1980; Oklahoma has supported the Republican presidential candidate in every election since 1968. Other Bible Belt states have voted for the Republican presidential candidate in the majority of elections since 1980, but have gone to the Democratic candidate either once or twice since then. However, with the exception of Mississippi, historical geographer Barry Vann shows that counties in the upland areas of the Appalachians and the Ozarks have a more conservative voting pattern than the counties located in the coastal plains.<ref>Barry Vann, In Search of Ulster Scots Land; Barry Vann, \"Natural Liberty in the Bible Belt,\" Nomocracy in Politics (February 2014), http://nomocracyinpolitics.com/2014/02/03/natural-liberty-in-the-bible-belt-an-explanation-of-conservative-voting-patterns-in-southern-appalachia-by-barry-a-vann/ {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140203064959/http://nomocracyinpolitics.com/2014/02/03/natural-liberty-in-the-bible-belt-an-explanation-of-conservative-voting-patterns-in-southern-appalachia-by-barry-a-vann/ |date=February 3, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Outside the United States==\n<!-- Any material that is unreferenced or not supported by the source, will be removed. Please make sure to provide appropriate sources for all the material added! -->\n\n===Australia===\nIn [[Australia]], the term \"Bible Belt\" has been used to refer to areas within individual cities, which have a high concentration of Christians, usually centralised around a [[megachurch]], for example:<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2004/09/14/1094927585127.html | location=Melbourne | work=The Age | title=Bible Belt wants to tighten a grip on power | date=September 15, 2004}}</ref>\n* the northwestern suburbs of [[Sydney]] focusing on The [[Hills District]], where [[Hillsong Church]] is located\n* the outer-eastern suburbs of [[Melbourne]], where [[CityLife Church]], [[Crossway Baptist Church]], Stairway Church and Discovery Church are located.\n* the northeastern suburbs of [[Adelaide]] focusing on [[Paradise, South Australia|Paradise]], [[Modbury, South Australia|Modbury]] and [[Golden Grove, South Australia|Golden Grove]], where [[Influencers Church]] is located\n* the southeastern region of [[Queensland]] comprising the towns of [[Laidley, Queensland|Laidley]], [[Gatton, Queensland|Gatton]] and [[Toowoomba]].\n* the Brisbane southern suburbs of Mansfield, Springwood, Carindale and Mount Gravatt.  Garden City Assembly of God church, Citipointe church, Clark Taylor's Worship Centre, and Brisbane Hillsong are notable mega-churches in this area.\n* More recently,{{when|date=January 2020}} the far northern suburbs of [[Perth]] are forming this reputation, with the focus being on One Church and Globalheart in the suburbs of [[Merriwa, Western Australia|Merriwa]] and [[Joondalup]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web |title=Perth suburbs by religion: evangelicals head to the northern suburbs |url=https://thewest.com.au/news/wa/evangelicals-migrate-to-northern-suburbs-ng-b88534387z |website=The West Australian |accessdate=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Toowoomba]] city in [[Queensland]] has long been regarded as fertile ground for Christian fundamentalist right-wing movements <ref name=\"espace.library.uq.edu.au\">https://espace.library.uq.edu.au/view/UQ:8027/HARRISON_eprint_.pdf</ref> that adhere to biblical literalism, particularly those within the Pentecostal and charismatic stream of Christianity.  This was exemplified by the highly publicised rise and subsequent fall of [[Howard Carter (evangelist)|Howard Carter]]<ref>http://www.lifemessenger.org/HTML/AboutUs/TheMessenger/TheStory.php{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and the [[Logos Foundation (Australia)|Logos Foundation]] in the 1980s. The Logos Foundation and other similar movements that have followed it, operate in a controlling, authoritarian and almost cultish manner, contributing to their notoriety.<ref name=\"espace.library.uq.edu.au\"/> Other similarly conservative Pentecostal churches within the city have, since that time, banded together into a loose federation known as the Toowoomba Christian Leaders' Network.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.onechurch.org.au/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 17, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214181124/http://www.onechurch.org.au/ |archive-date=February 14, 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> (note - most traditional church denominations have their own, separate ecumenical group) This network views itself as having a divine mission to 'take the city for the Lord' and as such, endorses elements of religious right-wing political advocacy, such as the [[Australian Christian Lobby]] (ACL).{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\nACL's former managing director who was raised in the Logos Foundation and is a former Toowoomba City councillor is [[Lyle Shelton (Australian lobbyist)|Lyle Shelton]].  These church groups are strongly associated with North American trends such as the [[New Apostolic Reformation]], [[Dominion theology]], Five-fold ministry thinking, [[Kingdom Now theology]] and [[revivalism]].  They support the achievement of a type of theocratic society where conservative and literal interpretations of the bible are the dominant drivers of government, education, the Arts, the media and entertainment. Churches involved in this group currently include the successor organization to the Logos Foundation, the Toowoomba City Church, along with the Range Christian Fellowship, Spring Street Assembly of God, Christian Outreach Centre, Hume Ridge Church of Christ, Revival Ministries of Australia Shiloh Centre, the Edge Christian Centre and many others.{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Canada===\nThe province of [[Saskatchewan]] has been referred to as Canada's Bible Belt with a significant [[Catholic]], [[Anabaptist]] population and other [[Protestants]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wells|first1=Kristopher|title=Progressive Albertans are challenging province's Bible Belt stereotypes|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/progressive-albertans-are-challenging-provinces-bible-belt-stereotypes/article28361567/|website=The Globe and Mail|accessdate=August 22, 2017}}</ref> Certain areas of Canada's east coast region, such as the province of New Brunswick, also contain significant populations of Catholic, Baptist, Anglican and United faith adherents, up to 85% overall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://worldpopulationreview.com/canadian-provinces/new-brunswick-population/|title=New Brunswick Population 2020|website=worldpopulationreview.com|access-date=August 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Estonia===\n[[Demographics of Estonia#Religion|Census results]] show religious belief in the country is more prevalent in the east running from north to south along the border with Russia, particularly in those areas with large populations of [[Russian Orthodox Church|Russian Orthodox]], [[Estonian Apostolic Orthodox Church|Estonian Orthodox]] and [[Old Believers|Orthodox Old Believers]].\n\n===Finland===\n[[Conservative Laestadianism]], a Finnish Lutheran revival, is widespread in northern ([[Northern Ostrobothnia]] and [[Lapland (Finland)]]) and central parts ([[Northern Savonia]]) of [[Finland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.helsinki.fi/maantiede/geofi/fennia/demo/pages/fig_pages/raento_cd4.htm|title=FENNIA 2002|website=www.helsinki.fi|accessdate=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Germany===\nRural portions of Bavaria, approximately stretching from [[Franconia]] into [[W\u00fcrttemberg]], constitute Germany's Bible Belt with mostly [[Catholics]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.statistik.bayern.de/presse/archiv/2013/216_2013.php|title=According to a 2011 census, Bavaria is still predominatly Catholic.|publisher=}}</ref>, some [[Lutherans]] and [[Reformed]] [[Protestants]].\nAn area in [[Erzgebirge]] in [[Saxony]] has been described also as the \"Saxon Bible Belt\" with a notable [[evangelical Protestant]]/[[Christian fundamentalist]]/[[free church]] community, as well as some conservative [[Lutheran]] parishes that are opposed to [[same-sex marriage]]. Nevertheless, the [[Evangelical-Lutheran Church of Saxony]] approved church resolutions regarding the issue regardless of opinions within those parishes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weiterdenken.de/sites/default/files/downloads/ErklaerungKirchgemeinden.pdf|title=Erkl\u00e4rung 144 s\u00e4chsischer Kirchgemeinden zum famili\u00e4ren Zusammenleben im Pfarrhaus|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weiterdenken.de/de/2014/06/01/evangelikale-sachsen-ein-bericht|title=Evangelikale in Sachsen - Ein Bericht|website=Weiterdenken - Heinrich-B\u00f6ll-Stiftung Sachsen}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.weiterdenken.de/sites/default/files/evangelikale_download_2014-08-19.pdf|title=Jennifer Stange: Evangelikale in Sachsen, Dresden 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://www.evlks.de/aktuelles/nachrichten/31864.html Evlks.de:\u201eSegnung von Paaren in Eingetragener Lebenspartnerschaft\u201c in Sachsen m\u00f6glich \u2013 Beschluss der Kirchenleitung vom 27.&nbsp;Oktober 2016] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161019081429/http://www.evlks.de/aktuelles/nachrichten/31864.html |date=October 19, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.evangelisch.de/inhalte/139413/18-10-2016/saechsische-kirche-ermoeglicht-segnung-homosexueller-im-gottesdienst|title=S\u00e4chsische Kirche erm\u00f6glicht Segnung Homosexueller im Gottesdienst|website=www.evangelisch.de}}</ref>\n\n===Netherlands===\nThe [[Bible Belt (Netherlands)|Bible Belt of the Netherlands]] stretches from [[Zeeland]], through the West-[[Betuwe]] and [[Veluwe]], to the northern parts of the province [[Overijssel]]. In this region, orthodox Calvinists prevail.\n\n===New Zealand===\nIn New Zealand, Mount Roskill, Auckland, contains the highest number of churches per capita in the country, and is the home of several Christian political candidates.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emigratenz.org/forum/archive/index.php/t-2606.html|title=New Zealand|work=emigratenz.org|accessdate=March 27, 2015}}</ref> The electorate was one of the last in the country to go \"wet\", in 1999, having formerly been a dry area where the selling of alcohol was prohibited.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/dominion-post/news/71757291/tawa-ditches-prohibition-a-century-after-banning-alcohol--150-years-of-news|title=Tawa ditches prohibition a century after banning alcohol - 150 years of news|website=Stuff|accessdate=February 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2013 New Zealand census]], the Mangere\u2013Otahuhu local board area of Auckland had the highest concentration of Christians in New Zealand, with 67.7 percent of the local board's 71,000 residents identifying as such.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stats.govt.nz/~/media/Statistics/Census/2013%20Census/profile-and-summary-reports/quickstats-culture-identity/tables.xls |title=Table 33: Religious affiliation (total responses) by territorial authority area, Auckland local board area, and sex \u2013 2013 Census QuickStats about culture and identity |publisher=[[Statistics New Zealand]] |date=April 15, 2014 |accessdate=July 18, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140524102811/http://www.stats.govt.nz/~/media/Statistics/Census/2013%20Census/profile-and-summary-reports/quickstats-culture-identity/tables.xls |archivedate=May 24, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn contrast to other bible belts, both areas tend to vote for left-wing candidates and are both currently represented in parliament by the governing centre-left [[New Zealand Labour Party|Labour Party]].{{cn|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Norway===\nThe [[Bible Belt (Norway)|Bible Belt of Norway]] is located mainly in [[Western Norway|the western]] and [[Southern Norway|southern parts of the country]], and contains numerous devout Lutherans.\n\n===Poland===\nSouth and East parts of Poland are much more religious than North and West.<ref>Wojciech Sadlon (ed.), [http://iskk.pl/images/stories/Instytut/dokumenty/Annuarium_Statisticum_2018.pdf Annuarium Statisticum Ecclesiae in Polonia AD 2018] </ref> See [[Poland A and B]].\n\n===Slovakia===\nIn the eastern and northern parts of [[Slovakia]], Christians comprise a majority, in some towns and villages almost 100%.<ref name=\"SVKCHFCK\">{{cite journal|url=http://portal.statistics.sk/files/Sekcie/sek_600/Demografia/SODB/Tabulky/tab13.pdf |title=Religious statistics in Slovakia |author=Statisticky urad SR |journal=None |year=2001 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522011958/http://portal.statistics.sk/files/Sekcie/sek_600/Demografia/SODB/Tabulky/tab13.pdf |archivedate=May 22, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Soviet Union===\nBefore its independence, [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Soviet Ukraine]] was known as the Bible Belt of the Soviet Union with a significant proportion of [[Baptists in Ukraine|Baptists]].<ref name=\"NCEEER\">{{cite journal | url=http://www.ucis.pitt.edu/nceeer/2006_819_19g_Wanner.pdf | title=Evangelicalism and the Resurgence of Religion in Ukraine | author=Wanne, Catherine | journal=The National Council for Eurasian and East European Research | year=2006}}</ref>\n\n===Sweden===\nThe area normally called the [[Bible Belt (Sweden)|Bible Belt of Sweden]] is centered on [[J\u00f6nk\u00f6ping]] in southern Sweden and contains numerous [[Free church|free churches]]. There are also numerous conservative Lutheran [[Laestadianism|Laestadians]] in the [[Me\u00e4nmaa|Torne valley]] area in the far north of the country.\n\n===United Kingdom and Ireland===\n\nIn [[Northern Ireland]], the area in [[County Antrim]] stretching from roughly [[Ballymoney]] to [[Larne]] and centred in the area of [[Ballymena]] is often referred to as a Bible Belt. This is because the area is heavily Protestant with a large [[evangelicalism|evangelical]] community. From 1970 to 2010, the MP for [[North Antrim (UK Parliament constituency)|North Antrim]] was [[Ian Paisley]], a [[Free Presbyterian Church of Ulster|Free Presbyterian]] minister well known for his theological fundamentalism. The town of Ballymena, the largest town in the constituency, is often referred to as the \"buckle\" of the Bible Belt. In the [[Republic of Ireland]], [[County Wicklow]] and western parts of [[County Cork]] have the highest population of Protestants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sluggerotoole.com/2005/07/29/more_news_from_the_bible_belt/|title=More news from the Bible Belt\u2026|first=Belfast|last=Gonzo|date=July 29, 2005|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|Christianity}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Banana Belt]]\n*[[Blue wall (politics)|Blue wall]]\n*[[Born again|Born again (Christianity)]]\n*[[Christian right]]\n*[[Deep South]]\n*[[Great Awakening]]\n*[[Jesusland map]]\n*[[List of belt regions of the United States]]\n*[[List of U.S. states by religiosity]]\n*[[Southern Baptist Convention]]\n*[[Quran Belt]]\n*[[Rust Belt]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|40em}}\n* Balmer, Randall H. (2002). Encyclopedia of Evangelicalism. Westminster John Knox Press.\n* Christine Leigh H, (1997), Southern Cross: The Beginnings of the Bible Belt. Knopf.\n* Denman, Stan. (2004). Political Playing for the Soul of the American South: Theater and the Maintenance of Cultural Hegemony in the American Bible Belt. Southern Quarterly, 42(3), 64-72.\n* Hayes, Turner Elizabeth. (1997). Women, Culture and Community: Religion and Reform in Galveston 1880-1920, Oxford University Press.\n* Heatwole, Charles A. (1978). The Bible Belt; a problem of regional definition. Journal of Geography, 77, 50-55.\n* Hill, Samuel S., Lippy, Charles H. & Wilson, Charles R. (2005). Encyclopedia Of Religion In The South. Mercer University Press.\n* Lippy, Charles, H. (1993). Religion in South Carolina. University of South Carolina.\n* Marsden, George M. (1982). Fundamentalism and American Culture: The Shaping of Twentieth-Century Evangelicalism, 1870-1925. Oxford University Press.\n* Moran, Jeffrey P. (2004). The Scopes Trial and Southern Fundamentalism in Black and White: Race, Region, and Religion. Journal of Southern History, 70(1), 95.\n* Park, Chris C. (1994). Sacred Worlds: An Introduction to Geography and Religion. Routledge.\n* Pettersson, Thorleif & Hamberg, Eva M. (1997). Denominational Pluralism and Church Membership in Contemporary Sweden. Journal of Empirical Theology, 10(2), 61-78.\n* Sparks, Randy J. (2001). Religion in Mississippi. University Press of Mississippi for the Mississippi Historical Society.\n* Stacey, Williams A. & Shupe, Anson. (1984). Religious Values and Religiosity in the Textbook Adoption Controversy in Texas, 1981. Review of Religious Research. 25(4), 321-333.\n* Tweedie, Stephen W. (1978). Viewing the Bible Belt. THE Journal of Popular Culture, 11(4), 865-876.\n{{refend}}\n{{Regions of the world}}\n{{U.S. Belt regions}}\n\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1920s]]\n[[Category:Cultural regions]]\n[[Category:Christianity in the United States]]\n[[Category:Evangelicalism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Christian fundamentalism]]\n[[Category:Religion in the Southern United States]]\n[[Category:Regions of the Southern United States]]\n[[Category:Belt regions of the United States]]\n[[Category:Conservatism in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Gospel Music Associationclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bible_Belt"}
{"title_page": "Jimmie Davis", "text_new": "{{Other people|James Davis}}\n{{short description|Singer and Louisiana governor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Jimmie Davis\n|image         = Jimmie Davis 1962.jpg\n|caption       = Davis in 1962\n|order         = 47th [[List of governors of Louisiana|Governor of Louisiana]]\n|term_start    = May 9, 1944\n|term_end      = May 11, 1948\n|lieutenant    = [[J. Emile Verret]]\n|predecessor   = [[Sam H. Jones]]\n|successor     = [[Earl Long|Earl K. Long]]\n|term_start2   = May 10, 1960\n|term_end2     = May 12, 1964\n|lieutenant2   = [[Clarence C. Aycock|Clarence C. \"Taddy\" Aycock]]\n|predecessor2  = [[Earl Long|Earl K. Long]]\n|successor2    = [[John McKeithen]]\n|birth_name    = James Houston Davis\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1899|9|11}}\n|birth_place   = [[Jackson Parish, Louisiana]], U.S.\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|2000|11|5|1899|9|11}}\n|death_place   = [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]], U.S.\n|resting_place = Jimmie Davis Tabernacle Cemetery, east of [[Jonesboro, Louisiana|Jonesboro]], Louisiana\n|spouse        = {{ubl|Alvern Adams Davis (died 1967)|Anna Carter Gordon Davis (married 1969-2000, his death)}}\n|children      = 1\n|profession    = Singer, songwriter, former educator, politician\n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|footnotes =\n|education = [[Louisiana College]] {{small|(BA)}}<br />[[Louisiana State University]] {{small|(MA)}}\n}}\n\n[[Image:Jimmie Davis homestead c. 1900 in Jackson Parish, LA IMG 5816.JPG|right|thumb|Davis homestead in [[Jackson Parish, Louisiana|Jackson Parish]]]]\n\n'''James Houston Davis''' (September 11, 1899 \u2013 November 5, 2000) was an American politician and a singer and songwriter of both sacred and popular songs.  Davis was elected for two nonconsecutive terms from 1944 to 1948 and from 1960 to 1964 as the [[governor of Louisiana|governor]] of his native [[Louisiana]]. He ran both campaigns as a controversial advocate for impoverished and rural white Louisianians.\n\nDavis was a nationally popular [[country music]] and [[gospel singer]] from the 1930s into the 1960s, occasionally recording and performing as late as the early 1990s. He appeared as himself in a number of Hollywood movies. He was inducted into six halls of fame, including the [[Country Music Hall of Fame]], the [[Southern Gospel Music Association]] Hall of Fame, and the [[Louisiana Music Hall of Fame]]. At the time of his death in 2000, he was the oldest living former governor as well as the last living governor to have been born in the 19th century.\n\n==Early life==\nDavis was born to a [[sharecropping]] couple, the former Sarah Elizabeth Works (1877\u20131965) and Samuel Jones Davis (1873\u20131945), in Beech Springs, southeast of [[Quitman, Louisiana|Quitman]] in [[Jackson Parish, Louisiana|Jackson Parish]], north Louisiana. It is now a ghost town.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wargs.com/other/davisjh.html|title=Ancestry of Jimmie Davis|website=Wargs.com|accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe family was so poor that young Jimmie did not have a bed in which to sleep until he was nine years old. Davis was not sure of his date of birth; according to the ''[[New York Times]]'', \"Various newspaper and magazine articles over the last 70 years said he was born in 1899, 1901, 1902 or 1903. He told The New York Times several years ago that his sharecropper parents could never recall just when he was born \u2013 he was, after all, one of 11 children \u2013 and that he had not had the slightest idea when it really was.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/11/06/us/jimmie-davis-louisiana-s-singing-governor-is-dead.html|title=Jimmie Davis, Louisiana's Singing Governor, Is Dead|date=November 6, 2000|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/nov/07/local/me-48244|title=Jimmie Davis; 'Singing Governor' Spread Sunshine|first=MYRNA|last=OLIVER|date=November 7, 2000|accessdate=July 17, 2016|newspaper=[[LA Times]]}}</ref> The birth date listed on his Country Music Hall of Fame plaque is September 11, 1902.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.ha.com/itm/music-memorabilia/awards/jimmie-davis-country-music-hall-of-fame-plaque-presented-to-country-gospel-singer-songwriter-former-louisiana-governor-jim/a/622-21201.s|title=Jimmie Davis Country Music Hall of Fame Plaque. Presented - Lot #21201 - Heritage Auctions|accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref> The 1900 US Census recorded his birth as September 1899, which his parents would have told the census taker.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nDavis graduated from Beech Springs High School and the [[New Orleans, Louisiana|New Orleans]] campus of Soule Business College. Davis received his [[bachelor's degree]] in history from the [[Baptist]]-affiliated [[Louisiana College]] in [[Pineville, Louisiana|Pineville]] in [[Rapides Parish, Louisiana|Rapides Parish]]. He received a master's degree from [[Louisiana State University]] in [[Baton Rouge]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nHis 1927 master's thesis, which examines the intelligence levels of different races, is titled ''Comparative Intelligence of Whites, Blacks and Mulattoes.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lsu.louislibraries.org:5203/uhtbin/cgisirsi/x/0/0/57/5/3?searchdata1=1955955{CKEY}&searchfield1=GENERAL^SUBJECT^GENERAL^^&user_id=WEBSERVER|title=Item Display - Comparative intelligence of whites, blacks and mulattoes|website=Lsu.louislibraries.org:5203|date=2003-08-21|accessdate=2013-07-01}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nDuring the late 1920s, Davis taught history (and, unofficially, [[yodeling]]) for a year at the former [[Dodd College|Dodd College for Girls]] in [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]].{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} The college president, [[Monroe E. Dodd]], who was also the pastor of the large First Baptist Church of Shreveport and a pioneer radio preacher, invited Davis to join the faculty.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Musical career==\nDavis became a commercially successful singer of rural music before he entered politics. His early work was in the style of country music singer [[Jimmie Rodgers (country singer)|Jimmie Rodgers]]. Davis was also known for recording energetic and raunchy [[blues]] tunes such as \"Red Nightgown Blues\". Some of these records included slide guitar accompaniment by black bluesman [[Oscar \"Buddy\" Woods]]. During his first run for governor, opponents reprinted the lyrics of some of these songs in order to undermine Davis's campaign. In one case, anti-Davis forces played some records over an outdoor sound system, only to give up after the crowds started dancing, ignoring the double-entendre lyrics. Until the end of his life, Davis never denied or repudiated those records.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nIn 1999, \"[[You Are My Sunshine]]\" was honored with a [[Grammy Hall of Fame Award]], and the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] named it one of the [[Songs of the Century]]. \"You Are My Sunshine\" was ranked in 2003 as No. 73 on ''CMT's 100 Greatest Songs in Country Music''.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nUntil his death, Davis insisted that he wrote the song. It will be associated with him. [[Virginia Shehee]], a Shreveport [[business]]woman, [[philanthropist]], and [[Louisiana State Senate|state senator]], introduced legislation to designate \"You Are My Sunshine\" as the official state song.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/shreveporttimes/obituary.aspx?n=virginia-ruth-kilpatrick-shehee&pid=175240971&fhid=10218|title=Virginia Ruth Kilpatrick Shehee|newspaper=[[The Times (Shreveport)|The Shreveport Times]]|accessdate=July 9, 2015}}</ref> The song was reportedly written for Elizabeth Selby, a resident of Urbana, IL and housemother of Wescoga, Wesley Co-Op for Gals at the time the song was written.\n\nDavis often performed during his campaign stops when running for governor of Louisiana. After being elected in 1944, he became known as the \"singing governor.\" While governor, he had a No. 1 hit single in 1945 with \"[[There's a New Moon Over My Shoulder]]\". Davis recorded for the [[Victor Talking Machine Company]], and [[Decca Records]] for decades and released more than 40 albums.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nA long-time [[Southern Baptist]], Davis recorded a number of [[Southern gospel]] albums. In 1967 he served as president of the Gospel Music Association. He was a close friend of the [[North Dakota]]-born band leader [[Lawrence Welk]], who frequently reminded viewers of his television program of his association with Davis.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nA number of his songs were used as part of motion picture soundtracks. Davis appeared in half a dozen films, including one starring [[Ozzie and Harriet]], who had a TV series under their names. Members of Davis's last band included [[Allen \"Puddler\" Harris]] of [[Lake Charles, Louisiana|Lake Charles]]. He had served as pianist for singer [[Ricky Nelson]] early in his career.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nHe was also a close acquaintance of the country singer-songwriter [[Hank Williams]], with whom he authored the top-10 hit<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hpcisp.com/~turp/egbbcharts.html|title=Articles|website=Hpcisp.com|accessdate=December 31, 2019}}</ref> \"[[(I Heard That) Lonesome Whistle]]\" back in 1951, supposedly on a fishing day they spent together.\n\n===Singles===\n[[File:Jimmie Davis Hall of Fame plaque, 2003 IMG 6904.JPG|thumb|Davis was [[Posthumous recognition|posthumously]] inducted in 2003 into the [[Delta Music Museum]] Hall of Fame in [[Ferriday, Louisiana]]]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Single\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| <small>[[Hot Country Songs|US Country]]</small>\n|-\n| 1937\n| \"Nobody's Darling but Mine\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1938\n| \"Meet Me Tonight in Dreamland\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n|-\n| \"There's a Gold Mine in the Sky\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.45worlds.com/78rpm/record/5473|title=78 Record: Jimmie Davis - There's A Gold Mine In The Sky (1938)|website=45worlds.com|accessdate=December 31, 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n|-\n| 1940\n| \"[[You Are My Sunshine]]\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1944\n| \"Is It Too Late Now\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3\n|-\n| \"There's a Chill on the Hill Tonight\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4\n|-\n| 1945\n| \"[[There's a New Moon Over My Shoulder]]\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\n|-\n| 1946\n| \"Grievin' My Heart Out for You\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4\n|-\n| 1947\n| \"Bang Bang\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4\n|-\n| 1951\n| \"[[(I Heard That) Lonesome Whistle]]\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9\n|-\n| 1962\n| \"Where the Old Red River Flows\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 15\n|}\n\n==Political career==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=January 2018}}\n[[File:Cork oak tree planted and dedicated by the Honorable Jimmie H. Davis.jpg|thumbnail|left|Cork oak tree planted and dedicated by the Honorable Davis]]\nDavis was elected in 1938 as Shreveport's public safety commissioner. At the time, Shreveport had the [[city commission]] form of government. After four years in Shreveport City Hall, Davis was elected in 1942 to the [[Louisiana Public Service Commission]]. The rate-making body meets in the capital, Baton Rouge. He was elected during his term as governor and left after two years.\n\n===First term as governor (1944\u20131948)===\n{{See also|Louisiana gubernatorial election, 1944}}\nDavis was elected governor as a Democrat in 1944. Among those eliminated in the primary were [[Louisiana State Legislature|State Senator]] [[Ernest S. Clements]] of [[Oberlin, Louisiana|Oberlin]] in [[Allen Parish, Louisiana|Allen Parish]], freshman [[U.S. Representative]] [[James H. Morrison]] of [[Hammond, Louisiana|Hammond]] in [[Tangipahoa Parish]], and [[Sam Caldwell]], the [[List of mayors of Shreveport, Louisiana|mayor of Shreveport]]. Davis and Caldwell had served together earlier in Shreveport municipal government.\n\nIn the [[runoff election|runoff]], Davis defeated [[Lewis L. Morgan]], an elderly attorney and former [[U.S. representative]] from [[Covington, Louisiana|Covington]], the seat of [[St. Tammany Parish]], who had been backed by former Governor [[Earl Kemp Long]] and [[mayor of New Orleans|New Orleans Mayor]] [[Robert Maestri]]. In the runoff, Davis received 251,228 (53.6 percent) to Morgan's 217,915 (46.4 percent).\n\nDavis recruited [[Chris Faser, Jr.]], a young staff member of the Public Service Commission, to manage his gubernatorial race and act as his chief of staff. Faser became the \"go-to\" guy to obtain access to the governor.<ref>{{cite news|title=Christian Faser, Jr. (1917-2004)|work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|Baton Rouge Morning Advocate]]|date=January 18, 2004}}</ref>\n\nDavis pleased white liberals with his appointments to high positions of two of the leaders of the [[impeachment]] effort against [[Huey Long|Huey Pierce Long Jr.]] He named [[Cecil Morgan]] of Shreveport to the Louisiana Civil Service Commission. Morgan was succeeded in the Louisiana House by [[Rupert Peyton]] of Shreveport, who also served as an aide to Davis. In addition, Davis retained the anti-Long [[Ralph Norman Bauer]] of [[St. Mary Parish, Louisiana|St. Mary Parish]] as House speaker, a selection made originally in 1940 by Sam Jones.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nDavis reached out to the Longites when he commuted the prison sentence imposed on former LSU President [[James Monroe Smith]], convicted in the [[Louisiana Hayride scandals]] of the late 1930s. Like Davis, Smith was a native of Jackson Parish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lahistory.org/site36.php|title=Smith, James Monroe|work=A Dictionary of Louisiana Biography ([[Louisiana Historical Association]])|accessdate=March 25, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716204559/http://www.lahistory.org/site36.php|archive-date=July 16, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nEarl Long was seeking the [[Lieutenant Governor of Louisiana|lieutenant governorship]] on the Lewis Morgan \"ticket\" and led in the first primary in 1944, but he lost the runoff to [[J. Emile Verret]] of [[New Iberia, Louisiana|New Iberia]], then the president of the [[Iberia Parish School Board]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nDavis kept his hand in show business, and set a record for absenteeism during his first term. He made numerous trips to [[Hollywood]] to make Western \"[[horse operas]].\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mathur |first=Monika |date=June 23, 2009|title=A look at odd behavior by US governors|journal=Associated Press|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5jQ7_25-eKs8eU2rs504vDLRpD6dAD990JHEG0|accessdate=January 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nUnder the state constitution, Davis was [[term limit|term-limited]] to a single non-consecutive term in office.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n===The election of 1959\u20131960===\n{{See also|Louisiana gubernatorial election, 1959-60}}\nWhen he became a candidate for a second term in 1959\u201360, Davis had been out of office for nearly a dozen years. In a later study of this election, three Louisiana State University [[political science|political scientist]]s described him by the following:\n\n<blockquote>Davis has all the external attributes of a \"man of the people\", but his serious political connections seem to be with the [parish-seat] elite and its allies, particularly the major industrial combinations of the state. He is in many respects a toned-down version of the old-style southern politician who could spellbound the mass of voters into supporting him regardless of the effects of his programs on their welfare. ... Davis creates the perfect image of a man to be trusted and one whose intense calm is calculated to bring rational balance into the political life of the state.<ref>William C. Havard, Rudolf Heberle, and [[Perry H. Howard]], ''The Louisiana Elections of 1960'', [[Baton Rouge]]: [[Louisiana State University]] Studies, 1963, pg. 40</ref></blockquote>\n\nDavis was running at a time when African Americans in the civil rights movement were seeking social justice and restoration of their constitutional rights. In 1954 the US Supreme Court had ruled in ''[[Brown v. Board of Education]]'' that segregation in public schools was unconstitutional and urged states to integrate their facilities. With a pledge to fight for continued [[Racial segregation in the United States|segregation]] in public education, Davis won the Democratic [[gubernatorial]] nomination over a crowded field.\n\nIt included fellow segregationist State Senator [[William M. Rainach]] of [[Claiborne Parish, Louisiana|Claiborne Parish]], former Lieutenant Governor [[Bill Dodd]] of [[Baton Rouge]], former Governor [[James A. Noe]] of [[Monroe, Louisiana|Monroe]], and [[mayor of New Orleans|New Orleans Mayor]] [[deLesseps Story Morrison]]. [[Addison Roswell Thompson]], the operator of a New Orleans [[taxicab]] stand and a member of the [[Ku Klux Klan]], also filed candidacy papers.\n\nDavis ran second in the primary to [[deLesseps Story Morrison|\"Chep\" Morrison]], considered an anti-Long liberal by Louisiana standards. He defeated Morrison in the party runoff held on January 9, 1960. As African Americans (who had supported the Republican Party after the Civil War) were still largely [[Disfranchisement after Reconstruction era|disenfranchised]] in Louisiana, the Democratic primary was the only competitive race for office in the one-party state.\n\nIn the first round of balloting, Davis polled 213,551 (25.3 percent) to Morrison's 278,956 (33.1 percent). Rainach ran third with 143,095 (17 percent). Noe finished fourth with 97,654 (11.6 percent), and Dodd followed with 85,436 (10.1 percent). Davis won the northern and central parts of the state plus Baton Rouge, while Morrison dominated the southern portion of the state, particularly the French cultural parishes. In the runoff, Davis prevailed, 487,681 (54.1 percent) to Morrison's 414,110 (45.5 percent). It was estimated that Davis drew virtually all the Rainach support from the first primary.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nEarl Long endorsed Davis in the runoff in part because he had a longstanding personal dislike of Morrison. Long's gubernatorial running-mate, James A. Noe, who finished fourth in the primary, stood with Morrison,<ref>\"Noe Gives Support to Morrison\", ''The Shreveport Times'', December 10, 1959, pg. 1</ref> as did the fifth-place gubernatorial candidate and former Long lieutenant governor, Bill Dodd.<ref>\"Dodd Announces Endorsement for Morrison Ticket\", ''The Shreveport Times'', December 8, 1959, pg. 1</ref>\n\nRainach and his unsuccessful candidate for state comptroller, later U.S. Representative [[Joe D. Waggonner]], both endorsed Davis on the premise that Davis would be a stronger segregationist than Morrison.<ref>''Minden Herald'', December 31, 1959.</ref> Davis had avoided segregationist rhetoric in the first primary race in 1959. According to Morrison, the singer had sought support from the [[NAACP]] in New Orleans and [[Lake Charles, Louisiana|Lake Charles]].<ref>\"Morrison Says Davis Sought NAACP Support\", ''The Shreveport Times'', December 16, 1959, pg. 10A.</ref>\n\nIn the runoff with Morrison, Davis tried to identify as a more determined and dedicated segregationist than his rival. Morrison questioned Davis's change in campaign strategy and also appealed to segregationists. Morrison charged that Davis had \"operated an integrated [[honky-tonk]] in [[California]]\", when Davis was out of state with his singing career. Morrison also said that Davis had allowed the illegal operation of nine thousand [[slot machine]]s when Davis was governor during the 1940s.<ref>\"Beaten Candidates Give Endorsements\", ''The Shreveport Times'', December 11, 1959, pg. 5-A.</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, Earl Long had run unsuccessfully for lieutenant governor in the first primary in 1959. There was a runoff between Morrison's choice for the job, Alexandria Mayor [[W. George Bowdon Jr.]], and Davis's selection, former state House Speaker [[Taddy Aycock|Clarence C. \"Taddy\" Aycock]] of [[Franklin, Louisiana|Franklin]], [[St. Mary Parish, Louisiana|St. Mary Parish]]. Aycock defeated Bowdon by a margin similar to the plurality of Davis over Morrison. The defeat was Long's second for lieutenant governor. He had lost in the 1944 primary to [[J. Emile Verret]] of [[Iberia Parish, Louisiana|Iberia Parish]], who served in the second-ranking position in the first Davis administration.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nDavis effectively used the slogan \"He's One of Us\" in the gubernatorial race. Number 6 on the ballot, he assembled an intraparty [[Ticket (politics)|ticket]] for other statewide constitutional officers, including Aycock for lieutenant governor, [[Roy R. Theriot]] of [[Abbeville, Louisiana|Abbeville]] for comptroller, [[Douglas Fowler]] of [[Coushatta, Louisiana|Coushatta]] for custodian of voting machines, [[Jack P.F. Gremillion]] for [[Attorney General of Louisiana|attorney general]], [[Dave L. Pearce]], originally from [[West Carroll Parish, Louisiana|West Carroll Parish]], for agriculture commissioner, [[Ellen Bryan Moore]] for register of state lands, and [[Rufus D. Hayes]] for insurance commissioner; the latter four were all based in Baton Rouge. The entire Davis ticket was elected.<ref>Davis exhibit, Delta Music Museum, [[Ferriday, Louisiana|Ferriday]], Louisiana.</ref>\n\nIn their study ''The Louisiana Election of 1960'', William C. Havard, Rudolf Heberle, and [[Perry H. Howard]] demonstrated that Davis built his second-primary victory by narrowly edging Morrison in the eastern and western extremities of south Louisiana. Davis secured the backing of [[organized labor]] and made inroads among the white, urban working class, which would have been essential to a Morrison victory. In the seven urban industrial parishes, which then comprised some 46.5 percent of the total turnout, Davis topped Morrison by 7,368 votes (50.8 percent) of the 419,537 applicable subtotal. {{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nMorrison polled 60 percent in his own Orleans Parish and 54.6 percent in adjacent [[suburban]] [[Jefferson Parish, Louisiana|Jefferson Parish]], but in the industrial strip and in more Protestant areas, Morrison slipped. The second primary attracted 57,744 more votes than the initial stage of balloting, and analysts found that the lion's share of additional ballots were filed by segregationists who backed Davis.<ref>Havard, Heberle, and Havard, ''The Louisiana Election of 1960'', pp. 50\u201352.<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed --></ref>\n\nIn the general election held on April 19, 1960, Davis defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Francis Grevemberg]], a [[Lafayette, Louisiana|Lafayette]] native, by a margin of nearly 82\u201317 percent. Grevemberg had been head of the state police under Democratic Governor [[Robert F. Kennon]] and had gained a reputation for fighting [[organized crime]]. He called for a true two-party system for Louisiana. As the Democratic nominee in the nearly one-party state, Davis faced no serious political threat and did little campaigning against Grevemberg.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nIt has been reported that had General [[Curtis LeMay]] turned down [[George C. Wallace]]'s offer to be his candidate for vice president in 1968 on the [[American Independent Party]] ticket, that Wallace was ready to announce Davis as his selection for vice president. Other sources say Wallace's second choice was the former [[governor of Arkansas]], [[Orval Faubus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,902367,00.html|title=The Campaign: George's General|date=October 11, 1968|website=Content.time.com|accessdate=December 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Davis and Dodd====\nIn the 1959 campaign, Bill Dodd had attacked Davis ferociously: it was part of Dodd's strategy to get Davis to withdraw from the primary. \"Nothing personal in his [Dodd's] heart, just a cold-blooded plan to wind up in a second primary against Morrison, who he figured could not win against anyone [else] in a runoff,\" said Davis in the introduction to Dodd's memoirs, ''Peapatch Politics: The Earl Long Era in Louisiana Politics''.\n\nDodd endorsed Morrison in the runoff, but he had a long-term reason for this decision. Dodd planned to run for school superintendent in the 1963 primary, and he wanted to have at least the neutrality of Morrison four years thereafter.\n\nDodd and Davis later became close friends. In Davis' words:\n\n<blockquote>Bill and I have many things in common. We share the same type of religion and boyhood background; we got our start as schoolteachers and figured prominently in public education; we both served in public life at or near the top. And I like to feel that we share a common appreciation and respect for people, all people. One of the greatest rewards in politics is meeting people. And one of the greatest and most unusual men I've ever met is Bill Dodd.</blockquote>\n\n===Second term (1960\u20131964)===\nDavis' appointees in the second term included outgoing State Representative [[Claude Kirkpatrick]] of [[Jennings, Louisiana|Jennings]], who was named to succeed [[Lorris M. Wimberly]] as the Director of Public Works. In that capacity, Kirkpatrick took the steps for a joint agreement with [[State of Texas|Texas]] to establish the popular [[Toledo Bend Reservoir]], a haven for [[boating]] and fishing. Mrs. Kirkpatrick, the former [[Edith Killgore Kirkpatrick|Edith Killgore]], a native of Claiborne Parish, headed Davis' women's campaign division for southwestern Louisiana. He appointed Alexandria businessman Morgan W. Walker, Sr., to the State Mineral Board. Walker founded a company which later became part of [[Continental Trailways]] [[Bus]] lines. Davis named as state highway director [[Ray Burgess]] of Baton Rouge, who considered running for governor in the 1963 primary.\n\nAs part of his support of segregation, Davis initiated passage of state legislation to create the [[Louisiana State Sovereignty Commission]], which operated from 1960 to 1967. It \"espoused states rights, anti-communist and segregationist ideas, with a particular focus on maintaining the status quo in race relations. It was closely allied with the Louisiana Joint Legislative Committee on Un-American Activities.\"<ref name=\"amistad\">[http://amistadresearchcenter.tulane.edu/archon/?p=creators/creator&id=1129 \"Louisiana State Sovereignty Commission\"], Amistad Research Center, Tulane University; Sources: Adam Fairclough. ''Race and Democracy: The Civil Rights Struggle in Louisiana, 1915-1972''. Athens, GA: University of Georgia Press, 1995.</ref> It was modeled after Mississippi's commission, established in 1956 to resist integration. Davis tapped [[Frank Voelker Jr.]], City Attorney of [[Lake Providence, Louisiana|Lake Providence]], to chair the newly established Commission. It was given unusual {{clarify|date=January 2018}} powers to investigate state citizens, and used its authority to exert economic pressure to suppress civil rights activists. Voelker left the commission in 1963 to run for governor but placed poorly in the primary; he withdrew and supported other candidates.<ref>Havard, Heberle, and Howard, ''The Louisiana Election of 1960'', pg. 99<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed, if any --></ref>\n\nIn his second term, Davis chose veteran Representative [[J. Thomas Jewell]] of [[New Roads, Louisiana|New Roads]] in [[Pointe Coupee Parish, Louisiana|Pointe Coupee Parish]] as [[Speaker of the Louisiana House of Representatives|House Speaker]] to succeed [[Bob Angelle]]. Davis secured passage of a $60&nbsp;million public improvements [[bond issue]] through the State Board and Building Commission, an organization controlled by the governor. He gained legislative support from many formerly pro-Long lawmakers and cemented his hold on the traditional anti-Long bloc. He avoided defeat on any legislation that he strongly supported and was able to defeat nearly all bills with which he did not concur.\n\nHe offered tacit support to Presidents [[John F. Kennedy]] and [[Lyndon B. Johnson]], national Democrats, to secure the state's hold of pending offshore oil revenues. In the 1963 legislative fiscal session, he defeated efforts to procure an unpledged presidential elector slate for the 1964 general election, by which time he had been succeeded by [[John J. McKeithen]].<ref>Havard, Heberle, and Howard, ''The Louisiana Elections of 1960'', pp. 90\u201392.<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed, if any --></ref>\n\n===Fourth place in 1971===\n{{Main|Louisiana gubernatorial election, 1971-72}}\nIn 1971, Davis entered another crowded Democratic [[gubernatorial]] primary field with new political prospects, but he finished in fourth place with 138,756 ballots (11.8 percent).\n\nIn a runoff election held in December 1971, U.S. Representative [[Edwin Washington Edwards]] of [[Crowley, Louisiana|Crowley]], [[Acadia Parish, Louisiana|Acadia Parish]], defeated then state Senator [[Bennett Johnston|J. Bennett Johnston Jr.]], of Shreveport for the party nomination. That vote was close: Edwards, 584,262 (50.2 percent) to Johnston's 579,774 (49.8 percent). Edwards beat Republican [[David C. Treen]] in the state general election held on February 1, 1972. By that time, Davis' days as a politician were clearly behind him.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nToward the end of his life, longtime Democrat Davis endorsed at least two Republican candidates after the state's voters had gone through a political realignment. By the late 20th century, white conservatives in the state largely supported the Republican Party. In 1996 Davis endorsed Republican state representative [[Woody Jenkins]] of Baton Rouge for the U.S. Senate against Democrat [[Mary Landrieu]] of New Orleans, and Governor [[Murphy J. Foster, Jr.|Murphy J. \"Mike\" Foster, Jr.]] seeking re-election in 1999. His opponent was African-American Democratic Congressman [[Bill Jefferson]] of New Orleans.<ref>Susie Labry, 1995<!-- page(s)?? --></ref>\n\n===Political legacy===\nDavis established a State Retirement System and funding of more than $100&nbsp;million in public improvements, while leaving the state with a $38&nbsp;million surplus after his first term.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sec.state.la.us/67.htm|title=Louisiana Secretary of State<!-- Bot generated title -->|accessdate=July 17, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070812153046/http://www.sec.state.la.us/67.htm|archivedate=August 12, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring his second term, Davis built the [[Sunshine Bridge]], the new [[Louisiana Governor's Mansion]], and [[Toledo Bend Reservoir]], all criticized at the time, but later recognized as beneficial to the state. Davis coordinated the pay periods of state employees, who had sometimes received their checks a week late, a particular hardship to those with low earnings.\n\nEarl Long once remarked that Davis was so relaxed and low-key that one could not \"wake up Jimmie Davis with an earthquake\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/05/08/opinion/carville-democrats-could-lose/index.html|title=Carville: Wake up Democrats; you could lose |website=Cnn.com|author=James Carville|accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPublic relations specialist [[Gus Weill]], who worked in the Davis campaign in 1959, wrote a biography of the former governor in 1977, entitled ''You Are My Sunshine,'' based on Davis' best-known song.<ref>''You Are My Sunshine: The Jimmie Davis Story, An Affectionate Biography'' ([[Baton Rouge]]: [[Pelican Publishing Company]], 1977); {{ISBN|0882896601}} (0-88289-660-1)</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[Image:Eglin House in Shreveport IMG 1571.JPG|200px|right|thumb|Davis married the former Alvern Adams in this historic Shreveport house in the Highlands neighborhood. It was formerly owned by the Eglins, the maternal grandparents of [[John McKeithen|John J. McKeithen]].<ref>Source: Historic marker, Eglin House in Shreveport</ref>]]\n\nDavis's first wife, the former Alvern Adams, the daughter of a physician in Shreveport, was the first lady while he was governor during both terms. Two years after her death in 1967, Davis married Anna Gordon, born Effie Juanita Carter (February 15, 1917 &ndash; March 5, 2004). A founding member of the gospel quartet ''The Chuck Wagon Gang'' along with her father and two of her brothers, she had been given the stage name \"Anna\" during the mid-1930s.  Davis was a longtime fan of the group, who were gospel music pioneers with more than 36 million records sold in forty years of affiliation with [[Columbia Records]].  \n\nOut of office, Davis resided primarily in Baton Rouge but made numerous singing appearances, particularly in churches throughout the United States.\n[[Image:Jimmie Davis grave marker IMG 5808.JPG|200px|right|thumb|Davis grave located in small cemetery behind the tabernacle]]\n\nDavis died on November 5, 2000. He had suffered a fall in his home some ten months earlier and may have had a [[stroke]] in his last days. He is interred alongside his first wife at the Jimmie Davis Tabernacle Cemetery in his native Beech Springs community near Quitman. Jim Davis was cremated.<ref name=mtvcom>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1472470/my-sunshine-singer-jimmie-davis-dead-at-101.jhtml|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130129170747/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1472470/my-sunshine-singer-jimmie-davis-dead-at-101.jhtml|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 29, 2013|title=\"Sunshine\" singer Jimmie Davis dead at 101|website=Mtv.com|accessdate=October 21, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/thenewsstar/obituary.aspx?n=james-william-davis&pid=160920202|title=James William Davis obituary|newspaper=[[Monroe News Star]]|accessdate=November 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDavis was aged 101 years and 55 days,<ref name=mtvcom/> which made him the longest-lived of all U.S. state governors at the time of his death. Davis held this record until March 18, 2011, when [[Albert Rosellini]] of [[Washington (state)|Washington]] achieved a greater lifespan of 101 years, 56 days.\n\n==Honors==\n[[Image:Jimmie Davis Bridge, Shreveport, LA IMG 1555.JPG|200px|thumb|The Jimmie Davis Bridge over the [[Red River of the South|Red River]] on Louisiana State Highway 511, connecting [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]] and [[Bossier City, Louisiana|Bossier City]]]]\n\n[[Image:Jimmie Davis Tabernacle, LA IMG 5817.JPG|200px|right|thumb|Jimmie Davis Tabernacle west of [[Quitman, Louisiana|Quitman]]]]\n\nThe Jimmie Davis Bridge over the [[Red River of the South|Red River]] connects Shreveport and [[Bossier City, Louisiana|Bossier City]] via Louisiana Highway 511. It was named in his honor during his second term as governor.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nThe Jimmie Davis Tabernacle is located near Weston in Jackson Parish. The tabernacle hosts occasional gospel singing. At the site is a replica of the Davis homestead (c. 1900) and of the Peckerwood Hill Store, an old [[general store]] that served the community.\n\n[[Jimmie Davis State Park]] is located on Caney Lake (not to be confused with [[Caney Lakes Recreation Area]] near [[Minden, Louisiana|Minden]]) southwest of [[Chatham, Louisiana|Chatham]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nDavis was [[Posthumous recognition|posthumously]] inducted into the [[Delta Music Museum]] Hall of Fame in [[Ferriday, Louisiana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deltamusicmuseum.com/inductees.html|title=Inductees|website=Deltamusicmuseum.com|accessdate=December 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDavis was inducted into the [[Nashville Songwriters Hall of Fame]] in 1971, the [[Country Music Hall of Fame]] in 1972, the [[Southern Gospel Music Association]] Hall of Fame in 1997 and The [[Louisiana Music Hall of Fame]] in 2008.\n\nIn 1993, Davis was among the first thirteen inductees of the [[Louisiana Political Museum and Hall of Fame]] in [[Winnfield, Louisiana|Winnfield]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofwinnfield.com/museum.html|title=Louisiana Political Museum and Hall of Fame|website=Cityofwinnfield.com|accessdate=August 22, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090703054258/http://cityofwinnfield.com/museum.html|archivedate=July 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe Hall of Fame periodically issues the \"Friends of Jimmie Davis Award\". In 2005, the award was presented to then [[U.S. Senator]] [[Ted Stevens]], an [[Alaska]] Republican, who once hosted Davis in a concert at the [[Kennedy Center]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] Speaking at the Louisiana Political Museum and Hall of Fame, Stevens recalled having been with both Davis and [[Ronald W. Reagan]], when Reagan was contemplating his first run for [[governor of California]] and asked Davis for political advice. Stevens joined the Jimmie Davis Band in a rendition of \"You Are My Sunshine\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepineywoods.com/HallFameF05.htm|title=Tom Kelly, \"Winnfield opens Civic Center with \"Hall\" event: Renovated forestry building is modern, ready to serve for years into the future\", February 2005|website=Thepineywoods.com|accessdate=February 6, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140628232133/http://www.thepineywoods.com/HallFameF05.htm|archive-date=June 28, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe 2006 recipient of the \"Friends of Jimmie Davis\" award was the late former State Senator [[B.G. Dyess]], a Baptist minister from [[Rapides Parish, Louisiana|Rapides Parish]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n \nThe Davis archives of papers and photographs is housed in the \"You Are My Sunshine\" Collection of the Linus A. Sims Memorial Library at [[Southeastern Louisiana University]] in Hammond.<ref>[http://www.selu.edu/acad_research/programs/csls/historical_collections/photo_collections/c_d_photos/davis_jimmie.html Davis Collection at Southeastern], Selu.edu, (retrieved 2012-05-06).</ref>\n\nDavis believed that his singing career enhanced his political prospects. He once told [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] Republican [[Ronnie Thompson (Georgia politician)|Ronnie Thompson]], a mayor of [[Macon, Georgia|Macon]]: \"If you want to have any success in politics, sing softly and carry a big guitar,\" a play on an old [[Theodore Roosevelt]] [[adage]].<ref>Davis, quoted in Eric Welch, \"Gospel-singing Jeweler Is 'Country' Candidate\", ''Macon Telegraph'', 1967 August 26, p. A1.</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\nDavis had several appearances in movies (usually or always as himself), including:\n*1942: ''[[Strictly in the Groove]]'' \n*1942: ''[[Riding Through Nevada]]'' \n*1943: ''[[Frontier Fury (1943 film)|Frontier Fury]]'' \n*1944: ''[[Cyclone Prairie Rangers]]'' \n*1947: ''[[Louisiana (1947 film)|Louisiana]]'' \n*1949: ''[[Mississippi Rhythm]]'' \n*1950: ''[[Square Dance Katy]]''\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|United States|Education|Music|Politics|Conservatism|Christianity}}\n* [[List of Governors of Louisiana]]\n* [[Jim Flynn (songwriter)|Jim Flynn]], a writer encouraged when Davis signed his first song writing contract\n\n==References and sources==\n\n===References===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* Toru Mitsui (1998). \"Jimmie Davis.\" In ''The Encyclopedia of Country Music.'' Paul Kingsbury, Ed. New York: Oxford University Press. p.&nbsp;136.\n* Kevin S. Fontenot, \"You Can't Fight a Song: Country Music in Jimmie Davis' Gubernatorial Campaigns,\" ''Journal of Country Music'' (2007).\n\n===External links===\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikisource author}}\n* {{IMDb name|204834|Jimmie Davis}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080110153727/http://www.sos.louisiana.gov/tabid/404/Default.aspx State of Louisiana Biography]\n* [http://www.la-cemeteries.com/Governors/Davis,%20James%20Houston/Davis,%20James%20Houston.shtml Cemetery Memorial] by La-Cemeteries\n* [https://archive.org/details/Jimmy_Davis-Shes_a_Real_Hum_Dinger Listen to Jimmie singing \"She's a Real Hum Dinger\"]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110418100814/http://countrymusichalloffame.org/full-list-of-inductees/view/jimmie-davis at the Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum]\n* [http://www.selu.edu/acad_research/programs/csls/historical_collections/archival_collections/c_d/davis_jimmie.html Jimmie Davis Collection] and [http://www.selu.edu/acad_research/programs/csls/historical_collections/photo_collections/c_d_photos/davis_jimmie.html Jimmie Davis Photo Collection] at [[Southeastern Louisiana University]] in [[Hammond, Louisiana|Hammond]].\n*{{Find a Grave|6370060}}\n*[[Southern Gospel Music Association]] Hall of Fame and Museum\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{Succession box|title=[[List of Governors of Louisiana|Governor of Louisiana]] | before=[[Sam H. Jones]]| after=[[Earl Long|Earl K. Long]] | years=May 9, 1944\u2013May 11, 1948}}\n{{Succession box|title=[[List of Governors of Louisiana|Governor of Louisiana]]\n|before=Earl K. Long| after=[[John McKeithen]] | years=May 10, 1960\u2013May 12, 1964}}\n{{s-hon}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Oldest living United States governor]]\n|before=[[J. Bracken Lee]]\n|after=[[Strom Thurmond]]\n|years=October 20, 1996 \u2013 November 5, 2000}}\n{{succession box\n|title=Oldest United States governor ever\n|before=[[Nellie Tayloe Ross]]\n|after=[[Albert Rosellini]]\n|years=October 2, 2000 \u2013 March 17, 2011}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{1970s Country Music Hall of Fame}}\n{{Governors of Louisiana}}\n{{Louisiana Political Museum and Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Jimmie}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:Educators from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:American actor-politicians]]\n[[Category:American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:American centenarians]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American gospel singers]]\n[[Category:Country Music Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Governors of Louisiana]]\n[[Category:People from Jackson Parish, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Shreveport, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Baton Rouge, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Louisiana College alumni]]\n[[Category:Louisiana State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Louisiana Democrats]]\n[[Category:Members of the Louisiana Public Service Commission]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American male composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American composers]]\n[[Category:American performers of Christian music]]\n[[Category:Southern gospel performers]]\n[[Category:Decca Records artists]]\n[[Category:Lawrence Welk]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Baton Rouge, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Shreveport, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American white supremacists]]\n[[Category:American anti-communists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|James Davis}}\n{{short description|Singer and Louisiana governor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Jimmie Davis\n|image         = Jimmie Davis 1962.jpg\n|caption       = Davis in 1962\n|order         = 47th [[List of governors of Louisiana|Governor of Louisiana]]\n|term_start    = May 9, 1944\n|term_end      = May 11, 1948\n|lieutenant    = [[J. Emile Verret]]\n|predecessor   = [[Sam H. Jones]]\n|successor     = [[Earl Long|Earl K. Long]]\n|term_start2   = May 10, 1960\n|term_end2     = May 12, 1964\n|lieutenant2   = [[Clarence C. Aycock|Clarence C. \"Taddy\" Aycock]]\n|predecessor2  = [[Earl Long|Earl K. Long]]\n|successor2    = [[John McKeithen]]\n|birth_name    = James Houston Davis\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1899|9|11}}\n|birth_place   = [[Jackson Parish, Louisiana]], U.S.\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|2000|11|5|1899|9|11}}\n|death_place   = [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]], U.S.\n|resting_place = Jimmie Davis Tabernacle Cemetery, east of [[Jonesboro, Louisiana|Jonesboro]], Louisiana\n|spouse        = {{ubl|Alvern Adams Davis (died 1967)|Anna Carter Gordon Davis (married 1969-2000, his death)}}\n|children      = 1\n|profession    = Singer, songwriter, former educator, politician\n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|footnotes =\n|education = [[Louisiana College]] {{small|(BA)}}<br />[[Louisiana State University]] {{small|(MA)}}\n}}\n\n[[Image:Jimmie Davis homestead c. 1900 in Jackson Parish, LA IMG 5816.JPG|right|thumb|Davis homestead in [[Jackson Parish, Louisiana|Jackson Parish]]]]\n\n'''James Houston Davis''' (September 11, 1899 \u2013 November 5, 2000) was an American politician and a singer and songwriter of both sacred and popular songs.  Davis was elected for two nonconsecutive terms from 1944 to 1948 and from 1960 to 1964 as the [[governor of Louisiana|governor]] of his native [[Louisiana]]. He ran both campaigns as a controversial advocate for impoverished and rural white Louisianians.\n\nDavis was a nationally popular [[country music]] and [[gospel singer]] from the 1930s into the 1960s, occasionally recording and performing as late as the early 1990s. He appeared as himself in a number of Hollywood movies. He was inducted into six halls of fame, including the [[Country Music Hall of Fame]], the [[Southern Gospel Music Association]] Hall of Fame, and the [[Louisiana Music Hall of Fame]]. At the time of his death in 2000, he was the oldest living former governor as well as the last living governor to have been born in the 19th century.\n\n==Early life==\nDavis was born to a [[sharecropping]] couple, the former Sarah Elizabeth Works (1877\u20131965) and Samuel Jones Davis (1873\u20131945), in Beech Springs, southeast of [[Quitman, Louisiana|Quitman]] in [[Jackson Parish, Louisiana|Jackson Parish]], north Louisiana. It is now a ghost town.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wargs.com/other/davisjh.html|title=Ancestry of Jimmie Davis|website=Wargs.com|accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe family was so poor that young Jimmie did not have a bed in which to sleep until he was nine years old. Davis was not sure of his date of birth; according to the ''[[New York Times]]'', \"Various newspaper and magazine articles over the last 70 years said he was born in 1899, 1901, 1902 or 1903. He told The New York Times several years ago that his sharecropper parents could never recall just when he was born \u2013 he was, after all, one of 11 children \u2013 and that he had not had the slightest idea when it really was.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/11/06/us/jimmie-davis-louisiana-s-singing-governor-is-dead.html|title=Jimmie Davis, Louisiana's Singing Governor, Is Dead|date=November 6, 2000|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2000/nov/07/local/me-48244|title=Jimmie Davis; 'Singing Governor' Spread Sunshine|first=MYRNA|last=OLIVER|date=November 7, 2000|accessdate=July 17, 2016|newspaper=[[LA Times]]}}</ref> The birth date listed on his Country Music Hall of Fame plaque is September 11, 1902.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.ha.com/itm/music-memorabilia/awards/jimmie-davis-country-music-hall-of-fame-plaque-presented-to-country-gospel-singer-songwriter-former-louisiana-governor-jim/a/622-21201.s|title=Jimmie Davis Country Music Hall of Fame Plaque. Presented - Lot #21201 - Heritage Auctions|accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref> The 1900 US Census recorded his birth as September 1899, which his parents would have told the census taker.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nDavis graduated from Beech Springs High School and the [[New Orleans, Louisiana|New Orleans]] campus of Soule Business College. Davis received his [[bachelor's degree]] in history from the [[Baptist]]-affiliated [[Louisiana College]] in [[Pineville, Louisiana|Pineville]] in [[Rapides Parish, Louisiana|Rapides Parish]]. He received a master's degree from [[Louisiana State University]] in [[Baton Rouge]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nHis 1927 master's thesis, which examines the intelligence levels of different races, is titled ''Comparative Intelligence of Whites, Blacks and Mulattoes.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lsu.louislibraries.org:5203/uhtbin/cgisirsi/x/0/0/57/5/3?searchdata1=1955955{CKEY}&searchfield1=GENERAL^SUBJECT^GENERAL^^&user_id=WEBSERVER|title=Item Display - Comparative intelligence of whites, blacks and mulattoes|website=Lsu.louislibraries.org:5203|date=2003-08-21|accessdate=2013-07-01}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nDuring the late 1920s, Davis taught history (and, unofficially, [[yodeling]]) for a year at the former [[Dodd College|Dodd College for Girls]] in [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]].{{citation needed|date=January 2016}} The college president, [[Monroe E. Dodd]], who was also the pastor of the large First Baptist Church of Shreveport and a pioneer radio preacher, invited Davis to join the faculty.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Musical career==\nDavis became a commercially successful singer of rural music before he entered politics. His early work was in the style of country music singer [[Jimmie Rodgers (country singer)|Jimmie Rodgers]]. Davis was also known for recording energetic and raunchy [[blues]] tunes such as \"Red Nightgown Blues\". Some of these records included slide guitar accompaniment by black bluesman [[Oscar \"Buddy\" Woods]]. During his first run for governor, opponents reprinted the lyrics of some of these songs in order to undermine Davis's campaign. In one case, anti-Davis forces played some records over an outdoor sound system, only to give up after the crowds started dancing, ignoring the double-entendre lyrics. Until the end of his life, Davis never denied or repudiated those records.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nIn 1999, \"[[You Are My Sunshine]]\" was honored with a [[Grammy Hall of Fame Award]], and the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] named it one of the [[Songs of the Century]]. \"You Are My Sunshine\" was ranked in 2003 as No. 73 on ''CMT's 100 Greatest Songs in Country Music''.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nUntil his death, Davis insisted that he wrote the song. It will be associated with him. [[Virginia Shehee]], a Shreveport [[business]]woman, [[philanthropist]], and [[Louisiana State Senate|state senator]], introduced legislation to designate \"You Are My Sunshine\" as the official state song.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/shreveporttimes/obituary.aspx?n=virginia-ruth-kilpatrick-shehee&pid=175240971&fhid=10218|title=Virginia Ruth Kilpatrick Shehee|newspaper=[[The Times (Shreveport)|The Shreveport Times]]|accessdate=July 9, 2015}}</ref> The song was reportedly written for Elizabeth Selby, a resident of Urbana, IL and housemother of Wescoga, Wesley Co-Op for Gals at the time the song was written.\n\nDavis often performed during his campaign stops when running for governor of Louisiana. After being elected in 1944, he became known as the \"singing governor.\" While governor, he had a No. 1 hit single in 1945 with \"[[There's a New Moon Over My Shoulder]]\". Davis recorded for the [[Victor Talking Machine Company]], and [[Decca Records]] for decades and released more than 40 albums.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nA long-time [[Southern Baptist]], Davis recorded a number of [[Southern gospel]] albums. In 1967 he served as president of the [[Gospel Music Association]]. He was a close friend of the [[North Dakota]]-born band leader [[Lawrence Welk]], who frequently reminded viewers of his television program of his association with Davis.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nA number of his songs were used as part of motion picture soundtracks. Davis appeared in half a dozen films, including one starring [[Ozzie and Harriet]], who had a TV series under their names. Members of Davis's last band included [[Allen \"Puddler\" Harris]] of [[Lake Charles, Louisiana|Lake Charles]]. He had served as pianist for singer [[Ricky Nelson]] early in his career.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nHe was also a close acquaintance of the country singer-songwriter [[Hank Williams]], with whom he authored the top-10 hit<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hpcisp.com/~turp/egbbcharts.html|title=Articles|website=Hpcisp.com|accessdate=December 31, 2019}}</ref> \"[[(I Heard That) Lonesome Whistle]]\" back in 1951, supposedly on a fishing day they spent together.\n\n===Singles===\n[[File:Jimmie Davis Hall of Fame plaque, 2003 IMG 6904.JPG|thumb|Davis was [[Posthumous recognition|posthumously]] inducted in 2003 into the [[Delta Music Museum]] Hall of Fame in [[Ferriday, Louisiana]]]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Single\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| <small>[[Hot Country Songs|US Country]]</small>\n|-\n| 1937\n| \"Nobody's Darling but Mine\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1938\n| \"Meet Me Tonight in Dreamland\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n|-\n| \"There's a Gold Mine in the Sky\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.45worlds.com/78rpm/record/5473|title=78 Record: Jimmie Davis - There's A Gold Mine In The Sky (1938)|website=45worlds.com|accessdate=December 31, 2019}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n|-\n| 1940\n| \"[[You Are My Sunshine]]\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \u2014\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1944\n| \"Is It Too Late Now\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 3\n|-\n| \"There's a Chill on the Hill Tonight\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4\n|-\n| 1945\n| \"[[There's a New Moon Over My Shoulder]]\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 1\n|-\n| 1946\n| \"Grievin' My Heart Out for You\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4\n|-\n| 1947\n| \"Bang Bang\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4\n|-\n| 1951\n| \"[[(I Heard That) Lonesome Whistle]]\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | 9\n|-\n| 1962\n| \"Where the Old Red River Flows\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 15\n|}\n\n==Political career==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=January 2018}}\n[[File:Cork oak tree planted and dedicated by the Honorable Jimmie H. Davis.jpg|thumbnail|left|Cork oak tree planted and dedicated by the Honorable Davis]]\nDavis was elected in 1938 as Shreveport's public safety commissioner. At the time, Shreveport had the [[city commission]] form of government. After four years in Shreveport City Hall, Davis was elected in 1942 to the [[Louisiana Public Service Commission]]. The rate-making body meets in the capital, Baton Rouge. He was elected during his term as governor and left after two years.\n\n===First term as governor (1944\u20131948)===\n{{See also|Louisiana gubernatorial election, 1944}}\nDavis was elected governor as a Democrat in 1944. Among those eliminated in the primary were [[Louisiana State Legislature|State Senator]] [[Ernest S. Clements]] of [[Oberlin, Louisiana|Oberlin]] in [[Allen Parish, Louisiana|Allen Parish]], freshman [[U.S. Representative]] [[James H. Morrison]] of [[Hammond, Louisiana|Hammond]] in [[Tangipahoa Parish]], and [[Sam Caldwell]], the [[List of mayors of Shreveport, Louisiana|mayor of Shreveport]]. Davis and Caldwell had served together earlier in Shreveport municipal government.\n\nIn the [[runoff election|runoff]], Davis defeated [[Lewis L. Morgan]], an elderly attorney and former [[U.S. representative]] from [[Covington, Louisiana|Covington]], the seat of [[St. Tammany Parish]], who had been backed by former Governor [[Earl Kemp Long]] and [[mayor of New Orleans|New Orleans Mayor]] [[Robert Maestri]]. In the runoff, Davis received 251,228 (53.6 percent) to Morgan's 217,915 (46.4 percent).\n\nDavis recruited [[Chris Faser, Jr.]], a young staff member of the Public Service Commission, to manage his gubernatorial race and act as his chief of staff. Faser became the \"go-to\" guy to obtain access to the governor.<ref>{{cite news|title=Christian Faser, Jr. (1917-2004)|work=[[The Advocate (Louisiana)|Baton Rouge Morning Advocate]]|date=January 18, 2004}}</ref>\n\nDavis pleased white liberals with his appointments to high positions of two of the leaders of the [[impeachment]] effort against [[Huey Long|Huey Pierce Long Jr.]] He named [[Cecil Morgan]] of Shreveport to the Louisiana Civil Service Commission. Morgan was succeeded in the Louisiana House by [[Rupert Peyton]] of Shreveport, who also served as an aide to Davis. In addition, Davis retained the anti-Long [[Ralph Norman Bauer]] of [[St. Mary Parish, Louisiana|St. Mary Parish]] as House speaker, a selection made originally in 1940 by Sam Jones.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nDavis reached out to the Longites when he commuted the prison sentence imposed on former LSU President [[James Monroe Smith]], convicted in the [[Louisiana Hayride scandals]] of the late 1930s. Like Davis, Smith was a native of Jackson Parish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lahistory.org/site36.php|title=Smith, James Monroe|work=A Dictionary of Louisiana Biography ([[Louisiana Historical Association]])|accessdate=March 25, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716204559/http://www.lahistory.org/site36.php|archive-date=July 16, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nEarl Long was seeking the [[Lieutenant Governor of Louisiana|lieutenant governorship]] on the Lewis Morgan \"ticket\" and led in the first primary in 1944, but he lost the runoff to [[J. Emile Verret]] of [[New Iberia, Louisiana|New Iberia]], then the president of the [[Iberia Parish School Board]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nDavis kept his hand in show business, and set a record for absenteeism during his first term. He made numerous trips to [[Hollywood]] to make Western \"[[horse operas]].\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mathur |first=Monika |date=June 23, 2009|title=A look at odd behavior by US governors|journal=Associated Press|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5jQ7_25-eKs8eU2rs504vDLRpD6dAD990JHEG0|accessdate=January 30, 2018}}</ref>\n\nUnder the state constitution, Davis was [[term limit|term-limited]] to a single non-consecutive term in office.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\n===The election of 1959\u20131960===\n{{See also|Louisiana gubernatorial election, 1959-60}}\nWhen he became a candidate for a second term in 1959\u201360, Davis had been out of office for nearly a dozen years. In a later study of this election, three Louisiana State University [[political science|political scientist]]s described him by the following:\n\n<blockquote>Davis has all the external attributes of a \"man of the people\", but his serious political connections seem to be with the [parish-seat] elite and its allies, particularly the major industrial combinations of the state. He is in many respects a toned-down version of the old-style southern politician who could spellbound the mass of voters into supporting him regardless of the effects of his programs on their welfare. ... Davis creates the perfect image of a man to be trusted and one whose intense calm is calculated to bring rational balance into the political life of the state.<ref>William C. Havard, Rudolf Heberle, and [[Perry H. Howard]], ''The Louisiana Elections of 1960'', [[Baton Rouge]]: [[Louisiana State University]] Studies, 1963, pg. 40</ref></blockquote>\n\nDavis was running at a time when African Americans in the civil rights movement were seeking social justice and restoration of their constitutional rights. In 1954 the US Supreme Court had ruled in ''[[Brown v. Board of Education]]'' that segregation in public schools was unconstitutional and urged states to integrate their facilities. With a pledge to fight for continued [[Racial segregation in the United States|segregation]] in public education, Davis won the Democratic [[gubernatorial]] nomination over a crowded field.\n\nIt included fellow segregationist State Senator [[William M. Rainach]] of [[Claiborne Parish, Louisiana|Claiborne Parish]], former Lieutenant Governor [[Bill Dodd]] of [[Baton Rouge]], former Governor [[James A. Noe]] of [[Monroe, Louisiana|Monroe]], and [[mayor of New Orleans|New Orleans Mayor]] [[deLesseps Story Morrison]]. [[Addison Roswell Thompson]], the operator of a New Orleans [[taxicab]] stand and a member of the [[Ku Klux Klan]], also filed candidacy papers.\n\nDavis ran second in the primary to [[deLesseps Story Morrison|\"Chep\" Morrison]], considered an anti-Long liberal by Louisiana standards. He defeated Morrison in the party runoff held on January 9, 1960. As African Americans (who had supported the Republican Party after the Civil War) were still largely [[Disfranchisement after Reconstruction era|disenfranchised]] in Louisiana, the Democratic primary was the only competitive race for office in the one-party state.\n\nIn the first round of balloting, Davis polled 213,551 (25.3 percent) to Morrison's 278,956 (33.1 percent). Rainach ran third with 143,095 (17 percent). Noe finished fourth with 97,654 (11.6 percent), and Dodd followed with 85,436 (10.1 percent). Davis won the northern and central parts of the state plus Baton Rouge, while Morrison dominated the southern portion of the state, particularly the French cultural parishes. In the runoff, Davis prevailed, 487,681 (54.1 percent) to Morrison's 414,110 (45.5 percent). It was estimated that Davis drew virtually all the Rainach support from the first primary.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nEarl Long endorsed Davis in the runoff in part because he had a longstanding personal dislike of Morrison. Long's gubernatorial running-mate, James A. Noe, who finished fourth in the primary, stood with Morrison,<ref>\"Noe Gives Support to Morrison\", ''The Shreveport Times'', December 10, 1959, pg. 1</ref> as did the fifth-place gubernatorial candidate and former Long lieutenant governor, Bill Dodd.<ref>\"Dodd Announces Endorsement for Morrison Ticket\", ''The Shreveport Times'', December 8, 1959, pg. 1</ref>\n\nRainach and his unsuccessful candidate for state comptroller, later U.S. Representative [[Joe D. Waggonner]], both endorsed Davis on the premise that Davis would be a stronger segregationist than Morrison.<ref>''Minden Herald'', December 31, 1959.</ref> Davis had avoided segregationist rhetoric in the first primary race in 1959. According to Morrison, the singer had sought support from the [[NAACP]] in New Orleans and [[Lake Charles, Louisiana|Lake Charles]].<ref>\"Morrison Says Davis Sought NAACP Support\", ''The Shreveport Times'', December 16, 1959, pg. 10A.</ref>\n\nIn the runoff with Morrison, Davis tried to identify as a more determined and dedicated segregationist than his rival. Morrison questioned Davis's change in campaign strategy and also appealed to segregationists. Morrison charged that Davis had \"operated an integrated [[honky-tonk]] in [[California]]\", when Davis was out of state with his singing career. Morrison also said that Davis had allowed the illegal operation of nine thousand [[slot machine]]s when Davis was governor during the 1940s.<ref>\"Beaten Candidates Give Endorsements\", ''The Shreveport Times'', December 11, 1959, pg. 5-A.</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, Earl Long had run unsuccessfully for lieutenant governor in the first primary in 1959. There was a runoff between Morrison's choice for the job, Alexandria Mayor [[W. George Bowdon Jr.]], and Davis's selection, former state House Speaker [[Taddy Aycock|Clarence C. \"Taddy\" Aycock]] of [[Franklin, Louisiana|Franklin]], [[St. Mary Parish, Louisiana|St. Mary Parish]]. Aycock defeated Bowdon by a margin similar to the plurality of Davis over Morrison. The defeat was Long's second for lieutenant governor. He had lost in the 1944 primary to [[J. Emile Verret]] of [[Iberia Parish, Louisiana|Iberia Parish]], who served in the second-ranking position in the first Davis administration.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nDavis effectively used the slogan \"He's One of Us\" in the gubernatorial race. Number 6 on the ballot, he assembled an intraparty [[Ticket (politics)|ticket]] for other statewide constitutional officers, including Aycock for lieutenant governor, [[Roy R. Theriot]] of [[Abbeville, Louisiana|Abbeville]] for comptroller, [[Douglas Fowler]] of [[Coushatta, Louisiana|Coushatta]] for custodian of voting machines, [[Jack P.F. Gremillion]] for [[Attorney General of Louisiana|attorney general]], [[Dave L. Pearce]], originally from [[West Carroll Parish, Louisiana|West Carroll Parish]], for agriculture commissioner, [[Ellen Bryan Moore]] for register of state lands, and [[Rufus D. Hayes]] for insurance commissioner; the latter four were all based in Baton Rouge. The entire Davis ticket was elected.<ref>Davis exhibit, Delta Music Museum, [[Ferriday, Louisiana|Ferriday]], Louisiana.</ref>\n\nIn their study ''The Louisiana Election of 1960'', William C. Havard, Rudolf Heberle, and [[Perry H. Howard]] demonstrated that Davis built his second-primary victory by narrowly edging Morrison in the eastern and western extremities of south Louisiana. Davis secured the backing of [[organized labor]] and made inroads among the white, urban working class, which would have been essential to a Morrison victory. In the seven urban industrial parishes, which then comprised some 46.5 percent of the total turnout, Davis topped Morrison by 7,368 votes (50.8 percent) of the 419,537 applicable subtotal. {{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nMorrison polled 60 percent in his own Orleans Parish and 54.6 percent in adjacent [[suburban]] [[Jefferson Parish, Louisiana|Jefferson Parish]], but in the industrial strip and in more Protestant areas, Morrison slipped. The second primary attracted 57,744 more votes than the initial stage of balloting, and analysts found that the lion's share of additional ballots were filed by segregationists who backed Davis.<ref>Havard, Heberle, and Havard, ''The Louisiana Election of 1960'', pp. 50\u201352.<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed --></ref>\n\nIn the general election held on April 19, 1960, Davis defeated [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Francis Grevemberg]], a [[Lafayette, Louisiana|Lafayette]] native, by a margin of nearly 82\u201317 percent. Grevemberg had been head of the state police under Democratic Governor [[Robert F. Kennon]] and had gained a reputation for fighting [[organized crime]]. He called for a true two-party system for Louisiana. As the Democratic nominee in the nearly one-party state, Davis faced no serious political threat and did little campaigning against Grevemberg.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nIt has been reported that had General [[Curtis LeMay]] turned down [[George C. Wallace]]'s offer to be his candidate for vice president in 1968 on the [[American Independent Party]] ticket, that Wallace was ready to announce Davis as his selection for vice president. Other sources say Wallace's second choice was the former [[governor of Arkansas]], [[Orval Faubus]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,902367,00.html|title=The Campaign: George's General|date=October 11, 1968|website=Content.time.com|accessdate=December 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Davis and Dodd====\nIn the 1959 campaign, Bill Dodd had attacked Davis ferociously: it was part of Dodd's strategy to get Davis to withdraw from the primary. \"Nothing personal in his [Dodd's] heart, just a cold-blooded plan to wind up in a second primary against Morrison, who he figured could not win against anyone [else] in a runoff,\" said Davis in the introduction to Dodd's memoirs, ''Peapatch Politics: The Earl Long Era in Louisiana Politics''.\n\nDodd endorsed Morrison in the runoff, but he had a long-term reason for this decision. Dodd planned to run for school superintendent in the 1963 primary, and he wanted to have at least the neutrality of Morrison four years thereafter.\n\nDodd and Davis later became close friends. In Davis' words:\n\n<blockquote>Bill and I have many things in common. We share the same type of religion and boyhood background; we got our start as schoolteachers and figured prominently in public education; we both served in public life at or near the top. And I like to feel that we share a common appreciation and respect for people, all people. One of the greatest rewards in politics is meeting people. And one of the greatest and most unusual men I've ever met is Bill Dodd.</blockquote>\n\n===Second term (1960\u20131964)===\nDavis' appointees in the second term included outgoing State Representative [[Claude Kirkpatrick]] of [[Jennings, Louisiana|Jennings]], who was named to succeed [[Lorris M. Wimberly]] as the Director of Public Works. In that capacity, Kirkpatrick took the steps for a joint agreement with [[State of Texas|Texas]] to establish the popular [[Toledo Bend Reservoir]], a haven for [[boating]] and fishing. Mrs. Kirkpatrick, the former [[Edith Killgore Kirkpatrick|Edith Killgore]], a native of Claiborne Parish, headed Davis' women's campaign division for southwestern Louisiana. He appointed Alexandria businessman Morgan W. Walker, Sr., to the State Mineral Board. Walker founded a company which later became part of [[Continental Trailways]] [[Bus]] lines. Davis named as state highway director [[Ray Burgess]] of Baton Rouge, who considered running for governor in the 1963 primary.\n\nAs part of his support of segregation, Davis initiated passage of state legislation to create the [[Louisiana State Sovereignty Commission]], which operated from 1960 to 1967. It \"espoused states rights, anti-communist and segregationist ideas, with a particular focus on maintaining the status quo in race relations. It was closely allied with the Louisiana Joint Legislative Committee on Un-American Activities.\"<ref name=\"amistad\">[http://amistadresearchcenter.tulane.edu/archon/?p=creators/creator&id=1129 \"Louisiana State Sovereignty Commission\"], Amistad Research Center, Tulane University; Sources: Adam Fairclough. ''Race and Democracy: The Civil Rights Struggle in Louisiana, 1915-1972''. Athens, GA: University of Georgia Press, 1995.</ref> It was modeled after Mississippi's commission, established in 1956 to resist integration. Davis tapped [[Frank Voelker Jr.]], City Attorney of [[Lake Providence, Louisiana|Lake Providence]], to chair the newly established Commission. It was given unusual {{clarify|date=January 2018}} powers to investigate state citizens, and used its authority to exert economic pressure to suppress civil rights activists. Voelker left the commission in 1963 to run for governor but placed poorly in the primary; he withdrew and supported other candidates.<ref>Havard, Heberle, and Howard, ''The Louisiana Election of 1960'', pg. 99<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed, if any --></ref>\n\nIn his second term, Davis chose veteran Representative [[J. Thomas Jewell]] of [[New Roads, Louisiana|New Roads]] in [[Pointe Coupee Parish, Louisiana|Pointe Coupee Parish]] as [[Speaker of the Louisiana House of Representatives|House Speaker]] to succeed [[Bob Angelle]]. Davis secured passage of a $60&nbsp;million public improvements [[bond issue]] through the State Board and Building Commission, an organization controlled by the governor. He gained legislative support from many formerly pro-Long lawmakers and cemented his hold on the traditional anti-Long bloc. He avoided defeat on any legislation that he strongly supported and was able to defeat nearly all bills with which he did not concur.\n\nHe offered tacit support to Presidents [[John F. Kennedy]] and [[Lyndon B. Johnson]], national Democrats, to secure the state's hold of pending offshore oil revenues. In the 1963 legislative fiscal session, he defeated efforts to procure an unpledged presidential elector slate for the 1964 general election, by which time he had been succeeded by [[John J. McKeithen]].<ref>Havard, Heberle, and Howard, ''The Louisiana Elections of 1960'', pp. 90\u201392.<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed, if any --></ref>\n\n===Fourth place in 1971===\n{{Main|Louisiana gubernatorial election, 1971-72}}\nIn 1971, Davis entered another crowded Democratic [[gubernatorial]] primary field with new political prospects, but he finished in fourth place with 138,756 ballots (11.8 percent).\n\nIn a runoff election held in December 1971, U.S. Representative [[Edwin Washington Edwards]] of [[Crowley, Louisiana|Crowley]], [[Acadia Parish, Louisiana|Acadia Parish]], defeated then state Senator [[Bennett Johnston|J. Bennett Johnston Jr.]], of Shreveport for the party nomination. That vote was close: Edwards, 584,262 (50.2 percent) to Johnston's 579,774 (49.8 percent). Edwards beat Republican [[David C. Treen]] in the state general election held on February 1, 1972. By that time, Davis' days as a politician were clearly behind him.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nToward the end of his life, longtime Democrat Davis endorsed at least two Republican candidates after the state's voters had gone through a political realignment. By the late 20th century, white conservatives in the state largely supported the Republican Party. In 1996 Davis endorsed Republican state representative [[Woody Jenkins]] of Baton Rouge for the U.S. Senate against Democrat [[Mary Landrieu]] of New Orleans, and Governor [[Murphy J. Foster, Jr.|Murphy J. \"Mike\" Foster, Jr.]] seeking re-election in 1999. His opponent was African-American Democratic Congressman [[Bill Jefferson]] of New Orleans.<ref>Susie Labry, 1995<!-- page(s)?? --></ref>\n\n===Political legacy===\nDavis established a State Retirement System and funding of more than $100&nbsp;million in public improvements, while leaving the state with a $38&nbsp;million surplus after his first term.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sec.state.la.us/67.htm|title=Louisiana Secretary of State<!-- Bot generated title -->|accessdate=July 17, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070812153046/http://www.sec.state.la.us/67.htm|archivedate=August 12, 2007|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring his second term, Davis built the [[Sunshine Bridge]], the new [[Louisiana Governor's Mansion]], and [[Toledo Bend Reservoir]], all criticized at the time, but later recognized as beneficial to the state. Davis coordinated the pay periods of state employees, who had sometimes received their checks a week late, a particular hardship to those with low earnings.\n\nEarl Long once remarked that Davis was so relaxed and low-key that one could not \"wake up Jimmie Davis with an earthquake\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/05/08/opinion/carville-democrats-could-lose/index.html|title=Carville: Wake up Democrats; you could lose |website=Cnn.com|author=James Carville|accessdate=July 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\nPublic relations specialist [[Gus Weill]], who worked in the Davis campaign in 1959, wrote a biography of the former governor in 1977, entitled ''You Are My Sunshine,'' based on Davis' best-known song.<ref>''You Are My Sunshine: The Jimmie Davis Story, An Affectionate Biography'' ([[Baton Rouge]]: [[Pelican Publishing Company]], 1977); {{ISBN|0882896601}} (0-88289-660-1)</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[Image:Eglin House in Shreveport IMG 1571.JPG|200px|right|thumb|Davis married the former Alvern Adams in this historic Shreveport house in the Highlands neighborhood. It was formerly owned by the Eglins, the maternal grandparents of [[John McKeithen|John J. McKeithen]].<ref>Source: Historic marker, Eglin House in Shreveport</ref>]]\n\nDavis's first wife, the former Alvern Adams, the daughter of a physician in Shreveport, was the first lady while he was governor during both terms. Two years after her death in 1967, Davis married Anna Gordon, born Effie Juanita Carter (February 15, 1917 &ndash; March 5, 2004). A founding member of the gospel quartet ''The Chuck Wagon Gang'' along with her father and two of her brothers, she had been given the stage name \"Anna\" during the mid-1930s.  Davis was a longtime fan of the group, who were gospel music pioneers with more than 36 million records sold in forty years of affiliation with [[Columbia Records]].  \n\nOut of office, Davis resided primarily in Baton Rouge but made numerous singing appearances, particularly in churches throughout the United States.\n[[Image:Jimmie Davis grave marker IMG 5808.JPG|200px|right|thumb|Davis grave located in small cemetery behind the tabernacle]]\n\nDavis died on November 5, 2000. He had suffered a fall in his home some ten months earlier and may have had a [[stroke]] in his last days. He is interred alongside his first wife at the Jimmie Davis Tabernacle Cemetery in his native Beech Springs community near Quitman. Jim Davis was cremated.<ref name=mtvcom>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1472470/my-sunshine-singer-jimmie-davis-dead-at-101.jhtml|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130129170747/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1472470/my-sunshine-singer-jimmie-davis-dead-at-101.jhtml|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 29, 2013|title=\"Sunshine\" singer Jimmie Davis dead at 101|website=Mtv.com|accessdate=October 21, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/thenewsstar/obituary.aspx?n=james-william-davis&pid=160920202|title=James William Davis obituary|newspaper=[[Monroe News Star]]|accessdate=November 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDavis was aged 101 years and 55 days,<ref name=mtvcom/> which made him the longest-lived of all U.S. state governors at the time of his death. Davis held this record until March 18, 2011, when [[Albert Rosellini]] of [[Washington (state)|Washington]] achieved a greater lifespan of 101 years, 56 days.\n\n==Honors==\n[[Image:Jimmie Davis Bridge, Shreveport, LA IMG 1555.JPG|200px|thumb|The Jimmie Davis Bridge over the [[Red River of the South|Red River]] on Louisiana State Highway 511, connecting [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]] and [[Bossier City, Louisiana|Bossier City]]]]\n\n[[Image:Jimmie Davis Tabernacle, LA IMG 5817.JPG|200px|right|thumb|Jimmie Davis Tabernacle west of [[Quitman, Louisiana|Quitman]]]]\n\nThe Jimmie Davis Bridge over the [[Red River of the South|Red River]] connects Shreveport and [[Bossier City, Louisiana|Bossier City]] via Louisiana Highway 511. It was named in his honor during his second term as governor.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nThe Jimmie Davis Tabernacle is located near Weston in Jackson Parish. The tabernacle hosts occasional gospel singing. At the site is a replica of the Davis homestead (c. 1900) and of the Peckerwood Hill Store, an old [[general store]] that served the community.\n\n[[Jimmie Davis State Park]] is located on Caney Lake (not to be confused with [[Caney Lakes Recreation Area]] near [[Minden, Louisiana|Minden]]) southwest of [[Chatham, Louisiana|Chatham]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nDavis was [[Posthumous recognition|posthumously]] inducted into the [[Delta Music Museum]] Hall of Fame in [[Ferriday, Louisiana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deltamusicmuseum.com/inductees.html|title=Inductees|website=Deltamusicmuseum.com|accessdate=December 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDavis was inducted into the [[Nashville Songwriters Hall of Fame]] in 1971, the [[Country Music Hall of Fame]] in 1972, the [[Southern Gospel Music Association]] Hall of Fame in 1997 and The [[Louisiana Music Hall of Fame]] in 2008.\n\nIn 1993, Davis was among the first thirteen inductees of the [[Louisiana Political Museum and Hall of Fame]] in [[Winnfield, Louisiana|Winnfield]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cityofwinnfield.com/museum.html|title=Louisiana Political Museum and Hall of Fame|website=Cityofwinnfield.com|accessdate=August 22, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090703054258/http://cityofwinnfield.com/museum.html|archivedate=July 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe Hall of Fame periodically issues the \"Friends of Jimmie Davis Award\". In 2005, the award was presented to then [[U.S. Senator]] [[Ted Stevens]], an [[Alaska]] Republican, who once hosted Davis in a concert at the [[Kennedy Center]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] Speaking at the Louisiana Political Museum and Hall of Fame, Stevens recalled having been with both Davis and [[Ronald W. Reagan]], when Reagan was contemplating his first run for [[governor of California]] and asked Davis for political advice. Stevens joined the Jimmie Davis Band in a rendition of \"You Are My Sunshine\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepineywoods.com/HallFameF05.htm|title=Tom Kelly, \"Winnfield opens Civic Center with \"Hall\" event: Renovated forestry building is modern, ready to serve for years into the future\", February 2005|website=Thepineywoods.com|accessdate=February 6, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140628232133/http://www.thepineywoods.com/HallFameF05.htm|archive-date=June 28, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe 2006 recipient of the \"Friends of Jimmie Davis\" award was the late former State Senator [[B.G. Dyess]], a Baptist minister from [[Rapides Parish, Louisiana|Rapides Parish]].{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n \nThe Davis archives of papers and photographs is housed in the \"You Are My Sunshine\" Collection of the Linus A. Sims Memorial Library at [[Southeastern Louisiana University]] in Hammond.<ref>[http://www.selu.edu/acad_research/programs/csls/historical_collections/photo_collections/c_d_photos/davis_jimmie.html Davis Collection at Southeastern], Selu.edu, (retrieved 2012-05-06).</ref>\n\nDavis believed that his singing career enhanced his political prospects. He once told [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] Republican [[Ronnie Thompson (Georgia politician)|Ronnie Thompson]], a mayor of [[Macon, Georgia|Macon]]: \"If you want to have any success in politics, sing softly and carry a big guitar,\" a play on an old [[Theodore Roosevelt]] [[adage]].<ref>Davis, quoted in Eric Welch, \"Gospel-singing Jeweler Is 'Country' Candidate\", ''Macon Telegraph'', 1967 August 26, p. A1.</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\nDavis had several appearances in movies (usually or always as himself), including:\n*1942: ''[[Strictly in the Groove]]'' \n*1942: ''[[Riding Through Nevada]]'' \n*1943: ''[[Frontier Fury (1943 film)|Frontier Fury]]'' \n*1944: ''[[Cyclone Prairie Rangers]]'' \n*1947: ''[[Louisiana (1947 film)|Louisiana]]'' \n*1949: ''[[Mississippi Rhythm]]'' \n*1950: ''[[Square Dance Katy]]''\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|United States|Education|Music|Politics|Conservatism|Christianity}}\n* [[List of Governors of Louisiana]]\n* [[Jim Flynn (songwriter)|Jim Flynn]], a writer encouraged when Davis signed his first song writing contract\n\n==References and sources==\n\n===References===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* Toru Mitsui (1998). \"Jimmie Davis.\" In ''The Encyclopedia of Country Music.'' Paul Kingsbury, Ed. New York: Oxford University Press. p.&nbsp;136.\n* Kevin S. Fontenot, \"You Can't Fight a Song: Country Music in Jimmie Davis' Gubernatorial Campaigns,\" ''Journal of Country Music'' (2007).\n\n===External links===\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikisource author}}\n* {{IMDb name|204834|Jimmie Davis}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080110153727/http://www.sos.louisiana.gov/tabid/404/Default.aspx State of Louisiana Biography]\n* [http://www.la-cemeteries.com/Governors/Davis,%20James%20Houston/Davis,%20James%20Houston.shtml Cemetery Memorial] by La-Cemeteries\n* [https://archive.org/details/Jimmy_Davis-Shes_a_Real_Hum_Dinger Listen to Jimmie singing \"She's a Real Hum Dinger\"]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110418100814/http://countrymusichalloffame.org/full-list-of-inductees/view/jimmie-davis at the Country Music Hall of Fame and Museum]\n* [http://www.selu.edu/acad_research/programs/csls/historical_collections/archival_collections/c_d/davis_jimmie.html Jimmie Davis Collection] and [http://www.selu.edu/acad_research/programs/csls/historical_collections/photo_collections/c_d_photos/davis_jimmie.html Jimmie Davis Photo Collection] at [[Southeastern Louisiana University]] in [[Hammond, Louisiana|Hammond]].\n*{{Find a Grave|6370060}}\n*[[Southern Gospel Music Association]] Hall of Fame and Museum\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{Succession box|title=[[List of Governors of Louisiana|Governor of Louisiana]] | before=[[Sam H. Jones]]| after=[[Earl Long|Earl K. Long]] | years=May 9, 1944\u2013May 11, 1948}}\n{{Succession box|title=[[List of Governors of Louisiana|Governor of Louisiana]]\n|before=Earl K. Long| after=[[John McKeithen]] | years=May 10, 1960\u2013May 12, 1964}}\n{{s-hon}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Oldest living United States governor]]\n|before=[[J. Bracken Lee]]\n|after=[[Strom Thurmond]]\n|years=October 20, 1996 \u2013 November 5, 2000}}\n{{succession box\n|title=Oldest United States governor ever\n|before=[[Nellie Tayloe Ross]]\n|after=[[Albert Rosellini]]\n|years=October 2, 2000 \u2013 March 17, 2011}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{1970s Country Music Hall of Fame}}\n{{Governors of Louisiana}}\n{{Louisiana Political Museum and Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davis, Jimmie}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:2000 deaths]]\n[[Category:Educators from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:American actor-politicians]]\n[[Category:American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Baptists from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:American centenarians]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American gospel singers]]\n[[Category:Country Music Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Governors of Louisiana]]\n[[Category:People from Jackson Parish, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Shreveport, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Baton Rouge, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Louisiana College alumni]]\n[[Category:Louisiana State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Louisiana Democrats]]\n[[Category:Members of the Louisiana Public Service Commission]]\n[[Category:American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:American male composers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American composers]]\n[[Category:American performers of Christian music]]\n[[Category:Southern gospel performers]]\n[[Category:Decca Records artists]]\n[[Category:Lawrence Welk]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Baton Rouge, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Shreveport, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American white supremacists]]\n[[Category:American anti-communists]]\n", "name_user": "Sandstein", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Gospel Music Associationclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jimmie_Davis"}
{"title_page": "Joaquim Sunyer", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=March 2018}}\n'''Joaquim Sunyer''' ({{IPA-ca|\u0292ua\u02c8kim su\u02c8\u0272e}}) ([[Sitges]], 1874\u20131956) was a [[Catalonia|Catalan]] painter often linked to the [[Noucentisme]] movement.\n\nHe began his artistic education with his uncle, Joaquim Mir, later moving to Barcelona where his fellow students included [[Joaqu\u00edn Torres Garc\u00eda]], [[Isidro Nonell]],<ref name=\"Cowling&Mundy_251\">Cowling and Mundy, p. 251.</ref> and [[Joaquin Mir Trinxet]]. In 1896 he moved to Paris, where he became acquainted with the [[neo-impressionist]] movement and worked extensively in the style. His paintings of this period include street scenes of working-class life. He also produced graphic works influenced by [[Toulouse-Lautrec]] and [[Th\u00e9ophile Steinlen]] that emphasize urban night life and urban poverty.<ref name=\"Cowling&Mundy_251\"/>  He was friends with [[Picasso]], and in the first years of the 20th century the two artists' work were similar in style and subject.<ref name=\"Cowling&Mundy_251\"/>\n\nIn 1908, Sunyer turned away from Parisian subject matter in favor of the themes that would occupy him for the rest of his life, especially nudes in pastoral landscapes, family scenes, women, and children.<ref>Cowling and Mundy, p. 252.</ref> He returned to Spain in 1911, establishing himself in his hometown of Sitges. There he painted numerous landscape paintings in which he highlights his preoccupation with capturing the Mediterranean light through the use of very light colours marking a clear rupture with his darker paintings executed in Paris. His compositions are noted as an example of balance, though sacrificing technical perfection for the benefit of a more intense evocative power.\n\nHe was an important influence on younger Catalan artists such as [[Joan Miro|Miro]].<ref name=\"Cowling&Mundy_251\"/>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"154px\" perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Sunyer_landscape.jpg|Landscape by Sunyer, 1913\nFile:Joaquim Sunyer, c.1920, La sand\u00eda, oil on canvas, 59 x 71.5 cm, Museu Nacional d'Art de Catalunya.jpg|''La sand\u00eda'' (''The Watermelon''), 1920, oil on canvas, 59 x 71.5 cm, [[Museu Nacional d'Art de Catalunya]], exhibited Exposici\u00f3 d'Art franc\u00e8s d'Avantguarda, [[Galeries Dalmau]], Barcelona, 1920\nFile:Joaquim Sunyer - The Daure Girls - c 1935-36 - Santander Foundation.jpg|''Les Noies Daure'' (''The Daure Girls''), 1935\u201336, [[Fundaci\u00f3n Banco Santander]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n==References==\n*Cowling, Elizabeth; Jennifer Mundy (1990). ''On Classic Ground: Picasso, L\u00e9ger, de Chirico and the New Classicism 1910-1930''. London: Tate Gallery. {{ISBN|1-854-37043-X}}\n* Various, ''Enciclopedia Monitor'' (1972). Barcelona: Salvat S.A. de Ediciones. {{ISBN|84-7137-213-4}} (complete works)\n\n== External links ==\n* {{in lang|es}} [http://www.epdlp.com/pintor.php?id=379 EPDLP.com]\n* {{in lang|en}} [https://www.fundacionbancosantander.com/coleccion/en/joaquim-sunyer/the-daure-girls/ Santander Foundation]\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sunyer, Joaquim}}\n[[Category:Catalan painters]]\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1956 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish painters]]\n[[Category:Spanish male painters]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=March 2018}}\n'''Joaquim Sunyer''' ({{IPA-ca|\u0292ua\u02c8kim su\u02c8\u0272e}}) ([[Sitges]], 1874\u20131956) was a [[Catalonia|Catalan]] painter often linked to the [[Noucentisme]] movement.\n\nHe began his artistic education with his uncle, Joaquim Mir, later moving to Barcelona where his fellow students included [[Joaqu\u00edn Torres Garc\u00eda]], [[Isidro Nonell]],<ref name=\"Cowling&Mundy_251\">Cowling and Mundy, p. 251.</ref> and [[Joaquin Mir Trinxet]]. In 1896 he moved to Paris, where he became acquainted with the [[neo-impressionist]] movement and worked extensively in the style. His paintings of this period include street scenes of working-class life. He also produced graphic works influenced by [[Toulouse-Lautrec]] and [[Th\u00e9ophile Steinlen]] that emphasize urban night life and urban poverty.<ref name=\"Cowling&Mundy_251\"/>  He was friends with [[Picasso]], and in the first years of the 20th century the two artists' work were similar in style and subject.<ref name=\"Cowling&Mundy_251\"/>\n\nIn 1908, Sunyer turned away from Parisian subject matter in favor of the themes that would occupy him for the rest of his life, especially nudes in pastoral landscapes, family scenes, women, and children.<ref>Cowling and Mundy, p. 252.</ref> He returned to Spain in 1911, establishing himself in his hometown of Sitges. There he painted numerous landscape paintings in which he highlights his preoccupation with capturing the Mediterranean light through the use of very light colours marking a clear rupture with his darker paintings executed in Paris. His compositions are noted as an example of balance, though sacrificing technical perfection for the benefit of a more intense evocative power.\n\nHe was an important influence on younger Catalan artists such as [[Joan Miro|Miro]].<ref name=\"Cowling&Mundy_251\"/>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"154px\" perrow=\"5\">\nFile:Sunyer_landscape.jpg|Landscape by Sunyer, 1913\nFile:Joaquim Sunyer, c.1920, La sand\u00eda, oil on canvas, 59 x 71.5 cm, Museu Nacional d'Art de Catalunya.jpg|''La sand\u00eda'' (''The Watermelon'''), 1920, oil on canvas, 59 x 71.5 cm, [[Museu Nacional d'Art de Catalunya]], exhibited Exposici\u00f3 d'Art franc\u00e8s d'Avantguarda, [[Galeries Dalmau]], Barcelona, 1920\nFile:Joaquim Sunyer - The Daure Girls - c 1935-36 - Santander Foundation.jpg|''Les Noies Daure'' (''The Daure Girls''), 1935\u201336, [[Fundaci\u00f3n Banco Santander]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n==References==\n*Cowling, Elizabeth; Jennifer Mundy (1990). ''On Classic Ground: Picasso, L\u00e9ger, de Chirico and the New Classicism 1910-1930''. London: Tate Gallery. {{ISBN|1-854-37043-X}}\n* Various, ''Enciclopedia Monitor'' (1972). Barcelona: Salvat S.A. de Ediciones. {{ISBN|84-7137-213-4}} (complete works)\n\n== External links ==\n* {{in lang|es}} [http://www.epdlp.com/pintor.php?id=379 EPDLP.com]\n* {{in lang|en}} [https://www.fundacionbancosantander.com/coleccion/en/joaquim-sunyer/the-daure-girls/ Santander Foundation]\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sunyer, Joaquim}}\n[[Category:Catalan painters]]\n[[Category:1875 births]]\n[[Category:1956 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish painters]]\n[[Category:Spanish male painters]]\n", "name_user": "Ewulp", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joaquim_Sunyer"}
{"title_page": "Mukesh Bhakar", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Mukesh Bhakar\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|6 May 1988|df=y}}\n| honorific-suffix = MLA Ladnun\n| image            = Mukesh Bhakar at Ladnun SDM Office for nomination.jpg\n| caption          = Bhakar at Ladnun SDM office\n| imagesize        = 250 px\n| birth_name       = Mukesh Bhakar\n| birth_place      = [[Ladnun, Rajasthan]], India\n| office1           = Member of Legislative Assembly (MLA) Ladnun\n| termstart1        = 17 December 2018\n| governor         = [[Kalraj Mishra]]\n| term_end1        = \n| assembly1        = [[Ladnun (Rajasthan Assembly constituency)|Ladnun]]\n| office2          = State President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]\n| term_start2      = 7 April 2020\n| office3          = State President, National Student\u2019s Union of India\n| term_start3      = January 2013\n| term_end3        = May 2015\n| office4          = [[National Students Union of India|National Secretary]]\n| term_start4      = 21 October 2015\n| term_end4        = 26 May 2018\n| office5          = Vice President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]\n| term_start5      = 22 November 2017\n| term_end5        = 6 April 2020\n| party            = [[Indian National Congress]]\n| parents          = Retd. Subedar Surjaram Bhakar (father)<br />Sohini Devi (mother)\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Rajasthan]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br /> [[University of Rajasthan|University of Rajasthan]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n}}\n\n'''Mukesh Bhakar''' (born 6 May 1988) is an Indian politician who is serving as the President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]], he represents also in [[Rajasthan Legislative Assembly]] from [[Ladnu|Ladnun]] of [[Nagaur district]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rajassembly.nic.in/MemberBioData.aspx|title=Rajasthan Legislative Assembly Member Information|website=rajassembly.nic.in}}</ref> As member of the [[Indian National Congress|Congress party]] <ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rajpcc.com/mukeshbhakar|title=Indian National Congress Party|website=www.rajpcc.com}}</ref>. Bhakar was previously State President of [[National Students' Union of India]] Rajasthan, the student wing of [[Indian National Congress]] from 2013 to 2015.\n\n== Political life ==\nHe elected State President of [[National Students' Union of India]] Rajasthan in 2013.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/news/RAJ-JAI-mukesh-bhakar-became-the-state-chief-of-nsui-4164425-NOR.html|title=NSUI \u0915\u0947 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0926\u0947\u0936\u093e\u0927\u094d\u092f\u0915\u094d\u0937 \u092c\u0928\u0947 \u092e\u0941\u0915\u0947\u0936 \u092d\u093e\u0915\u0930|date=31 January 2013|website=Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref>  During his tenure NSUI made come back in [[University of Rajasthan]] after 12 years in the Largest University of Rajasthan.<ref>https://www.bhaskar.com/rajasthan/jaipur/news/RAJ-JAI-10-candidates-for-presidents-post-rajasthan-4719233-NOR.html.</ref> After completion of his term National president nominated him National Secretary. Congress Party gave him an opportunity to contest Rajasthan State assembly elections 2018, where he successfully managed a win by margin of 12947 votes against 3 times MLA [[Thakur Manohar Singh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/election-result-2018/rajasthan-election-result-2018/nagaur/ladnun/mukesh-bhakar/|title=Ladnun Congress Candidate Mukesh Bhakar, Mukesh Bhakar vs Manohar Singh, \u0932\u093e\u0921\u0928\u0942\u0902 \u0938\u0940\u091f \u0938\u0947 \u0915\u093e\u0902\u0917\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0938 \u0909\u092e\u094d\u092e\u0940\u0926\u0935\u093e\u0930 \u092e\u0941\u0915\u0947\u0936 \u092d\u0915\u0930|website=Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/elections/rajasthan-election/article/ladnun-assembly-constituency-election-2018-rajasthan-assembly-polls-rajasthan-vasundhara-raje-bharatiya-janata-party-bjp-congress-sachin-pilot-manohar/320646|title=Ladnun Assembly Election Results 2018: Congress' Mukesh Bhakar won by 12,947 votes against BJP's sitting MLA|website=www.timesnownews.com}}</ref>. He won election for State President, [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]] over nearest candidate [[Amardin]] by 9872 votes.<ref>https://www.jagran.com/rajasthan/jaipur-congress-mla-mukesh-bhakar-appointed-as-rajasthan-pradesh-youth-congress-state-president-organization-elections-20172785.html</ref>\n\n== Positions held ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Position\n|-\n| 2009 - 10 || Unit President, National Students Union of India, University of Rajasthan\n|-\n| 2013 - 15 ||State President, National Students Union of India, NSUI Rajasthan\n|-\n| 2015 - 18 || National Secretary, National Students Union of India\n|-\n| 2018 \u2013 20  || State Vice President, Rajasthan Youth Congress\n|-\n| 2017 \u2013 cont. || PCC Member, Rajasthan Pradesh Congress Committee\n|-\n| 2017 \u2013 cont. || Member, All India Congress Committee\n|-\n| 2018 \u2013 cont. ||Member of Legislative Assembly (MLA) from Ladnun, Rajasthan State Assembly\n|-\n| 2019 \u2013 cont.  || Member of Committee on Petitions, Rajasthan State Assembly\n|-\n| 2020 \u2013 cont.  || State President, Rajasthan Youth Congress\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{twitter.com|mukeshbhakar_}}\n\n{{Indian National Congress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhakar, Mukesh}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani people]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani politicians]]\n[[Category:Rajasthan MLAs 2018\u2013]]\n[[Category:People from Nagaur district]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Autobiography|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Mukesh Bhakar\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|6 May 1988|df=y}}\n| honorific-suffix = MLA Ladnun\n| image            = Mukesh Bhakar at Ladnun SDM Office for nomination.jpg\n| caption          = Bhakar at Ladnun SDM office\n| imagesize        = 250 px\n| birth_name       = Mukesh Bhakar\n| birth_place      = [[Ladnun, Rajasthan]], India\n| office1           = Member of Legislative Assembly (MLA) Ladnun\n| termstart1        = 17 December 2018\n| governor         = [[Kalraj Mishra]]\n| term_end1        = \n| 1blankname1      = [[Chief Minister of Rajasthan|Chief Minister]]\n| 1namedata1       = [[Ashok Gehlot]]\n| assembly1        = [[Ladnun (Rajasthan Assembly constituency)|Ladnun]]\n| office2 = President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]\n| term_start2 = 7 April 2020\n| 1blankname2 = National President\n| 1namedata2 = [[Srinivas BV]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Ashok Chandna]]\n| office3          = State President, National Student\u2019s Union of India\n| term_start3      = January 2013\n| term_end3        = May 2015\n| office4          = [[National Students Union of India|National Secretary]]\n| term_start4      = 21 October 2015\n| term_end4        = 26 May 2018\n| office5          = Vice President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]\n| term_start5      = 22 November 2017\n| term_end5        = 6 April 2020\n| party            = [[Indian National Congress]]\n| parents          = Retd. Subedar Surjaram Bhakar (father)<br />Sohini Devi (mother)\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Rajasthan]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br /> [[University of Rajasthan|University of Rajasthan]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n}}\n\n'''Mukesh Bhakar''' (born 6 May 1988) is an Indian politician who is serving as the President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]], he represents also in [[Rajasthan Legislative Assembly]] from [[Ladnu|Ladnun]] of [[Nagaur district]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rajassembly.nic.in/MemberBioData.aspx|title=Rajasthan Legislative Assembly Member Information|website=rajassembly.nic.in}}</ref> As member of the [[Indian National Congress|Congress party]] <ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rajpcc.com/mukeshbhakar|title=Indian National Congress Party|website=www.rajpcc.com}}</ref>. Bhakar was previously State President of [[National Students' Union of India]] Rajasthan, the student wing of [[Indian National Congress]] from 2013 to 2015.\n\n== Political life ==\nHe elected State President of [[National Students' Union of India]] Rajasthan in 2013.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/news/RAJ-JAI-mukesh-bhakar-became-the-state-chief-of-nsui-4164425-NOR.html|title=NSUI \u0915\u0947 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0926\u0947\u0936\u093e\u0927\u094d\u092f\u0915\u094d\u0937 \u092c\u0928\u0947 \u092e\u0941\u0915\u0947\u0936 \u092d\u093e\u0915\u0930|date=31 January 2013|website=Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref>  During his tenure NSUI made come back in [[University of Rajasthan]] after 12 years in the Largest University of Rajasthan.<ref>https://www.bhaskar.com/rajasthan/jaipur/news/RAJ-JAI-10-candidates-for-presidents-post-rajasthan-4719233-NOR.html.</ref> After completion of his term National president nominated him National Secretary. Congress Party gave him an opportunity to contest Rajasthan State assembly elections 2018, where he successfully managed a win by margin of 12947 votes against 3 times MLA [[Thakur Manohar Singh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/election-result-2018/rajasthan-election-result-2018/nagaur/ladnun/mukesh-bhakar/|title=Ladnun Congress Candidate Mukesh Bhakar, Mukesh Bhakar vs Manohar Singh, \u0932\u093e\u0921\u0928\u0942\u0902 \u0938\u0940\u091f \u0938\u0947 \u0915\u093e\u0902\u0917\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0938 \u0909\u092e\u094d\u092e\u0940\u0926\u0935\u093e\u0930 \u092e\u0941\u0915\u0947\u0936 \u092d\u0915\u0930|website=Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/elections/rajasthan-election/article/ladnun-assembly-constituency-election-2018-rajasthan-assembly-polls-rajasthan-vasundhara-raje-bharatiya-janata-party-bjp-congress-sachin-pilot-manohar/320646|title=Ladnun Assembly Election Results 2018: Congress' Mukesh Bhakar won by 12,947 votes against BJP's sitting MLA|website=www.timesnownews.com}}</ref>. He won election for State President, [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]] over nearest candidate [[Amardin]] by 9872 votes.<ref>https://www.jagran.com/rajasthan/jaipur-congress-mla-mukesh-bhakar-appointed-as-rajasthan-pradesh-youth-congress-state-president-organization-elections-20172785.html</ref>\n\n== Positions held ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Position\n|-\n| 2009 - 10 || Unit President, National Students Union of India, University of Rajasthan\n|-\n| 2013 - 15 ||State President, National Students Union of India, NSUI Rajasthan\n|-\n| 2015 - 18 || National Secretary, National Students Union of India\n|-\n| 2018 \u2013 20  || State Vice President, Rajasthan Youth Congress\n|-\n| 2017 \u2013 cont. || PCC Member, Rajasthan Pradesh Congress Committee\n|-\n| 2017 \u2013 cont. || Member, All India Congress Committee\n|-\n| 2018 \u2013 cont. ||Member of Legislative Assembly (MLA) from Ladnun, Rajasthan State Assembly\n|-\n| 2019 \u2013 cont.  || Member of Committee on Petitions, Rajasthan State Assembly\n|-\n| 2020 \u2013 cont.  || State President, Rajasthan Youth Congress\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{twitter.com|mukeshbhakar_}}\n\n{{Indian National Congress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhakar, Mukesh}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani people]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani politicians]]\n[[Category:Rajasthan MLAs 2018\u2013]]\n[[Category:People from Nagaur district]]\n", "name_user": "Mukesh Bhakar 0013", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mukesh_Bhakar"}
